commit_message:
Add missing hyphen to swift install section

As reported by Alex Roig, the section of the swift install
guide that added the keystone endpoint was missing a hyphen
in the command. This patch adds it.

Change-Id: I8a7bfa43e5dc53d4a9e70e52fa58673e08e584c6
Closes-Bug: 1384174

[{'created': '2014-10-13 15:21:25.000000000', 'message': "VMware: Fix initialization of datastore selector

The WSDL URL of storage policy service is determined and a session is
created using it in do_setup(). This session is later used to initialize
the datastore selector property (ds_sel), which uses the session for all
storage policy related API calls.

After commit a8fa3ceb1e72bac2ab67f569a2ca009f995f59fd (Integrate
OSprofiler and Cinder), the properties defined in vmdk module are called
before do_setup(). As a result, the ds_sel (datastore selector) property
is initialized with a session instance containing a 'None' PBM (storage
policy service) WSDL URL. This results in failures of all storage policy
related APIs invoked using datastore selector. This patch fixes the
problem by re-initializing the property in do_setup().

Change-Id: Ibdf8b23f9e215000cf9053b81d374066fabd6851
Closes-Bug: #1380675

commit_message:
VMware: Fix initialization of datastore selector

The WSDL URL of storage policy service is determined and a session is
created using it in do_setup(). This session is later used to initialize
the datastore selector property (ds_sel), which uses the session for all
storage policy related API calls.

After commit a8fa3ceb1e72bac2ab67f569a2ca009f995f59fd (Integrate
OSprofiler and Cinder), the properties defined in vmdk module are called
before do_setup(). As a result, the ds_sel (datastore selector) property
is initialized with a session instance containing a 'None' PBM (storage
policy service) WSDL URL. This results in failures of all storage policy
related APIs invoked using datastore selector. This patch fixes the
problem by re-initializing the property in do_setup().

Change-Id: Ibdf8b23f9e215000cf9053b81d374066fabd6851
Closes-Bug: #1380675

commit_message:
workarounds for nova networking

this patch creates a dummy interface ("flat0") and uses that for
flat_interface.  This prevents nova from breaking container networking
when it adds the container eth0 to the nova bridge (br100).

Change-Id: I93c696a8476228d6bbca678748170c2a11d5af11

commit_message:
Increase settings for dnsmasq and sysctl

* Make a new variable dhcp_lease_max. It increases the number of
  available leases from 1000 to 1800. It allows to provision nodes on
  scale, when Debian Installer or Anaconda looses IP in the middle of
  install.
* Make a new variable lease_time. It increases the default lease size
  to 120m, up from the default 60m.
* Add cache-size to dnsmasq template. dnsmasq will keep more entries in
  case.
* Increased neighbour table on master node to keep more ARP requests
  that come in parallel once deployment is started. This change also
  removes unneed broadcast traffic. New values are:
  net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh1 = 256
  net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh2 = 1024
  net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh3 = 2048
* Fix linting

commit_message:
Address how to contribute to existing modules

W/o this patch, it is unclear how to contribute
to existing fuel library modules. In order to fix this,
fuel dev docs should be updated as appropriate.

Closes-bug: #1382432

Change-Id: I3d152c9b09297f3ae01e54f364723ef904f9f7c5
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Cisco N1kv: Fix update network profile for add tenants

This patch makes sure that while updating network profile to add new
tenants, it does not delete the older profile bindings and maintains
them, while adds only the new tenant ids to the bindings.

Change-Id: I862eb1c400e022334a2f6a4078425448bb144843
Closes-bug: #1379609

commit_message:
Porting SecurityGroup related controller into v2.1

This patch port SecurityGroup, ServerSecurityGroup and SecurityGroupAction
controller into v2.1 security_groups extension.

This patch just move the v2 code into v2.1 and share the unittest. The other
v2.1 related fix and improvement will be addressed by subsequent patchset.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I93951ce677b74ebed7db1b2fff1f788344806dba

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-06-13 00:05:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Thanks for doing this after we've talked about it for so long...

Since stack.sh often runs multiple times per system boot (on non-CI systems anyway) this should probably also check to see if 35357 is already reserved and do nothing if so.  Duplicates are probably mostly harmless but it should be clean.

Also, you can call reserve_keystone_port() from init_keystone() and not need to add it to stack.sh as it is a Keystone-only thing."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-06-13 00:12:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I am adding it as a keystone only thing in stack.sh so we do it before we have extra stuff "running" on the system.  if this _really_ needs to go in keystone init, i think we're not eliminating the problem, because by the time we hit keystone init something could be using that port. The earlier in the process we reserve the port, the less likely it will be in use when keystone tries and starts.

Unfortunately when it comes to detecting if it's already there the kernel likes to emit "ranges".

You could have ports 30000-39999,42675 as the return value of the reserved ports (for example). If you re-reserve it, the kernel will just smush down the multiple reservations into a range (if possible) or ignore it. It doesn't hurt to reserve it over and over.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-06-13 00:14:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I also expect this code to go away once we have a better solution for gate (i really dislike this solution, but it's what we have)."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-06-13 00:32:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-06-13 01:45:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

keystone_init() runs before any OpenStack stuff is started and Keystone is the first project started.  If running it earlier than that is needed let's consider moving it to tools/fixup_stuff.sh.  Conceptually it fits well there as the holding-tank for ugly hacks that need to go away eventually.

Good to know about the multiple calls, I was worried that it would just keep appending additional ports.  I missed getting KEYSTONE_AUTH_PORT_INT too."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-06-13 03:15:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'll get it in the fixup scripts, this really is more along those lines (I dislike it being here at all, but what can we do?). I don't think it's OpenStack stuff starting that is causing the issue, i think it's something else running that is consuming an ephemeral port that just happens to be keystone's. 

I'll get the variables used for the port instead of the number(s) in the next patch.

Thanks for the comments!"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-13 04:09:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Reserve Keystone ports from the ephemeral range

Reserve Keystone ports from the ephemeral range as early as reasonably
possible in the fixup_stuff.sh process to reduce the likelihood that the
port will be in use. This does not completely resolve the issue
where Keystone's IANA assigned port falls into Linux's ephemeral
range, but this should reduce the occurrences. The default ports
are 35357 and 35358.

Change-Id: I8cfb53d8f90c1ff1fb1083c59fefabca3d14323b
Partial-Bug: #1253482

commit_message:
Add periodic Juno jobs

New integrated project in Juno is Sahara

Add periodic tempest jobs even when they run as compat jobs
on each tempest master check for stable-maint visiblity

Change-Id: Ieb9486134e54805941049159f0756103c68f4b36

commit_message:
Add juno compat jobs to the tempest check pipeline

Now that Juno has been released we need to run every tempest commit
against juno to verify that a commit to tempest master doesn't break
running against the new stable branch. This commit adds these jobs.
However, until all the machinery is in place for grenade we can't run
it against stable/juno, so those jobs are missing.

Change-Id: I4835c321bb22eaadc0d9fe282a0004ba00019ffa

commit_message:
The modified puppet codeing style

Add the Rakefile file:
 * add dependency rubygems
 * disable 80 char line limit
 * disable class parameter defaults
The remaining work is in the correction puppet code specifications

Change-Id: I0e6f9bffd717ffe627f299852893573947b3f98a
Closes-Bug: #1338559

commit_message:
Halt test_cinder_volume_create_backup_restore on error

test_cinder_volume_create_backup_restore fails frequently due to issues
outside heat. Instead of failing, this change halts the test when the
error condition is triggered. This will allow some of the test to run
while making the check job voting.

Once logging is configured in heat_integrationtests an elastic-recheck
search can monitor for the frequency of this error to aid
nova/cinder/swift developers to fix it.

Change-Id: I09722ad725a8d23fb2028c17b0dd9fcab3957649
Related-Bug: #1382300

This feature aims to improve the libvirt driver so
that it can use large pages for backing the guest
RAM allocation. This will improve the performance of

commit_message:
Virt driver large page allocation for guest RAM

This feature aims to improve the libvirt driver so
that it can use large pages for backing the guest
RAM allocation. This will improve the performance of
guest workloads by increasing TLB cache efficiency.
It will ensure that the guest has 100% dedicated RAM
that will never be swapped out.

Previously approved: juno
Change-Id: Ie3e3337241a514723d2c85b2186ee15ee8d57fff

commit_message:
Use oslo_debug_helper and remove our own version

With the latest version of oslotest, we can now take advantage
of a common oslo_debug_helper script.
We can now remove our own homebrewed version, minor changes to
tox.ini were needed.

Change-Id: Ibd4317e8b1a9e38c9f4ef839352b74f14e9ddcfa

What's the point of having this copied over rather than having the project fixing their config right now?"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:03:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> What's the point of having this copied over rather than having the project fixing their config right now?

We don't break all operators on upgrade?

I'm failing to find the docs for it atm, but previously I've been pointed at docs which say that all config options should be deprecated for at least one cycle, and that on upgrade, a service should still work with the previous release's config (albeit with warnings).  That, AIUI is the point of grenade testing, isn't it?

So to clarify, I think we *should* fix all the project configs right now, the problem is when operators upgrade and forget to update their paste.ini files, and experience breakage of all their services with no warning.

Perhaps paste ini files are special, but my experience of introducing backwards incompatible changes to *.conf files is that it is not allowed.

Obviously, if it is allowed, it makes life easier for everyone, but AFAIK, it's not, ref my ML thread on this topic, perhaps you can weigh in there?"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:06:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

FWIW, this is a good example of why I dislike the fact that we encourage deployers to change paste config files.

ML discussion: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-October/048764.html'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:24:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Doug: FWIW I do agree, and I know that some distributors have taken steps to discourage folks from editing them (e.g moving from the default /etc/ location).

So if someone can point to evidence that it's OK to just flip the default (e.g that the policy for .ini files is more relaxed than for .conf files), I'll happily abandon this :)

It's just a shame we didn't get that deprecation warning sync'd before Juno shipped really :("}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:27:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:33:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Add middleware.request_id shim for Kilo

A deprecation warning was added to oslo-incubator for Juno, but
unfortunately not to any of the projects actually using it.

Since this module is referenced in the api paste config, removing
the module from the projec trees without deprecation warning
constitutes an operator-visible backwards incompatible change,
which AIUI is not allowed.

This mitigates the lack of deprecation period by adding a shim for
Kilo, which projects can sync before switching their paste defaults
to point to oslo.middlware, we can then remove the shim in L.

Change-Id: I11caf1119c44712ed1d15810703e38c50e009709
Related-Bug: #1380629

commit_message:
Wrap a CONF object and intercept authtoken options

To use the keystoneclient session stuff we need to operate on CONF
objects. However we have paste options that are suppose to override
those coming from CONF.

Create a horrible little object that acts like a CONF object but checks
to see if values were passed via paste params before querying the CONF.

commit_message:
Fuel agent tiny fixups

1) Fix issue with /etc/mtab for fuel-agent

Sometimes /etc/mtab inside of chrooted image during provisioning stage
appears as symlink to /proc/self/mounts. It can't be rewritten in such
case. So its removing really helps.

2) Fix grub_utils

`chroot` parameter was missed few times. Should work now

3) Fix improper stdout handling in manager.py when `blkid` was called

Output should be stripped as it contains new-line symbol (\n) on end
Closes-Bug: #1383371

Change-Id: I756b85b104fc06a065bc2f297b30f0b738aea3f4

commit_message:
Disallow Resize Volume If Status Is Shutdown

if the status of a database instance is 'shutdown', a resize-volume
operation should not be allowed.

Change-Id: I3eda2915a0167b35a19831b96d9cbcfe8075bdf7
Closes-Bug: #1382914

svc-map requires PyYAML

svc-map requires PyYAML, so install it. It's not always installed on all base
images.

x-openstack-request-id is the common header name for request ID going
forward. Nova, cinder, and neutron return this header. Using the
falcon before/after hook  is a convenient way to ensure this header is in
the response. We will also be using the hook to generate the
request ID.

The ID will be generated by the before hook and is inserted into the
request environment and is available for use in the handling of the request.

attach the x-openstack-request-id header, using the value of the
generated request ID.

commit_message:
Add x-openstack-request-id to zaqar responses

x-openstack-request-id is the common header name for request ID going
forward. Nova, cinder, and neutron return this header. Using the
falcon before/after hook  is a convenient way to ensure this header is in
the response. We will also be using the hook to generate the
request ID.

The ID will be generated by the before hook and is inserted into the
request environment and is available for use in the handling of the request.

On the response end, the falcon after hook is used, this time to
attach the x-openstack-request-id header, using the value of the
generated request ID.

DocImpact: responses of the API will include x-openstack-request-id

Change-Id: I329afb4213e54072df0191232f86ed40ba58a357
Implements: blueprint cross-service-request-id

commit_message:
do not auth if insufficient args are present

Currently, we try to auth with keystone before argument checking,
so, when insufficient args are present however we will still auth
with keystone. This is wasteful.

Change-Id: I7663e3e678e86e6a31d874f3dece282ddb01158d
Closes-Bug: #1355838

Calling this good on interpretation and implementation, though I also initially thought comma placement looked wonky (but then so many things in the English language look 'off' even when they're right...)

I also read it as:
os-cloud-config grew out of the need to call common cloud bring-up tasks from different code bases.

Which expands to the way James has it:
os-cloud-config grew out of the need to call common cloud bring-up tasks, such as <example bring-up tasks>, from different code bases."}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-10-13 20:47:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't know who wrote the original, but I assume that they were trying to avoid use of the Oxford Comma (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serial_comma)

As the wikipedia page says, sometimes the best way to avoid ambiguity is to rework the sentence.

I think the core of the problem here is a nesting issue: we have a comma-separated list of tasks, separated from the surrounding context by commas. It's not clear which commas are internal to the list and which indicate the start/end of the list. My first attempt to fix this removed the internal comma, but it seems that's still not hugely clear

Perhaps we could avoid ambiguity by switching to parentheses or hyphens:

os-cloud-config grew out of the need to call common cloud bring-up tasks (such as initializing Keystone, or configuring Neutron) from different code bases.

os-cloud-config grew out of the need to call common cloud bring-up tasks - such as initializing Keystone, or configuring Neutron - from different code bases.

I think either of those forms is clearer; I think I prefer the second, so I'll push that up now."}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-10-13 21:13:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-13 21:24:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-10-12 20:19:38.000000000', 'message': 'Tweak commas for clarity

As written (lacking the Oxford Comma), the readme suggests to me that we
had two common bring-up tasks:

* initializing keystone
* configuring Neutron from different code bases

I believe that the actual case is that this is intending to describe two
common bring-up tasks:

* initializing keystone
* configuring Neutron

each of which may be called from different code-bases.

I think that my proposed change makes this clearer.

Change-Id: I7c6e4b219468f92e31fc51b3d1aac8bafd9640d8
'}, {'created': '2014-10-13 21:13:56.000000000', 'message': "Nitpicky grammar tweaks for readme

* Tweak commas for clarity

  As written (lacking the Oxford Comma), the readme suggests to me that we
  had two common bring-up tasks:

  * initializing keystone
  * configuring Neutron from different code bases

  I believe that the actual case is that this is intending to describe two
  common bring-up tasks:

  * initializing keystone
  * configuring Neutron

  each of which may be called from different code-bases.

  I think that my proposed change (using hyphens to delimit the list and
  a comma internally) makes this clearer.

* Reword the final line for consistency

  The final of this paragraph seems to have been left in an inconsistent
  state by a partial edit; I've tweaked some of the prepositions and
  tenses to make it more internally consistent

commit_message:
Changed fuel-cli options name

* changed names of --os-username and --os-password
* changed errors message and tests
* added possibilities of using change-password instead
  --change-password

DocImpact
Change-Id: If20e1a5754345b0d356be8982eb4989bae9ed21b
Closes-Bug: #1382474

If we fix the `neutron agent-list` check and pass `-e $TRIPLEO_ROOT/tripleo-heat-templates/overcloud-resource-registry.yaml` to Heat only if that file exists in t-h-t, that's not going to break the existing workflow and once merged will let us run CI on this change.

This provides three templates: overcloud.yaml, compute.yaml and
controller.yaml. These can be used in combination with
overcloud-resource-registry.yaml to deploy the overcloud on their own --
without having to do any pre-processing (via merge.py).

There's a handful of modifications necessary to use these with devtest:

1. Add the resource registry environment (in addition to the existing
`-e` option) to the Heat call in devtest_overcloud.sh (line 374):

    heat $HEAT_OP -e $TRIPLEO_ROOT/overcloud-env.json \
        -e "$TRIPLEO_ROOT/tripleo-heat-templates/overcloud-resource-registry.yaml" \
        -t 360 \
        -f $TRIPLEO_ROOT/tripleo-heat-templates/overcloud.yaml \
        -P "ExtraConfig=${OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG}" \
        $STACKNAME

2. Removing `$STACKNAME` from the `neutron agent-list` check in
devtest_overcloud.sh (line 511):

-wait_for 30 10 neutron agent-list -f csv -c alive -c agent_type -c host \| grep "\":-).*Open vSwitch agent.*$STACKNAME-novacompute\"" #nodocs
+wait_for 30 10 neutron agent-list -f csv -c alive -c agent_type -c host \| grep "\":-).*Open vSwitch agent.*-novacompute\"" #nodocs

(this is because the resources created by Heat are now in a different
format and no longer contain the full name of the stack)

The `make overcloud.yaml` call can stay (we've turn the overcloud
target in Makefile to no-op and removed it from .gitignore) and the
inputs and outputs of the template remain the same.

This means that the existing environment should continue to work.
Scaling is now being controlled by the `ControllerCount` and
`ComputeCount` template parameters, though.

NOTE: the changes here depend on a fairly recent Heat build (commit
e5f285f6cb from ~7th September, 2014). In other words, this requires
Juno Heat.

commit_message:
Compute and controller templates without merge.py

This provides three templates: overcloud-without-mergepy.yaml,
compute.yaml and controller.yaml. These can be used in combination with
overcloud-resource-registry.yaml to deploy the overcloud on their own --
without having to do any pre-processing (via merge.py).

To test these you have to add the resource registry environment (in
addition to the existing `-e` option) and use the new overcloud template
in the Heat call in devtest_overcloud.sh (line 374):

    heat $HEAT_OP -e $TRIPLEO_ROOT/overcloud-env.json \
        -e "$TRIPLEO_ROOT/tripleo-heat-templates/overcloud-resource-registry.yaml" \
        -t 360 \
        -f $TRIPLEO_ROOT/tripleo-heat-templates/overcloud-without-mergepy.yaml \
        -P "ExtraConfig=${OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG}" \
        $STACKNAME

The existing overcloud Heat environment
($TRIPLE_ROOT/overcloud-env.json) should keep on working.  Scaling is
now being controlled by the `ControllerCount` and `ComputeCount`
template parameters, though.

NOTE: the changes here depend on a fairly recent Heat build (commit
e5f285f6cb from ~7th September, 2014). In other words, this requires
Juno Heat.

Also, passing more than one environment file to Heat requires
python-heatclient version 0.2.11.

Change-Id: I687a00c7dc164ba044f9f2dfca96a02401427855

commit_message:
Prevent stable branches to use glancelcient 0.14.0

This version contains a bug introduced that prevents using that specific
version of the client with older openstack deployments. The fix is:
I8c871f11b909337bd7df19b77e606772dbc634b2 and was released in 0.14.1

Change-Id: I46b01da2f2fee805281513434099e4c5ebbee8f9

commit_message:
Fix race condition on processing DVR floating IPs

Fip namespace and agent gateway port can be shared by multiple dvr routers.
This change uses a set as the control variable for these shared resources
and ensures that Test and Set operation on the control variable are
performed atomically so that race conditions do not occur among
multiple threads processing floating IPs.
Limitation: The scope of this change is limited to addressing the race
condition described in the bug report. It may not address other issues
such as pre-existing issue with handling of DVR floatingips on agent
restart.

closes-bug: #1381238

Change-Id: I6dc2b7bad6e8ddbaa86c1f7a1e2028aeacc3afef

commit_message:
Improve error log for expired image location url

If image is not present at the specified location while creating instance
from image, then HTTPInternalServerError 500 response along with stack trace
is logged on nova compute which does not help user to understand the exact
cause of failure.

Return HTTPNotFound error to the nova compute in case of image url got
expired or image is not present at the given location to give clear
indication of the cause of failure to user.

Closes-Bug: #1198566
Change-Id: I9acd9112aeae8d3b3c0c3921f306e716e5808c2e

commit_message:
Add tests for nova floating IP Heat resources

Tests were added to ensure that a FloatingIP is successfully
created and associated with a nova server when the following
resource-types are used in a Heat template:
* OS::Nova::FloatingIP
* OS::Nova::FloatingIPAssociation

Change-Id: I1c7581683b273f402eeeb96f4ffc1c9933c9bddb
Closes-Bug: #1295950

commit_message:
Set default branches of Sahara and Zaqar to stable/juno

The default branches of Sahara and Zaqar are still set to master
and they cannot be run due to global-requirements conflict.

Change-Id: I2d05118537b68bef0e3c6686b7263e1dc445d39e

Thanks to you both for the quick feedback.

@Randall: Yeah I thought about that asymmetry and decided the least-bad solution was to apply the force_remove blacklist unconditionally, so if you do an update after removing via force_remove, we just add more resources with a higher index (as demonstrated by the test).

There is still some weirdness in that if you later update and remove force_remove then we may then remove those higher index additions and replace them with the indexes no longer blacklisted.

I'm thinking what is here's probably fine for a first iteration, and a possible future enhancement could be to allow resource uuid's in the force_remove list, such that we lookup which index and only blacklist it for the duration of the update (e.g until the resource with the matching uuid has been deleted from the nested stack).  There's quite a bit more complexity associated with all of that though, so if Clint is confident this solves the TripleO use-case, I'd rather keep it simple for now :)"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-14 19:08:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-14 20:17:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Drawing from [1] lets assume there are 2 other available policies: oldest_server and newest_server.

In patch set 2 [2] of that spec I made the following 2 suggestions (adapted to this review):

1) specify the remove hint in the policy list
eg: 
  remove_policies:
  - 0
  - 2
  - newest_resource

2) Instead of a list of strings, allow a list of dicts so that arguments can be specified for each policy (AWS::AutoScaling::AutoScalingGroup would be string-list only)
eg:
  remove_policies:
  - remove_hint: [0, 2]
  - newest_resource: []

I think I would prefer 2) to give policies the ability to consume arguments, and if the schema can't enforce this structure then we can always enforce in the validate method.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110379/4/specs/scale-down-plug-point.rst

A few things.

On reviewing the proposed code more carefully, I see that it breaks the equation name = index (as in "ordinal position in current list of existing members").  And the proposed policy statement is in terms of names rather than indices, so the identifiers are not so ephemeral as I thought.  That said, there remains a bit of a problem: because names are re-used in OS::Heat::ResourceGroup, there is a potential for confusion between concurrent clients.  An interface is for everybody, not just TripleO.

OTOH, using resource IDs has another problem: https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1381136 .  So I am not sure there is a good solution now.  Maybe fix that bug first?  OTOH, I see that Stack::resource_by_refid works around that bug (although quite inefficiently!  I do not think Clint be happy if TripleO has to use that.)

My point about operations vs object properties is to wonder whether a better solution is to have an operation in the Heat API for annihilating a scaling group member.  It feels to me like what TripleO seems to want here is more of an operation than a new model.  When I imagine writing a client that does a stack update on a parent stack (passing a new template for the whole parent stack) when it wants to remove certain members from a scaling group, it feels pretty fiddly to me.

That said, you can indeed give sensible model semantics to a property listing members to exclude.  It seems to me that there is no problem with CREATE on a template that has a list of excluded members for a scaling group resource --- it just forbids the creation of members that would be identified by certain identifiers.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-17 09:27:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

@Mike:

> I see that it breaks the equation name = index (as in "ordinal position in current list of existing members"). 

I don't think we've ever made any claims of equivalence here, the name==index thing is an implementation detail.  Perhaps the names should be randomly generated UUID's instead?

> That said, there remains a bit of a problem: because names are re-used in OS::Heat::ResourceGroup, there is a potential for confusion between concurrent clients. 

Yeah, this is true, and I'm pondering solutions to it (it's related to the problem I have in the next patch in this series).

Seems to me we have two options:

1. Switch to random names so we never reuse a name and there is no name==index equivalence anymore (stuff like "oldest" would need to be derived by other means, e.g the resource DB timestamps)

2. Keep the current scheme, but don't reuse excluded names and just count up (again this breaks the name==index equivalence you mention, but I'm not sure if this is really a problem, let me know your use-case if you think it is.)

> An interface is for everybody, not just TripleO.

Uh, okay?!  TripleO is the use-case justifying this feature, the interface is intended to be for everybody, if you don't like it, propose a better one - incase you hadn't noticed I'm working very hard to satisfy everyone's (specific) requests re this interface.

> OTOH, using resource IDs has another problem: https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1381136 . 

Okay, so we either need to fix that bug, or add logic which will match either resource RefId or resource.id.

> resource_by_refid works around that bug (although quite inefficiently! I do not think Clint be happy if TripleO has to use that.)

I'm not going to speculate about what might make Clint happy, but personally I see one stack traversal via resource_by_refid as an acceptable cost for what is most likely going to be an infrequently used interface - happy to work on optimising this later if you have better, more efficient suggestions :)

> ... an operation in the Heat API for annihilating a scaling group member.

Maybe, I know you've been advocating that recently, and I don't see anything I'm doing here as preventing that as a possibly future addition.

FWIW, I see that solution as fraught with additional complexity, because it's a nested-stack update from the bottom-up (a back-door stack update if you will).

So you have the problem of how to propagate the change if you allow a user to delete a resource via a non-update interface, this implies the template for the stack will change (outside control of the user who may have templates stored in revision control etc), and also that we have to somehow "push" the update up the tree to all parent stacks, all of which may modify the declarative model in a way that's completely opaque to the user.

Hence my preference, right now, to use what we have, which is our primary user interface of templates.

In future, it may be that you could allow out-of band deletion of the bad resource-group member, followed by recovery via continuous convergence, but tbh I just don't want to project this solution to some future model which we haven't even started yet.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-17 09:57:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

(1 comment)

Attempt to consolidate Steve, Angus, Mike, Thomas and Randall's requests re interface naming and what it will accept added inline (who said this wasn't for everybody! ;)"}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-10-17 10:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

+1 on that proposal'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-17 17:30:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I did not mean to suggest that I the equation name=index is good; I mention the breaking of it to explain why I am happier with the use of numeric names than I was yesterday.

Of your two options for member name generation, the second is technically superior.  If Clint wants a million names, avoiding the birthday problem requires longer names than we currently use.

If the list of excluded names is part of the properties of the group, it will probably have to be handled anytime anything is done with the group.  I am OK with a plan to use refid instead of resource ID and plan to make refid lookup as efficient as needed.

It looks to me like we are agreeing there are two distinct concepts, even though they often overlap: refid and resource ID.  Maybe each should have its own "get" intrinsic function in Heat?

Autoscaling is already the sort of back-door nested stack update you fear.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-17 17:32:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

BTW, there is also a semantic difference: must remove vs remove when needed.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-19 05:09:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Thanks, Steven.  I see you put in the list structure so that users can order policies.  However, as I noted in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110379/ , I am not so hot on the unification --- due to the semantic difference.  If we do not unify, we do not need list structure here.

As noted in that other review, I am going to write up two blueprints that each enables a better way to do health maintenance.  One uses this idea of a property listing members to remove.  It involves adding to the Heat API an operation for applying deltas to the template of a stack; it is stack-update but given deltas instead of a new stack.  The other goes more directly through a Heat API operation for removing members from a stack, allowing interception by a resource (in a parent stack, of course) if that resource is backed by the stack from which members are being removed.  The interception is so the resource (e.g., a scaling group) can transform the operation to maintain the resource's integrity (e.g., by also adding some group members).

If you have another idea about how health maintenance could be done today or soon, I would be interested in seeing the outline."}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-19 06:33:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

OK, see https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/healthy-asg-via-stack-update-by-deltas and https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/asg-health-via-remove-members .  I prefer the latter because it is more direct, and involves only one stack update per member removal.  OTOH, the former does the stack update on the parent of the scaling group rather than its backing stack and so may be less buggy.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-19 08:16:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Mike: Thanks for the feedback, a lot to digest there, but I get the impression we're getting slowly closer to a solution we can all live with.

I took a quick look at your BP's (both will need specs IMO), and re OS::Heat::StackMembersRemover, "MembersRemover" is not a resource, it's an action on some other resource, which is back to the whole problem of HARestarter all over again IMO.

I do have an idea of how we can better do health maintenance within our existing resource structure, but really I need a bit more time to hack on a PoC before documenting it in a spec.  Here's a very quick brain-dump of where I'm headed:

1. Make OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup a SignalResponder, so you can send a signal (containing data including hints of what to remove on scale-down) to the ASG which triggers scale up/down.  This will replace the non-standard "adjust" interface we currently have, which will be problematic when we get into convergence implementation.

2. Modify ScalingPolicy so it sends a signal to the ASG instead of calling the adjust method.

2. Follow the basic strategy you outline to monitor the health and get the ceilometer alarm to send a signal to the ASG directly.  This is supplementary to any alarms which send signals to a policy resource.

Really, this is just a different approach to the API call triggering resource removal you wanted, but IMO it fits better with our existing interfaces and resource structure.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-19 08:51:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

> Maybe each should have its own "get" intrinsic function in Heat?

IMHO definitely not - The resource ID's are always available via the API, and if template authors need to distinguish between refid and resource_id, we are doing something wrong.

(Almost) all native resources should return resource ID via get_resource, AWS resources (almost) always return an ARN, for compatibility with CFN.  

The template author should, in almost all cases, not care, you're just specifying one resource refers to another, and we should handle any refid/resource ID misalignment transparently inside our resources, if we don't it's probably a bug.

In the rare cases where the template author just absolutely has to get the resource ID, adding a common attribute would be better IMO than an intrinsic function.  Other than AWS resources and the TemplateResource bug you raised (which we do need to fix), I'm not aware of any situations where this is actually needed though.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-19 14:52:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Ceilometer gives the client no control over the HTTP headers and request body used in an alarm action; the client controls only the URL.  I asked a colleague about the prospects of changing that soon, and the answer was not encouraging.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-19 16:10:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Steven Hardy: regarding the idea that StackMembersRemover takes us "back to the whole problem of HARestarter all over again", I do not see it that way.  But maybe you have a different idea about what the whole problem of HARestarter is.  I am still trying to understand what people consider to be that problem.  I got one idea on Wednesday from Zane.  See http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23heat/%23heat.2014-10-15.log and look from 2014-10-15T14:11:51 through 2014-10-15T14:23:56.  The problems I see identified there are two: (1) it is bad for a resource to operate on a sibling, even though it is OK for a client to operate on a resource that happens to be a sibling of a resource that caused that client to act, and (2) HARestarter does not do a regular stack update.  The proposed OS::Heat::StackMembersRemover avoids both of those problems.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-20 07:21:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

@Mike:

> Ceilometer gives the client no control over the HTTP headers and request body

Yeah, I'm aware of that, so we'll need a somewhat suboptimal step of an additional query to ceilometer to introspect data associated with the alarm (the request body does contain the alarm ID)

I'm not getting yet into another debate re HARestarter here as we're already very OT from the code review, but suffice to say one of the issues is that every time we've used a resource as a place to poke non-api-backed code, we've run into trouble (because, invariably, you introduce unwanted coupling between "real" resources which are backed by real APIs).'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-20 14:46:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

> With the current schema, the language for changes used in the anticipated stack PATCH operation will have to be relatively sophisticated if it is going to be able to express "add Foo to the list of members to remove".

Mike, you can always add multiple remove_list entries, or you can completely replace the remove_list with a new remove_list since the resource maintains its own blacklist. Wouldn't that make any naively implemented PATCH operation just work?'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-22 04:18:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I think other things are easier if we avoid re-using names, but it takes a bit of care to avoid re-using names.  In addition to the things already merged, I am also thinking ahead to a future in which we replace randomly generated names with deterministically (e.g., by hashing) generated names so that the results of a preview are consistent with a following create.  I am also interested in seeing how well we can do without a total ban on name re-use.

Ah, right, the permanence of the blacklist removes some of the concerns about concurrency --- as long as one stack UPDATE has to finish before another stack UPDATE starts to run.

My remark about the change language was motivated by a different concern.  I was thinking about what happens in a future when additional removal policy types are available.  But I think there is an issue even now when only the one current policy type is available --- if we can not rely on all the clients to maintain a simplifying discipline.  In short, the issue is how expressive a language do you need to identify the list that you want to add a name to or remove a name from.

Here is a concrete illustration.  The schema in patch set 1 allowed a template snippet like this:

  properties:
    force_remove: [foo, bar]

Identifying the list that gets an addition or removal is simple, it is just a path of names; this might be written as "properties/force_remove".

The schema of patch set 10 allows a template snippet like this:

  properties:
    removal_policies:
    - resource_list: [foo]
    - resource_list: [bar, baz]

In this case we have two levels of list structure, and the outer (higher) level is the concern.  How to identify which member of the outer list to operate on?  The first idea is by index.  Let us consider a deletion scenario.  Client A looks at the template and sees that it wants to navigate to properties/removal_policies/1/resource_list and remove bar and baz from the inner list there.  Concurrently client B decides it wants to completely delete properties/removal_policies/0 from the outer list --- which will shift the outer element at index 1 down to index 0.  If client B's operation is done first then client A's operation will fail to have the desired effect.

You could try instead to identify the desired outer list member by content.  But a concurrent client could slip in a modification of content.'}]

commit_message:
ResourceGroup add remove_policies property

To cater for the requirement of TripleO (and others) to specify a
victim for removal from a Resource group ("eliding" in merge.py speak)
add a new property, which enables specific indexes to be passed on
update, which will force removal of those specific resources.

In future it may be that we add additional ways to specify the removal
policy, so this interface is a list of policies, with each policy being
a map taking an optional list of arguments.

'resource_list' policy added now, which takes one of the following:

1. Resource name (as specified in the nested stack, obtainable e.g via
heat resource-list --nested-depth $n <parent stack>, or by doing
resource-list directly using the nested stack ID obtainable via
physical_resource_id of the ResourceGroup resource.

2. The nested resource refid - this is typically (but not always,
particularly for AWS resources) the resource physical_resource_id,
and is obtainable via either get_resource or the "refs" attribute
of the ResourceGroup.

Note that once removed, the resource name is never reused, so the
%index%, where used, will always increment on replacement.

Change-Id: Icbc76b54bae3eb39efdaa704b036b1bbb94db206
blueprint: resourcegroup-force-remove

commit_message:
Add maintenance_reason when setting maintenance mode

Sets the reason for maintenance when the power status loop
automatically puts a node into maintenance mode.

Implements: blueprint maintenance-reason

Change-Id: If6c54d0eeb8b874fc9c59ef4f57fa812d78531b0

subject: Add API endpoint to set/unset the node maintenance mode

commit_message:
Add API endpoint to set/unset the node maintenance mode

This patch is adding an API endpoint to user set/unset the maintenance
mode of a node, since now we have an extra db field where operators can
specify the reason why the node was put in maintenance mode we should
make sure we clean this field as well once the node is removed from
maintenance mode, operations that requires extra actions as a consequence
of updating a attribute from a resource should have a separated endpoint
for it. Right now the endpoint is only updating the DB, but in the future
setting a node to maintenance mode should do more things like signalizing
Nova that the node is now in maintenance mode so that instances do not
gets scheduled onto it.

Implements: blueprint maintenance-reason
Change-Id: I1d4f609d248535064b9e3daeb67481d5b921aa7c

commit_message:
Make HARestarter do a proper lookup of the RefID

HARestarter is a primitive prototype that is barely maintained.  Its
implementation still dates to the era when the resource name, physical
resource ID and RefId were regularly used interchangably.

This change substitutes Stack.resource_by_refid() for the previous
(incorrect) home-grown hack, so that at least the giant red flags will be
easy to grep for.

Change-Id: I9d81dfcd5d34282c8bd83bbd98350e75c1ec0eb2
Closes-Bug: #1381136

commit_message:
Updated run_tests.sh to run tests in debug mode

Start directory was not configured property in run_tests.sh which raises
error while running entire test suit using debug mode.

Updated "testrargs" value from "discover ./glance/tests" to
"discover ./tests" as default starting point to run all tests
if specific test is not provided.

Closes-Bug: 1383117
Change-Id: Ie26d6ec02c92e9ac03dd7c35d313ea377715322f

commit_message:
Remove redundant initialization and check from DVR RPC mixin

The initialization, as well as the recurrent checks on whether the agent
is able to handle DVR requests, are not necessary; this is because the
dvr_agent is going to be set at the time the L2 agent starts receiving
RPC messages.

Change-Id: I9caad965d0ff507e2ed93d6432997ad86139ac04

commit_message:
Use correct name of oslo debugger script

As of oslotest 1.2.0 the oslo debugger script dropped the .sh
extension. This patch corrects the use the script name in tox.ini

Change-Id: I0b814f5136e2858ac53ba45db523790d220a6b88

commit_message:
add v3 API documentation

These are the restructuredtext documents produced as a result of the
following changes (originally proposed to openstack/identity-api):

* Convert markdown to restructured text:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/128676/

* Split HTTP methods & resources from section titles:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/128690/

* And a few minor content changes to comply with doc8:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/128693/

This change also adds doc8 validation to the new api/ directory.

Change-Id: Ia575cf8f00558503bf6b4bea11836ddc1d2f1188

commit_message:
split HTTP methods & resources from section titles

Some of these section titles are absurdly long as a result of having a
human-readable description, and the entire HTTP method + example
resource included as a literal.

The HTTP method + example resource is still featured prominently as the
first item under the section title.

Change-Id: Ifd78c9f3aa712401b1fa06d12d703ec6bfd75d1f

User Interface of IBM FlashSystem is based on SVC like IBM Storwize. But it's
a totally unlike storage backend and it's hard to rework the Storwize driver.

In the future, it is likely that the two systems will diverge in their

The development felt it was best to create a separate driver.

Implements: blueprint ibm-flashsystem-driver

commit_message:
Add OpenStack Cinder support for IBM FlashSystem.

Blueprint: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/ibm-flashsystem-driver

User Interface of IBM FlashSystem is based on SVC like IBM Storwize. But it's
a totally unlike storage backend and it's hard to rework the Storwize driver.
The functionality is completely different.
In the future, it is likely that the two systems will diverge in their
similarity.
The development felt it was best to create a separate driver.

Tempest cert has been passed.

Change-Id: I4054254cceb6928626138770a1f4f20f1451f540
Implements: blueprint ibm-flashsystem-driver

Samuel or Evgeny,

So at the LBaaS hackathon, Dustin, Carlos and I discussed order vs. hostname and we came to the conclusion that we'd be OK with order on the SNI list / SNI Policy, so long as we also make note that individual back-ends may choose to implement this as a hostname hash lookup, based on hostnames embedded in the cert as the CN or x509v3 Subject Alternative Names.

In this case, then, we should specifically not make 'hostname' an attribute of the SNI list / SNI policy object because this information will be extracted by the driver / back-end implementation.

I think, though, we all still agree that supporting cipher selection criteria is probably beyond the scope of what we think we can reasonably offer in Juno. Back-ends should plan on using sane defaults for the first release, eh.

If you're in agreement with the above, could y'all update the spec, and we'll remove our '-1's?

Thanks,
Stephen"}, {'account_id': 8446, 'date': '2014-06-20 14:46:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I would like to see a few enhancements to this spec to make it a bit more clear.

1. Can we define the certificate order required for the intermediate CA cert chain?  Different implementations seem to have specific requirements on the order of the certs.

2. Can we standardize on DER format instead of PEM?  DER will give us a large storage space advantage on the barbican and the back end systems.

3. The section discussing the SNI table isn't clear.  This table should be a mapping between SNI IDs and barbican container IDs correct?

4. The order of the SNI mapping table doesn't seem to be a critical feature as the backend should be able to map wildcard certs based on the most specific to least specific.

5. We should have a test case that validates we can do a certificate renewal without interrupting customer traffic.  This should be a workflow via the update API.

6. I think we need a status API defined that allows querying the SNI mapping table.  I would also like to see cipher suite usage statistics.

7. I think we should have a discussion of flavors in this spec and the API.

8. Do we need metadata about the certificate type stored in barbican?  I.e. RSA, DSA, ECDSA  NSA suite b requires ECDSA support so we should support it.

9. What about timeouts such as TLS handshake?

10. We should have session persistence based on the ssl session ID.  I don't see a discussion of this capability in the spec.  I think we should also consider storing the session ID in an HTTP header as an option.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-06-25 19:00:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

IMO - If the storage advantage of der vs pem is that large, pem can always be converted on the fly before writing.  But der is a whole lot less user-fiendly, especially for web protocols that are by nature mostly ascii.  Not to mention that pem is what just about every ca issues by default, so why push that conversion out to everyone?  If anything, accept both before only accepting der.'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-06-25 19:43:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Err, sorry, this spec doesn't have user or API involvement with certs, so I retract my pem/der comments.  That's an issue with how barbican chooses to export certs to services."}, {'account_id': 7398, 'date': '2014-06-25 20:55:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

>1. Can we define the certificate order required for the 
>intermediate CA cert chain? Different implementations seem 
>to have specific requirements on the order of the certs.

    The cert chain is one field which will have a 
concatonation of PEM encoded certs. This concationation of 
pem blocks will determine order.

>2. Can we standardize on DER format instead of PEM? DER 
>will give us a large storage space advantage on the 
>barbican and the back end systems.

    No. With base 64 your encode ratio is 3 binary bytes 
for every 4 base64 text bytes so the savings isn't much 
db side. Also its inappropriate to dictate the storage 
format on the back end implimentation. Most systems I've encountered store the objects in pem form. I'm against using raw binary over a rest interface and PEM is the format most systems use.

>3. The section discussing the SNI table isn't clear. This 
>table should be a mapping between SNI IDs and barbican 
>container IDs correct?

   Yes the SNI IDs list is really just a list of TLS containers. The host names will be extrtacted from the subjectCN as well as altSubjectNames from the cert. Which determines the hostnames the certs are associated.

>4. The order of the SNI mapping table doesn't seem to be a 
>critical feature as the backend should be able to map 
>wildcard certs based on the most specific to least 
>specific.

    SNI order evaluation was requested by at least one vender. It is optional though so if you feel its not needed by your backend implementation doesn't need it you don't have to implement it.

>5. We should have a test case that validates we can do a 
>certificate renewal without interrupting customer traffic. 
>This should be a workflow via the update API.

    certificate renewal is unusual as on the barbican side TLS containers are immutable in that you don't renew them you create new certificates and attach the new TLS id to your listener. 
  
>6. I think we need a status API defined that allows 
>querying the SNI mapping table. I would also like to see 
>cipher suite usage statistics.

    I don't think we can provide this by Juno.

>7. I think we should have a discussion of flavors in this 
>spec and the API.

    I'm not sure what to comment here. I'd rather work with the technical details of the spec.

>8. Do we need metadata about the certificate type storedin 
>barbican? I.e. RSA, DSA, ECDSA NSA suite b requires ECDSA 
>support so we should support it.

    No. We can retrieve the the subject public key info 
from the x509 directly which will provide 
subjectKeyInfo->PublicKeyAlgorithm which identifies the 
cert type.

>9. What about timeouts such as TLS handshake?

    This is rather backend implementation defined. I'm not ready to prescribe behavior for the backend on timeouts in the neutron api.

>10. We should have session persistence based on the ssl 
>session ID. I don't see a discussion of this capability in 
>the spec. I think we should also consider storing the 
>session ID in an HTTP header as an option.

    We did plan on using SSL session persistence but in absence of a ref implementation that actually does it we were pushing this till after juno. SNI was approved as its doable from stunnel or haproxy1.5 which is in the works for the ref implementation."}, {'account_id': 11302, 'date': '2014-06-25 21:11:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7398, 'date': '2014-06-25 21:13:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

evengy I've made a comment before that the TLS containers will hold the text fields
[certificate, private_key, private_key_passphrase, intermediates]

so the lines Creating TLS container with should read

  * Creating TLS container with:

    * certificate : PEM text field
    * private_key: PEM text field
    * Private_key_passphrase : text field
    * intermediates: PEM text field (Optional)

ie cut out the Name description and name field.

Can you make these changes or would you mind if I uploaded my own patch set."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-06-26 03:43:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

+1 to Carlos' response to Michael above. The only other notes I would add to this are:

4. It is possible (and we have seen the occasional deployment) where two uploaded certificates would be valid for the same DNS names, and the user has specific requirements around which one wins this collision. Certificate ordering provides a mechanism to define which cert wins in the event of a collision.

9. While I would like to be able to specify timeouts as well, I think for Juno this should be left out. Let's leave it to a future feature improvement to allow for timeouts.

10. Indeed, this was essentially impossible with haproxy 1.4 + stunnel so was out of the question. haproxy 1.5 is now out, but it's not yet clear that this feature is supported with haproxy 1.5. Again, something for a future feature improvement spec, IMO."}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2014-06-26 03:55:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

We do how ever expect it to be supported by the reference implementation. Evengy can you add this to the document. There are 2 things here

2. Also, I object to mention SubjectAlternativeName (SAN) in context of SNI. The typical use case is to use SubjectCommonName (SCN) for purpose of SNI. My suggestion is to revise the spec to not mention both SAN and SCN. Or mention that specific backend might choose to ignore SAN entries in the certificate.'}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-07-10 22:00:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: Code-Review+1

It is expected that the SubjectCN and alternalteSubjectNane would be inspected at loadbalancer provisioning time and are only required at provisioning. During the TLS handshake the SNI only contains the host name the client is expecting to connect to. The last change you made implies that parsing the X509 would be happening during the TLS handshake which would never happen. IE the decision tree to select the x509 would be build up at lb prov time not during the actual handshake.  I'm negative -1 this comment since its obscuring the intended behavior of SNI. I originally wanted to avoid this can of worms by advocating the user explicity assign an SNI hostname or wildcard per each certificate rather then inspecting all the X509s to fetch the SubjectCN and AltSubjName during lb prov time but as a convenience to the user. 

    While the SNI decision is done at Handshake time I never took this to mean a group of X509s would be parsed at handshake time. Please tell me if you know of a back end solution that does this at request time. I would think the x509s are parsed at provision time (A lot of decisions have to made when ASN1 parsing the x509 and I can't imagine repeating that on every request).

    I think the real question is are we going to go forward with SubjectCN and SubjAltName parsing or are we going to just specify a list of hostnames for a TLS container like originally planned. I don't suggest a hybrid approach. This was also supposed to be discussed on the mailing list and not in blue print patch sets. :("}, {'account_id': 8446, 'date': '2014-07-15 14:06:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Carlos, there is no mean to extract host names from X509 during TLS handshake. SCN and/or SAN should be extracted from X509 while provisioning the listener. It will be done by driver code or by some back-end code that actually provisions the listener.
I didn't see a mailing list thread for this point, I can start one"}, {'account_id': 10273, 'date': '2014-07-15 15:35:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Hi,

Please see comments inline.
There are several issues:

1. new TERMINATED-HTTPS protocol. We have to come to consensus on this issue

2. Immutable protocol for listener. I removed this constraint although I have concerns.

3. Shared pools for listeners. Seems not relevant for this spec right now since this capability will not be part of first release.

4. Horizon project is not a part of this spec. 
 
5. Certificates data caching (SCN and SAN). I sent an email on ML with my proposal not to cache cert data in Neutron database and leave it to drivers who need it to be cached on back-end, since there will be a common API exposing the capability of extraction this data from containers x509. Caching this data in Neutron database seems to be unnecessary and causing extra complication. 

If there are no major/critical objections to the specification with mentioned above modifications, we might want to proceed to approval. We have a week to get it approved for the Juno release.

Thank you!

commit_message:
LBaaS TLS termination capability specification

This document comes to specify TLS termination
capabilities of LBaaS.
The document defines the scope of the first release,
covers configuration options, external requirements,
data model modifications, functional specification,
testing requirements, etc.

Change-Id: I322724946104b836b9a1589c183945496a5e7aff
Implements: blueprint lbaas-ssl-termination

commit_message:
Add tempest-lib as a global requirement and a tracked project

This commit adds tempest-lib to global requirements and also adds it
to project.txt. This will only be a test-requirement on projects,
except for tempest. This is needed so tempest can migrate to using
tempest-lib. The stable jobs run with tempest master, however since
tempest-lib isn't in requirements for the stable branches these jobs
can't pass which blocks the tempest changes from landing.

Change-Id: Iaf6228a5e0968e9578abd93d2d0e47cf6a089c75
(cherry picked from commit ed1126717eedfed036888aa56f4fc6000b4fc6a6)

commit_message:
Ensure create_engine() retries the initial connection test

Before return create_engine() tests the connectivity to a DB. At this
moment a DB might be unavailable for some reason, in which case
create_engine() retries a few times. When used with MySQL, we didn't
actually retry, but instead failed on the first connectivity error
when trying to get the value of sql_mode session variable.

Closes-Bug: #1376211

Co-Authored-By: Mike Bayer <mike_mp@zzzcomputing.com>
Change-Id: I14e25cfe1ed51b0d51a94e491b7267f26e42d34e
(cherry picked from commit 01a54cc5cc43c8b497007dbb07c78dacd03c1ed2)

commit_message:
share neutron admin auth tokens

Admin tokens in nova.network.neutronv2 were being created once per
"thread" (i.e., green thread) and shared. For example, during instance
creation, a single token was created then reused 6 times.  However,
this scheme was far from optimal. Given that tokens, by default, have
a shelf life of 24H, a single token can be shared by _all_ admin
nova.network.neutronv2 calls in a 24-hour period.

DocImpact
Signed-Off-By: Peter Feiner <peter@gridcentric.ca>
Closes-Bug: 1255594

Change-Id: I5c743aa86030e4ab000dcdefb6a7183305512303
(cherry picked from commit 5c01b9e618af44640332871757ff613b2f0b66e2)

commit_message:
Remove compiled message catalogs

A kind of binary files are useless to be maintained in git repo.
I18N team and package distributors have agreed to remove compiled
message catalogs from openstack-auth git repository.

To compile message catalogs, run the following command before
the installation:

  python setup.py compile_catalog

Make sure to install Babel>=1.3 before running the above command.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1196982

Change-Id: Iab2398e942e142f9ab370d8a8f9d539b257e1620

commit_message:
Use response.text for returning unicode EC2 metadata

When serving meta-data that contains unicode, use the webob Response.text
instead of Response.body.  This also adds a test that triggers the bug in
addition to testing that all meta-data offered by the server can be served.

Closes-bug: #1380792

Change-Id: If2ddaa97bbc89cf574205c0327e3caa02dd503fc

[{'created': '2014-09-26 11:01:08.000000000', 'message': 'Use reasonable timeout for rpc service_update()

nova.servicegroup.drivers.db.DbDriver._report_state() is called every
service.report_interval seconds from a timer in order to periodically
report the service state. It calls self.conductor_api.service_update().

If this ends up calling nova.conductor.rpcapi.ConductorAPI.service_update(),
it will do an RPC call() to nova-conductor.

If anything happens to the RPC server (failover, switchover, etc.)
by default the RPC code will wait 60 seconds for a response
(blocking the timer-based calling of _report_state() in the meantime).
This is long enough to cause the status in the database to get old
enough that other services consider this service to be "down".

if rpc_reponse_timeout is smaller than report_interval then we could
use the existing RPC timeout, but wait longer won't hurt. So the patch
didn't check it and only use report_interval.

Change-Id: I88743183bce1a534812cfe6110c3fc2892058c53
Closes-Bug: #1368989

commit_message:
Use reasonable timeout for rpc service_update()

nova.servicegroup.drivers.db.DbDriver._report_state() is called every
service.report_interval seconds from a timer in order to periodically
report the service state. It calls self.conductor_api.service_update().

If this ends up calling nova.conductor.rpcapi.ConductorAPI.service_update(),
it will do an RPC call() to nova-conductor.

If anything happens which causes the RPC reply to be lost or
never sent in the first place, by default the RPC code will
wait 60 seconds for a response (blocking the timer-based
calling of _report_state() in the meantime).
This is long enough to cause the status in the database to get old
enough that other services consider this service to be "down".

if rpc_reponse_timeout is smaller than report_interval then we could
use the existing RPC timeout, but wait longer won't hurt. So the patch
didn't check it and only use report_interval.

Change-Id: I88743183bce1a534812cfe6110c3fc2892058c53
Closes-Bug: #1368989

commit_message:
libvirt: abort init_host method on libvirt that is too old

Nova has a declared minimum supported libvirt and the init_host
method will log an error message if it sees an older version is
installed. Unfortunately people are frequently not seeing this
error message and then filing bugs about things that are broken
on older libvirt versions.

Turn the log message into an exception so that nova-compute
process startup is completely aborted so people will see the
problem immediately rather than some unpredictable time later.

Closes-bug: #1376651
Change-Id: I87d5a41145b05cc2be3559ab528497fe8355ba85

commit_message:
Big Switch: Don't clear hash before sync

This patch removes the step of clearing the consistency
hash from the DB before a topology sync. This will ensure
that inconsistency will be detected if the topology sync
fails.

This logic was originally there to make sure the hash header
was not present on the topology sync call to the backend.
However, the hash header is ignored by the backend in a sync
call so it wasn't necessary.

Closes-Bug: #1379510
Change-Id: I2d58fa2aea3b692834d64192d06ace727c7df8a0
(cherry picked from commit 24e4110eb284078775496501ff81630eb1619c11)

and as a result grenade/functions has been updated with grenade-specific

commit_message:
Move shared devstack functions to functions-common

Syncing devstack/functions-common -> grenade/functions is confusing,
and as a result grenade/functions has been updated with grenade-specific
stuff.  This moves existing functions to 'functions-common' and isolates
grenade specific things to 'functions'.  'functions' sources 'functions-common'
so this should not require any other changes and will make it easier to keep
code synced with devstack.

Change-Id: I3b6324fc3067833075fc5487684d31593627b779

commit_message:
Move generation of baremetal VM names to lib/ironic

The create-nodes script currently receives a total # of VMs to create
and creates them all, generating their names on the fly.  This moves
that name generation to lib/ironic and makes the script create only
single VMs as directed.  This centralizes the naming of things to
lib/ironic and will make it easier to reference these things elsewhere.

Change-Id: I98e61f7188e027e690303e32aff7cd2347f6d2c2

commit_message:
Moves the HA resource creations outside of transaction

Currently the HA resources are created in the
_create_router_db which includes calls to
the plugin and generates RPC calls. Even if the
resource creations are outside of any transaction
from the _create_router_db point of view, this
method is  called in a transaction from the
create_router method.
This patch moves the resource creations to the
create_router method outside the transaction.
The failures are handled as previously with
a try/expect.

Change-Id: If8fcfd012f8e992175e49bbefb2ae667881a620a
Closes-bug: #1374461

commit_message:
Allow documentation to create sequence diagrams

Sequence diagrams are very useful thing for developer
documentation to include and show (especially seeing that
most of openstack is one big sequence diagram) so it would
be great to include and enable the sequence diagram sphinx
plugin and associated seqdiag software.

It will likely also be required to include:

https://bitbucket.org/blockdiag/seqdiag

Where the docs are being built (so there might be a infra
related changed needed to accomdate this).

Change-Id: I85c163265ea0a10881b5d34f601eea6147d4469d

Require Jinja2>=2.6

commit_message:
Add manila to projects.txt

Add manila and python-manilaclient to the list of projects.

A requirements gate job has been proposed as well and the two projects
do not contain any extra or incompatible requirements.

Change-Id: I621bf742211c640e08ee349a2f5d4d52bc8062e0

commit_message:
Convert Neutron driver to use new datasource_driver

Change the Neutron driver to use the declarative way of describing the data
transformation for the driver.

Change-Id: Ie9cc58e4e4bc7c1b3d6be1e96c0bde7aaf5494df

subject: Add a new openstack-specs repo under the control of the TC

Blair', 'email': 'jim@acmegating.com', 'username': 'corvus'}, {'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 7, 'name': 'Jay Pipes', 'email': 'jaypipes@gmail.com', 'username': 'jaypipes'}, {'_account_id': 67, 'name': 'Vish Ishaya', 'email': 'vishvananda@gmail.com', 'username': 'vishvananda'}, {'_account_id': 308, 'name': 'Thierry Carrez', 'email': 'thierry@openstack.org', 'username': 'ttx'}, {'_account_id': 964, 'name': 'Anne Gentle', 'email': 'annegentle@justwriteclick.com', 'username': 'annegentle'}, {'_account_id': 1561, 'name': 'Russell Bryant', 'email': 'rbryant@redhat.com', 'username': 'russellb'}, {'_account_id': 1849, 'name': 'Joe Gordon', 'email': 'joe.gordon0@gmail.com', 'username': 'jogo'}, {'_account_id': 2243, 'name': 'John Griffith', 'email': 'john.griffith8@gmail.com', 'username': 'john-griffith'}, {'_account_id': 2271, 'name': 'Michael Still', 'email': 'mikal@stillhq.com', 'username': 'mikalstill'}, {'_account_id': 2472, 'name': 'Doug Hellmann', 'email': 'dhellmann@redhat.com', 'username': 'doug-hellmann'}, {'_account_id': 2592, 'name': 'Mark McClain', 'email': 'mark@mcclain.xyz', 'username': 'markmcclain'}, {'_account_id': 2889, 'name': 'Aeva Black', 'email': 'aeva.online@gmail.com', 'username': 'tenbrae'}, {'_account_id': 6316, 'name': 'Anita Kuno', 'email': 'anteaya@anteaya.info', 'username': 'anteaya'}]

[{'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-01 22:12:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-01 22:12:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/09/125509/1/check/noop/79901ce : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-02 10:22:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

openstack/governance is owned by the TC, and I think this repository should be owned by the TC as well. I guess we could encode the list of repositories that are "under the TC directly" in a specific file under reference/, since the TC is not technically a program :)'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-02 18:33:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-02 18:33:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/09/125509/2/check/noop/1088453 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-03 09:18:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-10-06 18:18:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I don't mind the idea of openstack-specs being a repository where cross-project specifications are developed. However, I don't think the TC should own the repository or have +2/+W rights on it. I think that working groups that are created to solve certain problems (log stuff, API consistency, etc) should be responsible for owning and approving specs in the openstack-specs repository, not the TC.

Unfortunately, we don't really have a good way of saying "for this spec, these people on this working group should develop and approve it". :( So, I guess I'm +0/light +1 on this because there really isn't a better Gerrit group than the TC membership at this point...

-jay'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-06 19:52:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Jay, by under the control of the TC, I mean the TC should decide how to set up gerrit permissions etc. For example one option is the TC gives the TC +2,+W Permissions. Another option is the TC gives that power to a body they create. Or just make it a group of PTLs etc.

I don't envision the TC officially playing a very active role in the discussion that happens in this repo. It is more of the repo needs a home."}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:08:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2014-10-16 17:59:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thierry said "openstack/governance is owned by the TC, and I think this repository should be owned by the TC as well. I guess we could encode the list of repositories that are "under the TC directly" in a specific file under reference/, since the TC is not technically a program :)"

I'm in agreement that there should be "a place" for repos of this type whereever that place is. The openstack-specs falls in this category and in my opinion so does the api-working-group, which also wants to create a repo: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/128466/ which I am -1 on simply because I don't know where it should live, nor do I have an understanding of the process to follow to add more repos of this type.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-10-21 05:35:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-10-21 06:41:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

+1 for a home for cross project specs, and the ability of the TC to decide who (not necessarily the TC itself) has approval rights on those specs.

Though, an alternate POV here is that, in a big-tent kind of world, what validity is there in a cross project spec that declares how projects should do a thing (like logging)? commit_message:
Add a new openstack-specs repo under the control of the TC

One of the takeaways from the exercise about kilo priorities was oslo is
not the right home for all cross project discussions. We need a new home
for cross project specs, and since the TC is our governing technical
committee this repo should be under there management.

The specific scope and model for this repo is left up to the TC to
decide. Although I am in favor of using this for specs that are not limited
to a just a few projects (although not every project may hit the issue
the spec is addressing at the same time) and using this as recommended
guidelines. For example having a spec on doing API microversioning would
be useful as several projects hope to implement this and it would be
ashame if they all did it slightly differently. Another example is
logging standards: what debug,info etc should consist of.

Related project-config change: Id9393dfc2c7f1f883a5f20d85f7ecb79e2c52063

Change-Id: I498a304057043a54370b132f2153a4c65840639c

commit_message:
Some wonky workaround to fix a boot error

for some reason nova-network image cannot find the kolla-common file
resulting in a failed startup of nova-network.  I would like to release
today and we don't really need this file sourced to work (I have tested
without it and booted VMs).  We can revisit in milestone #2.

commit_message:
ModelsMigrationsSync: Add check for foreign keys

Add method that checks that foreign keys in models are synchonized
with foreign keys that are created in database.

Change-Id: I4a776da0f53a79218ed4b111cac33b37d264fa1b

Something that has been bothering me when looking at the PCI code is
that the modules in /nova/pci/ unnecessarily were prefixed with pci_.
For instance, nova/pci/pci_device.py, whereas all other module directory
organizations for all other code in Nova uses the directory name to
demarcate a submodule.

commit_message:
Clean up the naming of PCI python modules

Something that has been bothering me when looking at the PCI code is
that the modules in /nova/pci/ unnecessarily were prefixed with pci_.
For instance, nova/pci/pci_device.py, whereas all other module directory
organizations for all other code in Nova uses the directory name to
demarcate a submodule.

This patch simply gets the nova/pci/ modules in-line with the standard
set everywhere else in Nova and cuts off the pci_ prefix from the module
names.

Change-Id: Ia5ca13f674f15b41e22b8488efe44eb926e5e4eb

If more than one NFS share is defined, all volumes are allocated on the
same NFS share until it is not eligible anymore. Then a second NFS share
is filled. The code is supposed to split volumes between the different
NFS shares, not fill them one by one.

It is a bug in _find_shares(). If at least one NFS share is eligible,
the "size" parameter (size of the requested volume in gigabytes) is
replaced with the total size in bytes of the share. Because of that,

_find_shares() sorts eligible volumes by available size. Because of this
bug, all volumes are allocated in the same NFS share, instead of being

commit_message:
Fix NetAppDirectCmodeNfsDriver._find_shares()

If more than one NFS share is defined, all volumes are allocated on the
same NFS share until it is not eligible anymore. Then a second NFS share
is filled. The code is supposed to split volumes between the different
NFS shares, not fill them one by one.

It is a bug in _find_shares(). If at least one NFS share is eligible,
the "size" parameter (size of the requested volume in gigabytes) is
replaced with the total size in bytes of the share. Because of that,
_find_shares() cannot find more one eligible NFS share.

_find_shares() sorts eligible volumes by available size. Because of this
bug, all volumes are allocated in the same NFS share, instead of being
splitted on different NFS shares.

The _find_shares() has been removed in Juno, see:

* commit 98aa91b0e271d6fbd9dfe43bf4152fb138a46a89
* change Ie6f155df7bc1ae2cd5f7fa39f1b1a0ad38075988

Change-Id: I7b72921a2a45d5dd0aa969c8c32f7d815175f3a8
Co-author: "Florent Flament" <florent.flament-ext@cloudwatt.com>
Closes-Bug: #1369426

commit_message:
VMware: Support OVA container format

Currently, the VMware is not supporting images with "ova" container
format. This spec adds support for it by extracting the root disk from
the OVA and use it to boot the VM.

Previously-approved: juno

Change-Id: I8704c697cafbe7f17cde6a3eadcad5e9d21e35b3
