commit_message:
Removed python26 from python-jobs

This patch removes the python26 jobs from the default python-jobs
template, and adds them manually to each project that was previously
using them. This patch is not intended to deprecate, pin, or remove
the python26 build from any project; instead, it is intended to support
such activity that may occur in subsequent patches.

Change-Id: I3124e9e557d7e537d173a4f6c421e55b17e693da

(1 comment)

Hi Jim,

Thanks for the patch, it LGTM. I'm +1 because I'm interested what other people think about how this maintenance_reason will work.

On IRC, I suggested that we create a new endpoint in our API to set/unset the node maintenance mode. Where unsetting it would also clean up the reason. Something like:

POST {'reason': 'blah'} v1/nodes/UUID/maintenance

DELETE v1/nodes/UUID/maintenance

IMO, when we have to do more actions consequently to update a resource field, it kinda means that we need a diff endpoint for it. And maintenance for e.g by having diff endpoint it also could be used to signalize Nova about it, like setting the node to maintenance would make the nova driver exclude the node immediately from the list of available nodes and vice versa when deleting it.

What people thing about it? Any other suggestions/ideas?"}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2014-10-15 13:55:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add Node.maintenance_reason

When a node is maintenanced by Ironic or an operator, an operator
should know the reason for that. Add a string column to allow
Ironic or operators to enter a reason that the node is in
maintenance mode.

Implements: blueprint maintenance-reason

Change-Id: I7c77c92501e53f81704e9b9e5b52e0e2a410cc91

commit_message:
Add tempest-lib as a global requirement and a tracked project

This commit adds tempest-lib to global requirements and also adds it
to project.txt. This will only be a test-requirement on projects,
except for tempest.

This is needed so tempest can migrate to using tempest-lib. The stable
jobs run with tempest master, however since tempest-lib isn't in
requirements for the stable branches these jobs can't pass which blocks
the tempest changes from landing.

Change-Id: Iaf6228a5e0968e9578abd93d2d0e47cf6a089c75
(cherry picked from commit ed1126717eedfed036888aa56f4fc6000b4fc6a6)

[{'created': '2014-10-21 19:24:26.000000000', 'message': "Handle AlarmDefinitionUpdatedEvents

The ThresholdEngine can now handle AlarmDefinition updates where the
associated Metrics don't changes. So, the only things that can
change are operator, function, threshold, period, periods and the boolean
operators linking AlarmSubExpressions together. The number of
AlarmSubExpressions and anything else like matchBy can't change.

Tie the SubALarms to the AlarmSubExpressions in the
Alarm Definition by the ID of the AlarmSubExpresssions

Move the logic that handles a SubExpression update into SubAlarmStats

Route the update messages to the proper bolts on the proper streams

Fix a problem in AlarmDAOImpl where the AlarmedMetrics didn't have
their dimensions set properly

Rewrite ThresholdingEngineAlarmTest to be clearer how it works. Also,
test the new functionality

SubExpression needs to be registered for Serialization or weird things
happen where sometimes it is serialized properly and sometimes the
id is null

Fix the ThresholdingEngineTest so all three tests can run. Topology
has to be torn down and rebuilt each time

Change-Id: I8b37d7d4791463a6e704d10d75e35332818d3a68
"}]
commit_message:
Handle AlarmDefinitionUpdatedEvents

The ThresholdEngine can now handle AlarmDefinition updates where the
associated Metrics don't changes. So, the only things that can
change are operator, function, threshold, period, periods and the boolean
operators linking AlarmSubExpressions together. The number of
AlarmSubExpressions and anything else like matchBy can't change.

Tie the SubALarms to the AlarmSubExpressions in the
Alarm Definition by the ID of the AlarmSubExpresssions

Move the logic that handles a SubExpression update into SubAlarmStats

Route the update messages to the proper bolts on the proper streams

Fix a problem in AlarmDAOImpl where the AlarmedMetrics didn't have
their dimensions set properly

Rewrite ThresholdingEngineAlarmTest to be clearer how it works. Also,
test the new functionality

SubExpression needs to be registered for Serialization or weird things
happen where sometimes it is serialized properly and sometimes the
id is null

Fix the ThresholdingEngineTest so all three tests can run. Topology
has to be torn down and rebuilt each time

Change-Id: I8b37d7d4791463a6e704d10d75e35332818d3a68

commit_message:
Improve hash ring value conversion

The current method for computing the point on the hash ring converts
the MD5 digest into a 4-byte integer (and assumes big-endian). The
digest is actually a 16-byte value, so we are eliminating much of
the value, thus increasing the possibility of hash collisions.

This patch does two things:

  * Removes the endianness assumption
  * Uses the full value of the digest to create a long integer,
    which has unlimited precision in Python.

Change-Id: I554ec46f506cb8cdfd5878c11a905a3acfe92db0

commit_message:
Reverse order of tests to avoid incompatibility

If py26 tests are run first, there is some incompatibility in the
.testrepository that breaks several tests.  To get around this, you
need to run the py33 tests first.  This change was made over in the
cliff project.

Before:

    (.venv)terry@brat:~/hp/sdk$ rm -rf .testrepository/
    (.venv)terry@brat:~/hp/sdk$ tox
      ...
      py26: commands succeeded
      py27: commands succeeded
    ERROR:   py33: commands failed
    ERROR:   py34: commands failed
    ERROR:   pypy: commands failed
      pep8: commands succeeded

After:

    (.venv)terry@brat:~/hp/sdk$ rm -rf .testrepository/
    (.venv)terry@brat:~/hp/sdk$ tox
      ...
      py33: commands succeeded
      py34: commands succeeded
      py26: commands succeeded
      py27: commands succeeded
      pypy: commands succeeded
      pep8: commands succeeded
      congratulations :)
    (.venv)terry@brat:~/hp/sdk$ 

Change-Id: I64925097ce003659c4daa0e105bd06dc30726921

[{'created': '2014-10-13 01:43:20.000000000', 'message': 'Refactored Client to use Keystone Sessions

This CR changes the Client to use Keystone Sessions exclusively. All
authentication that was previously available in barbicanclient is
removed so that we can defer all authentication to keystoneclient.

Unit tests for the client module have been refactored to test the new
functionality.

The README file has been updated to give an example of how to
authenticate using Sessions.

The Client will now give priority to an endpoint that is passed in over
endpoints found in the service catalog, which closes bug #1276002.  This
is helpful for development, where you might be running an instance of
Barbican locally that uses a Keystone instance for authentication that
does not have the Barbican service in its catalog.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint use-keystone-sessions
Closes-Bug: #1276002

Change-Id: I9d07cb50143c1f5cafea48318018a205f745999f

commit_message:
Refactored Client to use Keystone Sessions

This CR changes the Client to use Keystone Sessions exclusively. All
authentication that was previously available in barbicanclient is
removed so that we can defer all authentication to keystoneclient.

Unit tests for the client module have been refactored to test the new
functionality.

The README file has been updated to give an example of how to
authenticate with Identity v3 using Sessions.

The Client will now give priority to an endpoint that is passed in over
endpoints found in the service catalog, which closes bug #1276002.  This
is helpful for development, where you might be running an instance of
Barbican locally that uses a Keystone instance for authentication that
does not have the Barbican service in its catalog.

The CLI uses Keystone API v3 as the default authentication method, but
can also use v2.0.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint use-keystone-sessions
Closes-Bug: #1276002

Change-Id: I9d07cb50143c1f5cafea48318018a205f745999f

commit_message:
Group Policy CLI-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

This patch includes Neutronclient (CLI) support for GP Endpoint, Endpoint Group, L2 Policy, L3 Policy resources.

Change-Id: I44acc6a6b340e931f7540794bbc929c426d1d2cc
Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

commit_message:
Use the mock that finds a working implementation

Instead of using the library provided mock, use the import
logic in our tests module that tries to find the best one that is
usable in the current environment. It appears that this logic
is *still* needed due to bugs in the non-bundled mock that
causes errors/exceptions such as:

AttributeError: 'method-wrapper' object has no attribute '__module__'

It seems this is related to (or is this same) upstream bug:

- https://code.google.com/p/mock/issues/detail?id=234

Change-Id: Ifeb3017f43b7d34af155ceca35d040706d34b185

commit_message:
Revert "Support service user and project in non-default domain"

This case can be handled by default/design by using a v3 authentication
plugin. The values also don't make sense for v2 authentication.

Having them here means extra values to support in the default case.

There has not been a release with this patch.

This reverts commit bb00caf15be9336663521a913984795af9bed185.
Related-bug: #1372142

Change-Id: I690f39284010906a0171178511729749ccc566b8

commit_message:
Revert "introduce $SYSTEMD_SYSTEM_UNIT_DIR"

This reverts commit 4bf38a829a00f1866e6d93f50d784694e16e93c2.

This variable is pointless since we can always replace it with
/lib/systemd.

Commit I459f7514ab35082d31607968252a9005fa25de2a will fix the issue
in tripleo-image-elements.

Change-Id: I524badb6836a0d04a5f6e6a5b5d95920fd923ef6

commit_message:
Group Policy Plugin-3: Contracts

(Patch series identifier: GP-PLG-3)

This patch includes the plugin and the policy driver framework to realize the
Contracts resource.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, Contracts contain Policy
Rules and Endpoint Groups consume or provide Contracts. Policy Rule were
introduces in GP-API-2 patch, and Endpoint Groups were introduced in
GP-API-1 patch (both are earlier patches in this series).

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: I1cb892967c1fdc4b2dbfd4c7a6527cf3415b6ce2
Author: Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

commit_message:
Group Policy: One Convergence NVSD Group Policy Driver

This patch introduces Group Policy driver for One Convergence NVSD.
The actual realization of the Group Policy implementation is done by the One Convergence NVSD.
This Group Policy Driver acts as a shim layer, translating the Openstack Group Policy API, to One Convergence NVSD API.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/108154
Implements: blueprint gbp-oc-nvsd-driver

Change-Id: I65470a80494c61b81717767f5472a545d0f0c8d6

commit_message:
Group Policy: Resource Mapping Driver (Security Groups)

(Patch series identifier: GPM-RMD-SG)

This patch adds the resource_mapping group policy driver for
contract rendering to Neutron security groups. This initial
patch for contract rendering does NOT yet handle policy rule
mappings persistency, as well as ability to handle individual
update of resources: policy-rule, classifier, and action

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Stephen Wong <stephen.kf.wong@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Change-Id: I970fb54e5d2aa4ebe4174fd2db8769ce95155a0d

(2 comments)

One should be able to associate a contract with provider and consumer endpoint groups when contracts are defined. This will allow supporting a workflow such as the following from the CLI:

$ neutron endpoint-group-create epg1
$ neutron endpoint-group-create epg2
$ neutron contract-create --provided-by epg1 --consumed-by epg2 ....

This can lead to a simpler and easier to understand workflow in particular for cases where contracts are essentially policies defined between two endpoint groups. commit_message:
Group Policy DB-3: Contracts

(Patch series identifier: GP-DB-3)

This patch includes the DB layer for the Contracts resource.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, Contracts contain Policy
Rules and Endpoint Groups consume or provide Contracts. Policy Rule were
introduces in GP-API-2 patch, and Endpoint Groups were introduced in GP-API-1
patch (both are earlier patches in this series).

The Plugin layer to back the Contract resource  will also be introduced in a
subsequent patche.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: I0a3199faf3003fdff4bd65ba9da5fb6257bce7b8
Author: Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>

Co-Authored-By: Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ivar Lazzaro <lazzaro@noironetworks.com>

commit_message:
Group Policy API-3: Contracts

(Patch series identifier: GP-API-3)

This is the third API patch in the Group Policy series. It introduces the
Resource Model and API for Contracts.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, Contracts contain Policy Rules
and Endpoint Groups consume or provide Contracts. Policy Rule were introduces
in GP-API-2 patch, and Endpoint Groups were introduced in GP-API-1 patch (both
are earlier patches in this series).

The DB and Plugin layers to back the Contract resource  will also be introduced in subsequent patches.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: I2b3ee58062e0e44a9090ee111adffda16f37524d
Author: Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

[{'created': '2014-06-30 06:09:12.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy Plugin-2: Classifiers, Actions, and Rules

(Patch series identifier: GP-PLG-2)

This patch includes the plugin and the policy driver framework to realize the Policy Classifiers, Policy Actions, and Policy Rules resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Policy Rule resource
is referenced by Contracts, which be will introduced in a subsequent patch.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469
("classifiers" and "actions" resources in the above spec have been renamed to
"policy_classifiers" and "policy_actions")

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: Ia7d4b379091a36152fde219918348fb2a41577a8
Author: Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>
'}, {'created': '2014-06-30 06:10:31.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy Plugin-2: Classifiers, Actions, and Rules

commit_message:
Group Policy Plugin-2: Classifiers, Actions, and Rules

(Patch series identifier: GP-PLG-2)

This patch includes the plugin and the policy driver framework to realize the
Policy Classifiers, Policy Actions, and Policy Rules resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Policy Rule resource
is referenced by Contracts, which be will introduced in a subsequent patch.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469
("classifiers" and "actions" resources in the above spec have been renamed to
"policy_classifiers" and "policy_actions")

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

commit_message:
Group Policy DB-2: Classifiers, Actions, and Rules

(Patch series identifier: GP-DB-2)

This patch includes the DB layer for Policy Classifiers, Policy Actions, and
Policy Rules resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Policy Rule resource
is referenced by Contracts, which be will introduced in a subsequent patch.

The Plugin layer to back these resources will also be introduced in a subsequent patch.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469
("classifiers" and "actions" resources in the above spec have been renamed to
"policy_classifiers" and "policy_actions")

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-23 07:40:47.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy API-2: Classifiers, Actions, and Rules

This is the second API patch in the Group Policy series. It introduces the
Resource Model and API for Policy Classifiers, Policy Actions, and Policy
Rules.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Policy Rule resource is
referenced by Contracts, which be will introduced in a subsequent patch.

The DB and Plugin layers to back these resources will also be introduced in
subsequent patches.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469
("classifiers" and "actions" resources in the above spec have been renamed to
"policy_classifiers" and "policy_actions")

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: Idf91331573bcf6dea193c222a8aa9b96708d81c8
Author: Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>

Co-Authored-By: Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

commit_message:
Group Policy API-2: Classifiers, Actions, and Rules

This is the second API patch in the Group Policy series. It introduces the
Resource Model and API for Policy Classifiers, Policy Actions, and Policy
Rules.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Policy Rule resource is
referenced by Contracts, which be will introduced in a subsequent patch.

The DB and Plugin layers to back these resources will also be introduced in
subsequent patches.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469
("classifiers" and "actions" resources in the above spec have been renamed to
"policy_classifiers" and "policy_actions")

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: Idf91331573bcf6dea193c222a8aa9b96708d81c8
Author: Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>

Co-Authored-By: Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-07 20:43:31.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy: Resource Mapping Driver

(Patch series identifier: GPM-RMD-1)

This patch adds the resource_mapping group policy driver, which
renders group policy via mappings to other neutron resources,
including networks, subnets, ports, and routers. This initial version
of the driver does not yet handle policy rule resources, so all
traffic is allowed between endpoint groups that share an L3 policy.

Note - This patch is currently a work in progress. Mapped resources
supplied via the client API are not validated, updates are not
handled, and mapped resources owned by the driver are not cleaned up
when group policy resources are deleted. A temporary subnet allocation
algorithm is used that depends on exceptions being raised for in-use
subnets. Finally, the mechanism for invoking operations on the mapped
resources is likely to change.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Change-Id: I73531726aa31ca41e6df5f5a8f90ba5aad066781

commit_message:
Group Policy: Resource Mapping Driver

(Patch series identifier: GPM-RMD-1)

This patch adds the resource_mapping group policy driver, which
renders group policy via mappings to traditional neutron resources,
including networks, subnets, ports, and routers. This initial version
of the driver does not yet handle policy rule resources, so all
traffic is allowed between endpoint groups that share an L3 policy.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Change-Id: I73531726aa31ca41e6df5f5a8f90ba5aad066781

commit_message:
Group Policy: Implicit Policy Driver

(Patch series identifier: GPM-IPD-1)

This patch adds the implicit_policy group policy driver, which is
responsible for implicitly supplying L2 and L3 policy objects when
they are not explicitly provided via the client API.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Change-Id: Iccb10642741851a96cc68822f0c7249461059445

resources.

commit_message:
Group Policy Mapping Plugin-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

(Patch series identifier: GPM-PLG-1)

This patch changes the plugin layer for the initial set of Group
Policy API resources (see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96393/) to
use the Group Policy Mapping DB layer and its unit tests. Subsequent
patches will add drivers rendering policy constructs via the mapped
resources.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Change-Id: I580d3f72daebc73228a9cecf49c4eb01caab4e8c

commit_message:
Group Policy Mapping DB-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

(Patch series identifier: GPM-DB-1)

This patch extends the DB layer for the initial set of Group Policy
API resources (see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/96050/) with
attributes mapping those resources to traditional Neutron
resources. Subsequent patches will add the plugin and driver support
for the mapped resources.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Change-Id: I07b371dea38ce3fe527da00cd7b795adfdc632cb

'}, {'created': '2014-06-19 15:38:29.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy Mapping API-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

This patch extends the initial set of Group Policy API resources (see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/95900/) with attributes mapping those
resources to traditional Neutron resources. Subsequent patches will
add the DB, plugin, and driver support for the mapping attributes.

Two minor fixes to the Group Policy API-1 patch are also included: the
maximum value for default_subnet_prefix_length is changed from 63 to
127, and the values used to test L3Policy attributes are changed from
the defaults to typical IPv6 values.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Group Policy Mapping API-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

(Patch series identifier: GPM-API-1)

This patch extends the initial set of Group Policy API resources (see
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/95900/) with attributes mapping those
resources to traditional Neutron resources. Subsequent patches will
add the DB, plugin, and driver support for these mapping attributes.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Author:            Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>

Co-Authored-By:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Change-Id: I788fa6372b36831ee3b8af973de410bfd5cbebdb

commit_message:
Group Policy Plugin-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

(Patch series identifier: GP-PLG-1)

This patch includes the plugin and the policy driver framework to realize the
Endpoint, Endpoint Group, L2 Policy, and L3 Policy resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Endpoint Group resource
references Contracts, which will be introduced in a subsequent patch.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: Iffaf41d84e3acab6cf628ac0305489e4177c05de

Co-Authored-By: Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

Please restore deletion functionality of the test context managers. If you don't want deletion in a certain test, use the create function instead of the context manager. The mapping level tests use these context managers along with the core neutron resource context managers, and expect both to delete the resources."}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2014-06-17 13:55:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Maru Newby		Jun 16 5:18 PM Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1
(2 comments):
"As per the inline comment, I'd like to see removal of contextmanager to manage object lifecycle in this patch's tests. Removing this pattern from existing tests will hopefully occur this cycle and I'd like to avoid having test additions add to the refactoring burden."

Can you explain why you'd like to see removal of this use of contextmanagers in the UTs? Has there been any discussion and consensus around this? I feel it is very valuable for the UTs to pervasively ensure that destruction actually works, especially when foreign keys and cascades and such are involved at the DB layer. This applies not only to the positive tests, but also to negative tests.

If there is consensus to move away from this use of context managers, is there a plan to ensure that delete functionality is adequately tested?

My immediate concern is that the GP mapping UTs, which inherit these UT support functions, use the GP resource context managers in combination with the network, subnet, port, and router context managers from the V2 API test base class. A mix of deletion semantics would make this code difficult to write, understand and maintain.'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2014-06-17 20:29:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2014-06-17 20:56:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

OK, I understand that there are reasonable arguments for removing unnecessary delete calls from the neutron UTs. But I'm not sure there is consensus around this yet, and it impacts a lot of code. Testing deletes across a wide variety of inputs may have some value, at least where DB schemas use foreign keys, like in the upcoming GP mapping patches.

The main issue right now is that the UTs in the upcoming mapping DB and plugin patches, which use these context managers, also extensively use the port(), subnet(), network(), and router() context managers. I don't think we should mix semantics and styles in the same tests, so therefore feel these GP resource context managers should follow the same pattern as the others, at least for now. All this can all be revisited later if there is a decision to eliminate the context managers from the UTs.

I'd also recommend that, if and when we do eliminate the deletes, we use functions in place of the context managers to avoid the extra indentation and make it clear no deletion is being done. So if we do not restore the deletes in these UTs, we at least need to replace the context managers with functions.

But just to be clear, my preference for the GP tests is to keep the context managers and restore the delete calls within them."}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2014-06-18 13:17:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

After discussion with marun and kevinbenton on #openstack-neutron, we've agreed to not add new context managers in these unit tests, and to do lifecycle testing via explicit deletes."}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2014-06-18 20:47:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

[{'created': '2014-05-28 04:11:46.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy DB-1: EP, EPG, L2 Context, L3 Context

This patch includes the DB layer for for Endpoint, Endpoint Group, L2
Context, and L3 Context resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Endpoint Group resource
references Contracts, which will be introduced in a subsequent patch.

The Plugin layer to back these resources will also be introduced in
subsequent patches.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469
("bridge_domains" and "routing_domains" resources in the above spec have been
renamed to "l2_contexts" and "l3_contexts"; "ip_supernet" and
"subnet_prefix_length" attributes in "routing_domains" has been renamed to
"ip_pool" and "default_subnet_prefix_length" attributes in "l3_contexts")

Implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

'}, {'created': '2014-07-02 09:58:46.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy DB-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

(Path series identifier: GP-DB-1)

This patch includes the DB layer for for Endpoint, Endpoint Group, L2
Policy, and L3 Policy resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Endpoint Group resource
references Contracts, which will be introduced in a subsequent patch.

commit_message:
Group Policy DB-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

(Patch series identifier: GP-DB-1)

This patch includes the DB layer for for Endpoint, Endpoint Group, L2
Policy, and L3 Policy resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Endpoint Group resource
references Contracts, which will be introduced in a subsequent patch.

The Plugin layer to back these resources will also be introduced in
subsequent patches.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

This initial patch has been ready to merge for quite a while now, with no new issues filed against it. The entire gp-api-1 through gpm-rmd-1 series is complete and functional, and has been updated in response to all review comments received so far. 

This series of patches provides a usable subset of the group policy API BP reviewed and approved for Juno, including a reference implementation that works with any core plugin. It can configure networking for VMs, with all traffic allowed between EndpointGroups that share an L3Policy. A tempest test has also been submitted for review and testing. Work is proceeding on subsequent series' of patches that complete the group policy API and the enforcement of its policy rules. I see no reason at this point to further delay final review and merging of at least the initial patches in this series. 

Mark, I believe that all of your conditions for merging these patches have been satisfied, so please either remove your -2 from this patch so reviews and merging can proceed, or provide detailed comments in this review that explain why you believe the -2 is still justified.

Thanks,

[{'created': '2014-05-27 20:27:46.000000000', 'message': 'Group Policy API-1: EP, EPG, L2 Context, L3 Context

This is the first in a series of patches which implement Group Policy. It
includes the Resource Model and API for Endpoint, Endpoint Group, L2
Context, and L3 Context resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Endpoint Group resource
references Contracts, which will be introduced in a subsequent patch.

The DB and Plugin layers to back these resources will also be introduced in
subsequent patches.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469
("bridge_domains" and "routing_domains" resources in the above spec have been
renamed to "l2_contexts" and "l3_contexts"; "ip_supernet" and
"subnet_prefix_length" attributes in "routing_domains" has been renamed to
"ip_pool" and "default_subnet_prefix_length" attributes in "l3_contexts")

Implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: Ie1cb58b5e3e0112e52a8b4a8e444b9868d9fcc6e
Author:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Author:    Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Author:    Stephen Wong <s3wong@midokura.com>
Author:    Mohammad Banikazemi <mb@us.ibm.com>
Author:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

commit_message:
Group Policy API-1: EP, EPG, L2 Policy, L3 Policy

(Patch series identifier: GP-API-1)

This is the first in a series of patches which implement Group Policy. It
includes the Resource Model and API for Endpoint, Endpoint Group, L2
Policy, and L3 Policy resources.

In the context of the larger Group Policy Model, the Endpoint Group resource
references Contracts, which will be introduced in a subsequent patch.

The DB and Plugin layers to back these resources will also be introduced in
subsequent patches.

DocImpact

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Partially-implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Set SWIFT_TEMPURL_KEY for Ironic agent_ssh checks

IPA requires swift temp urls for deployment, and all runs of this check
are failing waiting for this variable to be input.

Currently, the undercloud, overcloud control and overcloud compute
flavors are hardcoded to 'baremetal', which makes it harder for
operators to decide what gets deployed where when they have a
heterogeneous environment. Allow the flavor to be deployed onto to

Change-Id: I1b653020acf4b5acb510ba4a092f854815e36a87

commit_message:
Add support for specifying flavors

Currently, the undercloud, overcloud control and overcloud compute
flavors are hardcoded to 'baremetal', which makes it harder for
operators to decide what gets deployed where when they have a
heterogeneous environment. Allow the flavor to be deployed onto to
be easily overridden, leaving the default as 'baremetal' for
backwards compatibility.

Change-Id: I1b653020acf4b5acb510ba4a092f854815e36a87

Adds configuration to support an API Working Group project.

across all the OpenStack projects

commit_message:
Naive script to verify extra-atc foundation status

This script is pretty naive and reports that some of the names in
extra-atcs do not appear in the foundation list. Still, it's a shorter
list to verify than the full set.

commit_message:
Add heat-translator to the Heat program

After having a good discussion on the IRC Heat weekly meeting and mailing
list, the Heat PTL and core team voted and agreed to have the Heat-Translator
project added to its official program. Heat-Translator is currently a
StackForge project and provides a way to translate non-Heat templates to
Heat Orchestration Template (HOT).

Change-Id: I038b9e9ac6fc2b3584dcbc5ffd1033fa8fb0d52e

++'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-17 12:41:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-10-17 16:03:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The only issue that Everett raised (and it's a good one) is that we don't want the API WG to consume resources from the TC, nor do we wish to require TC member votes on API WG proposals -- the API WG members should do the voting. We do, however, wish to have a single chair for the API WG able to tally the votes and do a +W in the same way that ttx does for the openstack/governance repo.

Is that possible?

-jay"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-20 09:11:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The way I see it is this: better API design is high on the TC priority list, so we are very happy to see an API WG forming and would like to facilitate their work. Having an official repository helps the mission of that WG, so the TC is happy to "host" such a repository until the workgroup evolves into a program (or anything else that would be allowed to have such an openstack/* repo). Responsibility for that repository is delegated to the nascent WG, so this is not taking up TC resources.

Think of it as a workaround to bypass the lack of flexibility of our current model.'}, {'account_id': 1112, 'date': '2014-10-21 01:41:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sounds good to me. Thanks ttx.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-10-21 05:36:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-10-21 17:42:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-21 17:48:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Even under the proposed more inclusive governance systems, I think it's appropriate for the TC to "own" these repositories and for the working groups to manage them.'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:22:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Out of curiosity, why not make API recommendations count as cross-project specifications (and put them into the openstack/specs repo instead of creating a new one)?'}, {'account_id': 67, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:23:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:25:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:29:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

The end goal process for the api-wg is unclear to me, but regardless I think it makes sense for the TC to own it.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:31:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Adds a new api-wg repo under the control of the TC

Adds the API WG repository under the list of repos to be controlled
by the TC. The API WG is a cross project workgroup that aims to
provide guidelines and standards for all openstack projects for
desgon of their REST APIs.

Related project-config change: Iecff31860eb36d124ebcc573d20f2a72dabdc8c4

Change-Id: I8c708bcb4ba9a818b6aecdd51e65619c66bb69e1

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary FloatingIpAssociated catch

FloatingIpAssociated exception happens on the following cases only:
 * nova/network/neutronv2/api.py: disassociate_floating_ip
 * nova/network/floating_ips.py: deallocate_floating_ip
However, addFloatingIp REST API catches the exception now.
This patch removes the unnecessary catch.

Change-Id: I9de14b1766fa0eccab48424843f8bb04a7a04523
Closes-Bug: #1376102

[{'created': '2014-10-21 19:17:13.000000000', 'message': "Add a new qa-specs-core group and use it

This commit changes the core group on the qa-specs repo to be a
separate group. When qa-specs started the only project it affected was
tempest, however for kilo we are going to be using it for devstack and
grenade too. To manage domain expertise in the separate projects we need
to be able to hand tailor the core group to include the appropriate sets
of people which we couldn't do if it was just using the core group from
tempest. So a new group is needed to handle this.

Change-Id: I3e3f0da0f2aea5903017444167c472867885a753
"}]
commit_message:
Add a new qa-specs-core group and use it

This commit changes the core group on the qa-specs repo to be a
separate group. When qa-specs started the only project it affected was
tempest, however for kilo we are going to be using it for devstack and
grenade too. To manage domain expertise in the separate projects we need
to be able to hand tailor the core group to include the appropriate sets
of people which we couldn't do if it was just using the core group from
tempest. So a new group is needed to handle this.

Change-Id: I3e3f0da0f2aea5903017444167c472867885a753

commit_message:
Fix libssl/crypto symlinks on Fedora

Fedora does not have the 1.0.0 versions of the .so files, so the
existing symlink step isn't working correctly.  This change looks
for any 1.0.* versions of libssl and libcrypto, so we shouldn't have
to update it for every minor version bump but it also won't
unintentionally pull in an incompatible version.

Change-Id: I8402d05be684337df70d8f48e6d2ac1ecc69eaf7
Related-Bug: #1304629
(cherry picked from commit adf7b081ee0074def5a36d5c63c686ef90a4d7f1)

commit_message:
Add specific doc build option to tox

Add a doc venv to align with other OpenStack projects. Useful
for doc testing locally.

As part of this change we also update the devtest.sh docs
generation example to be a bit more generic so as not to
refer to a specific release (which may or may not
have the new tox -edocs command).

Change-Id: I37771db339d864b2b938d1c02d15d38b07093493
(cherry picked from commit 0f828a7e6c7dbb3265a0461451b2b5da094f3400)

commit_message:
Fix ssl link for percona on i686

The ssl link for percona on i686 references the incorrect directory
(i686 instead of i386).

Change-Id: Id7397107465854eaf4d2de5c12b4a202e4723516
(cherry picked from commit c73b0a55c1c735c0dced42803ded42e9db6e88b1)

Change URL to get-pip.py

raw.github.com is redirecting to here and github all of a sudden has
started rejecting the redirected request from curl on fedora.

Closes-Bug: #1312962

(cherry picked from commit f23f2ec7ef493f9fda6875128952c7664cd3e462)

commit_message:
libvirt: fully parse PCI addresses to integer data type

When parsing node device XML, the PCI addresses were left in their
string form, which is unhelpful for later code wishing to use their
raw values. Fully parse them to the integer form instead.

Blueprint: virt-driver-get-available-resources-object
Change-Id: I46b9c33e08122eb7c28601752ecfc652e09175c3

commit_message:
Fix token issue after auth changeup

IssueToken.take_action() was missed in updating the structure of
the ClientManager.

Also, TOKEN_WITH_TENANT_ID in v3 is just wrong...

Closes-Bug: #1383396

Change-Id: If2dd82a26af1d743ee9df73e0c1aebce497bf22e

commit_message:
libvirt: use six.text_type when setting text node value in guest xml

Trying to spawn an instance with a unicode name using the libvirt driver
fails with a UnicodeDecodeError because the value is cast to str().

The fix is to use six.text_type for the cast.

Closes-Bug: #1382318

Conflicts:
        nova/virt/libvirt/config.py

Change-Id: I4628b94459a3c1e757d388916f1268884cb02038
(cherry picked from commit 73fcf4628089dd784889062e916b80d3fc9988a2)

commit_message:
Add more input validation of bdm param in server creation

Adds a check to ensure that block_device_mapping is a list and
return 400 Bad Request rather than 500 as currently happens.

Change-Id: I30551bcbb7d658734da158dbb8dd7d825c526896
Closes-Bug: 1379973

commit_message:
libvirt: remove pointless HostState class

Now that the get_host_stats method is removed, the only user
of the HostState class passes 'refresh=True' every time. Given
this, there is no point in caching the data in the HostState
class. Instead just populate the data directly in the
get_available_resources method.

Blueprint: virt-driver-get-available-resources-object
Change-Id: I19c391a1bae27c3e8d891ecf77ceeaf170299be3

commit_message:
Allow headers to be retreived with GET bodies

If a Resource.get* call with include_headers is set to True, the
response body will include header keys and values.

Change-Id: I49390715b0e39d5ca279dad85e3bed786e975b10

commit_message:
Handle booleans that are strings in APIs

Coerces string values to a boolean only when the prop is given a
type=BoolStr. BoolStr only accepts string words, no shortened values,
synonyms or integer values. When no acceptable value is found a
TypeError or ValueError is raised. Setters and Constructor calls
validate the attribute value as a fail-fast behavior.

Change-Id: I382426325522227a83ec5234c5116da97e71cfa2
Closes-Bug: #1365724

commit_message:
Use jsoncheck in doctest

This patch makes doctest use jsoncheck.

It offers:
- more helpful syntax error messages (courtesy of demjson)
- additional niceness checks for standardized formatting

Change-Id: Id92c43daeb6ee17ed03052b3c9b92cbf60f3f4a5
blueprint modularize-doctest

commit_message:
BSN: Add context to backend request for debugging

Include the request context with calls to the backend
Big Switch controllers to assist with event correlation
and debugging object provenance.

This also removes mutable objects from default arguments
in some of the server manager function definitions that
were interferring with the new use of the headers dict.

Note: The commit to master stripped out an auth_token
field, however that logic is removed because Icehouse
did not have the auth_token to begin with.

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/bigswitch/servermanager.py
	neutron/tests/unit/bigswitch/test_servermanager.py
	neutron/tests/unit/ml2/drivers/test_bigswitch_mech.py

Closes-Bug: #1364696
Change-Id: I5b80b1596cc145742457b3603cbcd67f6e0d9f36
(cherry picked from commit 50c65d16bee8e6e46840f232519e92d9ba9989b4)

commit_message:
Set SWIFT_TEMPURL_KEY for ironic agent_ssh job

This job enables swift temp URLs but does not set a key, causing the
it to fail at a read_password prompt.

Change-Id: I97608813a4cb42896df628b13f2674ee6bfa15a7

looks good, just a question:  How will this work with the newly proposed timeout client socket timeout patch?  In that patch a connection will be closed if idle for a configurable amount of time (default 900 seconds).  It looks like this one will stop retrying after 250 seconds + overhead.  What happens to the threads handling this if the client timeout is lowered below 250 seconds?'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2014-10-16 04:25:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm interested in the same question which John asked above."}, {'account_id': 10485, 'date': '2014-10-16 06:09:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi John/Zhi Yan,

IMO 'client_socket_timeout' patch 'https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119132/' will not effect the above patch because 'client_socket_timeout' patch allows closing idle client connections after a period of time but retry decorator is continuously retrying on 'image_destroy' method and client connection is not idle in this case.

I followed following steps to test this scenario:

1. Applied patch 'https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119132/' on this retry on db_deadlock patch.
2. Set 'client_socket_timeout' to 60 seconds in glance-api.conf and glance-registry.conf.
3. Updated retry count to 500 in retry decorator and add a delay of 1 sec in 'image_destroy' method.
4. Raise db_exception.DBDeadlock to simulate the exception.
5. Restart glance-api and glance-registry services.
6. Delete an image.
7. It retries 500 times to call 'image_destroy' even after exceeding the client_socket_timeout (60 sec).

Please let me know your suggestions."}, {'account_id': 11356, 'date': '2014-10-16 13:32:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

That behavior looks good to me. Retrying means the connection is not idle.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-10-16 13:49:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The socket timeout patch times out the connection from the glance client to the glance api. This isn't the same as the socket from the (say) glance registry to the glance db.

I think the effect of the new timeout triggering while the db call is being retried would be the same as the current behaviour if, for example, the client died unexpectedly.

It's probably worth testing what that is. (This type of decorator is already being used so it's possible we could hit a dead client scenario with the existing code.)"}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-10-17 09:39:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I think John's query is a good one, and we should look into it, but I don't see it as a reason to block this patch which fixes a known issue (and doesn't introduce any known new failure modes) and is consistent with the existing wrapper around _image_update."}, {'account_id': 8127, 'date': '2014-10-17 10:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2014-10-17 10:24:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Agreed to move forward first. Let's do more check on client stock timeout case, and do a separated MP if needed."}, {'account_id': 6493, 'date': '2014-10-17 18:53:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Makes sense.  Stuart's point is taken as well.  Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-17 18:53:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Can not delete images if db deadlock occurs

Glance api returns 500 Internal Server Error, if db deadlock occurs
in glance-registry for some reason while deleting an image.

Added retry on image_destroy when db deadlock occures which will again
try to delete the image from database.

Closes-bug: 1378215
Change-Id: Ifad403e363daf368e846b5b6838432a7bedbe81a

commit_message:
Write image directly to disk

Write image directly to disk by telling qemu-img that the output
file is the disk. Still uses O_DIRECT directly within qemu-img.

This avoids the need to have a huge amount of system memory to be
able to deploy an image that contains a huge disk.

The only feature left behind by that commit is the 64K block size.

Change-Id: If60bcd82581b2ea76c4acbc3eaa3f317d2ee6590

commit_message:
Fix DB2 column 'id' autoincrement issue

After installing heat against DB2, we can't insert data in table
event, the reason is that "event_table.c.tmp_id.alter(
sqlalchemy.Integer, autoincrement=True)" can't make sense after
above "tmp_id=>id" transformation, Now need work around it.

Change-Id: I50025fc5db87d458e660d42c773d799fc36f1b27
Closes-Bug: #1316041

   'table-name': 'example_table',
   'id-col': 'id_col',
   'selection-type': 'DOT_SELECTOR',
   'field-translators': ({'fieldname': 'field1', 'col': 'col1',

of (123, 456).

This change adds 4 conversion types HDICT, VDICT, LIST, and VALUE.  The
container types (HDICT, VDICT, and LIST) can recursively contain conversion
types.

commit_message:
Use declarative description to drive datasource data conversion

Use a declarative description to describe the translation from a python object
to Congress table rows.  For example, the translator:

 {'translation-type': 'HDICT',
   'table-name': 'example_table',
   'id-col': 'id_col',
   'selection-type': 'DOT_SELECTOR',
   'field-translators': ({'fieldname': 'field1', 'col': 'col1',
                          'translator': {'translation-type': 'VALUE'}},
                         {'fieldname': 'field2', 'col': 'col2',
                          'translator': {'translation-type': 'VALUE'})}

Would create a single table named 'example_table' with three columns:
  (id_col, col1, col2).

Given an object {'field1': 123, 'field2': 456}, the translator would produce a
row for table 'example_table' containing (id, 123, 456) where id is the hash
of (123, 456).

This change adds 4 conversion types HDICT, VDICT, LIST, and VALUE.  The
container types (HDICT, VDICT, and LIST) can recursively contain conversion
types.

Change-Id: I9f93e6e81cc7cf010a296a9a9ea784f0425ff720

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-01 13:46:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The point of this is to release this new resource type at least one release before we remove HARestarter so that users can start getting HARestarter out of their templates early.  I am suggesting this because there seems to be a real danger that HARestarter will have to be removed in the same release that introduces the first viable alternative.

AutoScalingHealthGroup is intended to be general enough for the current users of HARestarter but not so general to risk not being implementable in the future that lacks HARestarter.  I know of no current user of HARestarter that could not use AutoScalingHealthyGroup instead.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-10-01 17:40:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

It would be nicer to have some change we could make to the regular autoscaling group that would continue to be useful even when convergence arrives, rather than another weird resource type that would itself have to be deprecated.

e.g. having some way to force the autoscaling group to delete a particular member based on an alarm would be generically useful for stuff like selective scale-down, even after we have convergence.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-03 04:37:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

Replies in-line to in-line comments.  Plus the following.

Today Ceilometer has a dismaying limitation: an alarm action is only a URL, it can not include an HTTP request body.  Correspondingly, when an HARestarter's webhook is hit, the action code does not look in the HTTP request body for any user data (just generic stuff).  These imply that today there has to be a distinct webhook for every health-maintained resource.  I hope for a better future, but am told it is not imminent.  Which means that an interface that exposes the existing webhooks is poorly future-proofed, and a little delay will not help.

However, I think your broader point is actionable.  Rather than introducing a new resource type that maintains health, we could change the existing OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup to optionally exhibit the behavior that I proposed here be new for a subclass.  That is, we could give OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup an optional parameter that is the name of an attribute of the member type that reveals the member's OS::Neutron::PoolMember.  If and only if that optional name is provided to an instance of OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup, the asg will engage in the health maintenance behavior proposed here.  As for the timeout_in_minutes, that could be another optional parameter that validation allows only if the pool member attribute name is supplied."}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-03 05:10:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The problem this is trying to solve is the lack of a commitment to a transition period in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121824/'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-03 13:55:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

When an OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup --- which is necessarily a resource (call it R) in some parent stack (call it X) --- scales in or out, do the dependents of R in X get UPDATEd?  Yes, R can have dependents that need updating --- remember that R has attributes.

Suppose that X is itself a resource (call it S) in a parent stack (call it W).  If R scales and this changes the outputs of X, do the dependents of S get UPDATEd?

If either answer is "no", I would argue it is a bug.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-07 06:52:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Angus made the following remarks on the older spec, which (I think) apply equally well to this one because he was (I think) addressing interface rather than implementation.

Mike I am not a fan of this as-is. But it's good to get some ideas out there. I think what is wrong with harestarter is it's "target" is not necessarily a stack. To follow what the autoscaling does better would be to have (highly abbreviated):

resources:
hapolicy:
type: a-better-ha-restarter
properties:
target: {get_resource: ha-thing}
some_alarm:
type: Alarm
properties:
alarm_actions: [{get_attr: [hapolicy, AlarmUrl]}]
ha-thing:
type: HaResource
properties:
resource:
type: server_and_some_stuff.yaml
properties:
image: dude
flavor: yum

The main thing is to "container-ize" the resources been restarted *and* force the harestarter to only point to one of these resource types.

It would be good to get some feedback from others tho'.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-07 07:08:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I deliberately proposed a rather narrow interface for a variety of reasons.  One reason I did not expose something like a-better-ha-restarter resource type is that I was warned that there may be no close analogue of OS::Heat::HARestarter once Convergence has arrived.

A little more broadly: I chose to expose essentially no implementation details, so that we would not find ourselves in a tight spot in the future (not having a crystal ball and all).  I tried to propose an interface that talks only about function, without detailing how it gets done.  Yes, that makes the proposal limited in scope.  Even so, it is pretty broad.  It is enough for the users of HARestarter that I know of, so I think the scope limitation is not a problem.

In fact, following Zane's line of thinking, I could even argue that merging this functionality into the modern scaling groups is the "other shoe" that we have been waiting to drop ever since we introduced scaling groups whose member type is not necessarily a Compute instance: with a fully general member type, a scaling group resource type can not be expected to understand how to test the member's health (including application function, not just resource existence) --- what is needed is an explicit connection to something that *does* know how to test a member's health.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-07 07:09:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Again, the obsoleted spec is at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/124620/

There you can read Angus' remark with proper white space."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-10-08 11:26:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Agree with Zane that ideally this would just be an enhancement of the existing AutoScalingGroup. This would be of general benefit for ASG, so it would be more than an interim new resource type. From your comment in reply to Zane's it seem you think this is doable, right?"}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-08 17:16:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Yes, I think that is doable.  I would have code for it now, except that my attention is being focused on other stuff right now.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-11 18:08:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Oh dang, see https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1326721

The bug description is wrongly worded, it describes a fix rather than the bug.  The bug is that Heat can not create an alarm that filters Samples based on anything (such as resource ID) other than metadata.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-10-13 00:47:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think this needs more discussion - Summit session? https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/kilo-heat-summit-topics'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-13 02:50:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

Answered the last of the outstanding comments inline.  Preparing code, along the lines discussed: adding optional health maintenance to OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup, building on my fix to https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1326721 .

Angus, if you'd like to indicate the outstanding issues that concern you, I'd be interested.

Thanks"}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-13 02:58:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

Revised and extended one remark inline.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-13 06:34:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127884/ for an implementation that is intended to follow what I think the discussion has converged on.  Yeah, the spec needs to be updated.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-14 22:31:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-14 22:34:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Mike: Would it be possible to remove all the repeated statements about HARestarter and how we got to this requirement, and just focus on the actual feature, e.g specific details of how we can modify AutoScalingGroup to meet your needs?

The deprecation strategy of HARestarter is really unrelated to this spec, other than that it may provide a solution for folks to migrate to, so I for one find all the relentless references to HARestarter as something of a distraction to the issue at hand.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-15 20:37:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-15 20:38:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I tried to refocus as I think Steven Hardy suggested.  Even so, HARestarter shows up as part of the problem --- but not really the same problem.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-15 20:42:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/56/124656/4/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/37289ac/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 59s'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-10-17 10:33:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(5 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-17 22:07:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

So, to clarify, we need a replacement for deprecated HARestarter, so you're proposing replacing it with a nested template solution based on.... HARestarter!

Doh!

I'm totally +1 on addressing this requirement but there has to be a better way than this.

I think the general pattern sounds fine (Neutron health metric, ceilometer alarm, ASG), it's just the AutoScalingGroup resource implementation which I personally view as completely not the direction we want to be headed."}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-18 21:12:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(6 comments)

Replies to Thomas in-line.  For Steven:

Are you objecting only to the implementation here, or also to the interface?  I think the interface here is reasonably good, and is something we could be willing to maintain in the long term --- as the implementation improves when the necessary other work gets done.

Do you know a better implementation that could be used today?  If so, can you please exhibit an outline?

Or maybe you are recommending an approach that can not be followed with today's code, but you hope the necessary gaps can be filled soon.  In that case I would also be interested in seeing an outline of the asg-with-health implementation in that anticipated future."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-20 08:10:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> Are you objecting only to the implementation here, or also to the interface?

It's mostly the implementation which I'm quite strongly opposed to."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-10-20 11:32:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2014-10-20 11:35:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

As a comment to Mike's and Steven's discussion: I think there are two major points here: (1) we need agreement on the interface, and (2) we need agreement on the implementation, right?

So (1) looks generally ok with me; we can talk about details regarding property naming etc.

Re (2), I think there is still some more discussion needed.

Does that distinction make sense, and if yes, is there consensus on at least (1)?"}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-20 14:56:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

One in-line reply to Thomas.  Also, overall, on the interface vs implementation thing:

If there are objections to the interface, I would like to understand them.  I have understood Thomas to make remarks about interface, and Steven to have made remarks about implementation plus one remark about the scope in the introductory paragraph.  That remark (if I understand it correctly) is not really challenging the scope, just challenging my statement of it.  Steven, if you have concerns about the interface, can you please help me understand them?

If there are objections to the initial implementation, I would like to see a viable alternative that works now.  I am happy to discuss better implementations for the future, but do not think they need to hold up acceptance of a change with an implementation that works currently.'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2014-10-21 10:39:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-21 12:33:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

> if you have concerns about the interface, can you please help me understand them?

My concern is that the interface may not make sense when we are in a position to remove this hack, either via coming up with a better pre-convergence solution, or via continuous convergence.

As Thomas Herve has mentioned, what you propose is already possible, we don't need to bake it into the resource implementation to make it more possible.

The main driver behind this does appear to be removing some inconvenient template boilerplate, rather than really implementing anything new, so as therve has asked, have you looked into putting the repeated stuff into a provider template?

Also, as mentioned by Thomas, the implicit dependency between the ASG and LB in your new interface is not ideal - I'd far rather we figured out a solution where "health" can be determined via a user-configurable alarm which can be triggered by anything (e.g an agent in the VM monitoring application health), not just the LB health monitor.

> I would like to see a viable alternative that works now.

Sure, so would I, but IMO it makes more long-term sense for the project if we work on identifying a viable, maintainable solution that can work soon (e.g in the Kilo timeframe), particularly given that this solution is already working for you, albeit via a different interface.'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-10-21 18:14:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yes, I tried to find a way to do it with a provider template, and could not.  Following are some of the difficulties I ran into.

* I can not write "resource_name: {get_param: resource_def}" in the resources section of a HOT.

* I can not write a template that reads the configured averaging period.

* I can not write a provider template that includes or omits a clause based on whether or what value the user gave to a property of the facade.  (OK, I have not implemented that part yet, but it is in the spec and should be added to the implementation.)

* I can not write a template that reads any clock or does arithmetic.  The implication is that I can not write a template that computes when the grace period for a given group member expires.  Ceilometer does not have the concept of a grace period built into its alarm concept, but it does allow the client to specify a start time (which the client has to calculate).  The concept of a grace period is not yet in this spec or implementation, but it needs to be added.

I am concerned about planning for automatic convergence of all resources.  The last time I asked about this, I was told that automatic convergence would first be implemented for scaling group members only, with automatic convergence for all resources happening later if at all.  I recall Angus' skepticism about automatically converging all resources, on the grounds that this would remove a level of control that users value.

I think that if Heat offers only a recreate webhook per member then the user will still have to code up a lot of boilerplate for the common case of reacting to determinations made for a Neutron PoolMember.  I completely agree that this should not be the only kind of health maintenance supported, but I think that maintaining health as determined for Neutron PoolMembers should be available with succinct template source --- both now and into the grand and glorious future.  Introducing this concept now does not prevent us from later introducing something that is more general but requires more boilerplate to use in common cases.'}]

The motivation for introducing this change is the lack of positive
affirmation in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121824/ that there
will be a reasonable transition period during which both
``OS::Heat::HARestarter`` and some newer better alternative are
available.  You can also see in the discussion in
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/heat/2014/heat.2014-10-01-12.01.log.html
a desire to keep open the possibility that HARestarter will be removed
without a 1 release transition period.  The proposed change is to
introduce, at least 1 release before HARestarter is removed, a wrapper
that (a) obscures the use of HARestarter, (b) has an interface that is
narrow enough that we are confident that it will be reasonable to
implement in the not clearly seen future, (c) has enough functionality
that current users of HARestarer can use the wrapper instead.  In
addition to those three sharp criteria, there is also a desire to make
the wrapper be something that we would be comfortable with users using
indefinitely, not just to smooth over a transition away from
HARestarter.  This enables current users to switch to using the
wrapper over a transtion period of at least 1 release before
HARestarter is removed.  Once users have made this transition, we can
remove HARestarter and change the implementation behind the wrapper
simultaneously without disturbing users.

This is the spec for
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/autoscaling-healthy-group

Change-Id: I9a76b5e7610c7f5b6f798ea7e03788f8a731157e
'}, {'created': '2014-10-15 20:37:12.000000000', 'message': "Adding Optional Health to OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup

Currently it is possible to write a Heat template that prescribes a
set of virtual resources with health maintenance, using the health
determinations made by Neutron's LBaaS.  While it is possible, it is
ugly.  The user is required to write a bunch of mechanism for each
thing that the user wants maintained.  There is no way for a user or a
cloud operator to write a template resource (formerly known as a
provider template) that implements this abstraction.  In contrast,
some other IaaS platforms have health maintenance as a built-in part
of the functionality of their scaling groups.  The proposed change is
to generalize ``OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup`` so that it can optionally
maintain member health as determined by LBaaS.  Note that LBaaS has
health checking functionality that does not require any actual
application traffic to be load balanced.  The goal here is not to
attempt fully general health maintenance, only to cover common cases
--- with an interface that we think is reasonable to use and does not
paint ourselves into a corner regarding future implementations.  It
just so happens that all of the users I know to be wanting health
maintenance will be satisfied with this generalization of
``OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup`` --- and be happy to use it instead of
repeating a bunch of mechanism using ``OS::Heat::HARestarter`` and/or
other stuff --- supposing the relevant schedulers do not keep putting
guests on broken hosts (which is really a separate problem).

This is the spec for
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/autoscaling-healthy-group

commit_message:
Adding Optional Health to OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup

Currently it is possible to write a Heat template that prescribes a
set of virtual resources with health maintenance, using the health
determinations made by Neutron's LBaaS.  While it is possible, it is
ugly.  The user is required to write a bunch of mechanism for each
thing that the user wants maintained.  There is no way for a user or a
cloud operator to write a template resource (formerly known as a
provider template) that implements this abstraction.  In contrast,
some other IaaS platforms have health maintenance as a built-in part
of the functionality of their scaling groups.  The proposed change is
to generalize ``OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup`` so that it can optionally
maintain member health as determined by LBaaS.  Note that LBaaS has
health checking functionality that does not require any actual
application traffic to be load balanced.  The goal here is not to
attempt fully general health maintenance, only to cover common cases
--- with an interface that we think is reasonable to use and does not
paint ourselves into a corner regarding future implementations.  It
just so happens that all of the users I know to be wanting health
maintenance will be satisfied with this generalization of
``OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup`` --- and be happy to use it instead of
repeating a bunch of mechanism using ``OS::Heat::HARestarter`` and/or
other stuff --- supposing the relevant schedulers do not keep putting
guests on broken hosts (which is really a separate problem).

This is the spec for
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/heat/+spec/autoscaling-healthy-group

Change-Id: I9a76b5e7610c7f5b6f798ea7e03788f8a731157e

commit_message:
Add keystone v3 CLI support

This change allows user domains and tenant/project domains to
be specified through CLI.  This is necessary because keystone
v2 API is deprecatedas of Icehouse.

Change-Id: I50187a12b73777118ee77590202746b272ecc030

commit_message:
Add ansible puppet module

Ansible puppet module executes
provided manifest and verifies that it is executed correctly
by parsing last_run_summary report

Should be placed in /usr/share/ansible to be
plugged in ansible core

Implements blueprint granular-deployment-based-on-tasks

Change-Id: I516aa9529a7c87fed4b1f950f98e7a030dc2839e

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-27 07:30:49.000000000', 'message': 'Change stunnel priority and binding addresses

1. Priority change is required to start stunnel4 before haproxy
2. Accept binding address changed to allow binding on vip for haproxy
3. Connect address changed to forward traffic only to 127.0.0.1

Change-Id: I7c85f94da377b6d694435a5d64e61be3698587d7
'}, {'created': '2014-05-28 08:59:21.000000000', 'message': 'Change stunnel priority and binding addresses

Priority change is required to start stunnel4 before haproxy

stunnel configuration refactoring will allow next configuration:

- stunnel
    accept_ip: 192.0.2.24
    connect_ip: 127.0.0.1
    ports:
        - name: horizon
          accept: 443
          connect: 80

This is required for ha story, so stunnel will accept connections only
on local-ipv4 address and connect to 127.0.0.1 where service will listen

Change-Id: I7c85f94da377b6d694435a5d64e61be3698587d7
'}]
commit_message:
Change stunnel priority and binding addresses

Priority change is required to start stunnel4 before haproxy

stunnel configuration refactoring will allow next configuration:

- stunnel
    accept_ip: 192.0.2.24
    connect_ip: 127.0.0.1
    ports:
        - name: horizon
          accept: 443
          connect: 80

This is required for ha story, so stunnel will accept connections only
on local-ipv4 address and connect to 127.0.0.1 where service will listen

Change-Id: I7c85f94da377b6d694435a5d64e61be3698587d7

commit_message:
Columns needs to be non-nullable for DB2

For DB2, we can not create constraints over nullable
columns. This patch makes some related changes to
035_event_uuid_to_id.py for Heat.

Change-Id: I6d251fa503848e03603a13ecb742d4915f0f6972
Closes-Bug: #1328045
Co-authored-by: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Libvirt: Always teardown lxc container on destroy

This fixes a bug where shutting down a libvirt-lxc based instance
would leak its underlying nbd device. This was happening because
_teardown_container would only get called if the domain was
present. After this fix, _teardown_container will always get called
on a destroy, which ensures the nbd device gets disconnected.

Change-Id: I8d0044fd038fef80568c6c86e34719ef679aa890
Closes-Bug: #1367363

It was unclear to me when ipmitool output becomes unparsable, here's explanation from eglynn:
"if the 'Senor Reading' is missing from the dict because one sensor is unavailable"
"due to the setup/configuration of the individual IPMI interface"
List of default ipmi pollsters is defined as stevedore entry points in https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/4683a15b3f49fed3f78fa41a58a9a354b176b85e/setup.cfg#L124
and IPMI might not be providing them all.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-21 12:34:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-21 12:43:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Alan it's not so much that the readings are not parseable but rather that one of a few outcomes from the parsing happens:

* there is no sensor reading (uncommon)
* the sensor reading has a value that is not of an expected form (e.g. can't be treated as float) (uncommon)
* is for a type of sensor that the receiver does not handle (common)

This is outcome is the result of the fact that the receiver is coded for specific sensors rather than to generically or declaratively receive (and store) any sensor data. That's by design, but I remain unconvinced that it is correct."}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:39:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So this a workaround for now and there might be a followup fix later?'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:01:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> So this a workaround for now and there might be a followup fix later?

No, not really.

The backported code is to bring the ipmi-agent code to the desired/designed behavior, which is to skip unknown sensor data in a message, rather than skipping an entire message.

That behavior was designed into the Ironic agent which essentially says "ipmitool can produce a lot of data but we only want some of it". That "some of it" is temperature, fan speed, current and voltage. Everything else, by design, is dropped.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-21 17:37:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+2

commit_message:
Handle poorly formed individual sensor readings

ipmitool returns a series of multiple readings per run. Some of
these readings may be of a form that parser code cannot handle. The
desired behavior in this case is for the single reading to be
dropped and for parsing to continue. This change ensures that
behavior by continuing through the loop instead of allowing
exceptions to cause the loop to exit.

Tests have been added which verify the correct behavior.

Note that though there was an opportunity to log each skipped
reading this would lead to a very large number of log messages as
many or even most samples from ipmitool are not parsed.

Change-Id: I6a3193d5a6e12c69ca5c548e5fb58d8bc9646348
Closes-Bug: #1381600
(cherry picked from commit 8323cfe92af2ad27f6611be0a6887cac12b2c630)

commit_message:
mock.assert_called_once() is not a valid method

mock.assert_called_once() is a no-op that tests nothing. Instead
mock.assert_called_once_with() should be used (or use
assertEqual(1, mock_obj.call_count) if you don't want to check
parameters).

Borrowed HACKING rule from Davanum Srinivas's nova patch to
prevent it from appearing again.

Change-Id: Idac1d3c89c07e13c9a209663f4e557fcb7547821
Closes-Bug: #1365751
Closes-Bug: #1300265

commit_message:
Make docs build - drop man page option

The man page option was breaking the docs build, since we don't expect
anyone to install this git repo and require a man page, don't build any
man pages.

Change-Id: I50b044c36cb4ec0b76da9dca1feefe0d9614fb7f
