commit_message:
Remove duplicate hook 00-disable-apt-recommends

A recent commit into the openstack/diskimage-builder project
disallows overriding of hooks.
(Ic2c46835b27c9319f7a889ffd0ccf3f5ccc1f0cd)

A duplicate hook (00-disable-apt-recommends) has existed 
in the trove image elements, and is now causing image 
builds to fail. This duplicate hook should be removed.

Change-Id: I898721b72b195d3a4d8be8d4bc5363f16249ed85
Closes-Bug: #1383467

commit_message:
Re-submitting OSSN 25 concerning Swift/Glance public images

Complete re-write adding more details.

Added section on root cause describing public label in Swift vs Glance,
as well as more details on fixes and their possible impacts.

Modified the config file and variable formatting per OSSN markup
standards, and smoothed over 'Summary' and 'Discussion' sections.

Expanded the 'delay_auth_decision' configuration item, clarified
remarks around auditing and configs, and specified this is in
multi-tenant mode only.

Split 'not use Swift' section into alternate back end storage section
and recommending Swift not in multi-tenant mode.

Change-Id: Ic61b2fa276a21e1617f90a3ce64f9e5972ff24bb
Closes-Bug: #1354512

commit_message:
Logging configuration reload

Parameters which are configured by the master process before launching
he child processes need special handling.

Here we handle the reload of all logging related parameters on SIGHUP.

Change-Id: I521d91fc7c69f609ed53aab82dd7880978c492ef

[{'created': '2014-10-15 11:30:48.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Driver VendorPassthru to support different HTTP methods

Add support for different HTTP methods when invoking the Driver
VendorPassthru.

This work will be needed for the iPXE driver because iPXE scripts will
issue GETs to the API, but this work is generic enough to be separated
in its own patch.

NEED UNITTESTS

Change-Id: If02e65f7e4fc7c15af68718eed64fef059742b41
'}]
commit_message:
WIP: Driver VendorPassthru to support different HTTP methods

Add support for different HTTP methods when invoking the Driver
VendorPassthru.

This work will be needed for the iPXE driver because iPXE scripts will
issue GETs to the API, but this work is generic enough to be separated
in its own patch.

NEED UNITTESTS

Change-Id: If02e65f7e4fc7c15af68718eed64fef059742b41

commit_message:
Add several insecure-related attributes

This change adds some attributes into the cookbook so
that they are configurable. They are mainly to configure
for glance_api_insecure and neutron_api_insecure in nova.conf.
It also makes neutron_url and neutron_admin_auth_url to be
prefixed with scheme(http or https).

Change-Id: If6d50a6963b47ee0983ecc71087414ab7c366623
Closes-Bug: #1381599

commit_message:
Use "berks vendor" instead of "berks install"

Berkshelf 3.x has been out of beta for a while and the install
command is no longer supported.  This is a quick update to the
documentation to make the bootstrap commands work.

Change-Id: I777a95d868ff51bc26ca40a314fa86df01beb660

commit_message:
Correct command line args in knife node command

Use "knife node run_list add" instead of "knife node add run_list".

Change-Id: I6e21bcafb9bcccd8d2fd886c451df239814a4893

commit_message:
Fix missing log-file arg for n-agents OCF

W/o this patch, neutron agents misplace their
logs to neutron-server.log file.
In order to fix it:
* use --log-file explicitely
  in OCF scripts for n-agents.
* remove redirection to log file to not duplicate
  the log records

Closes-bug: #x1371629

Change-Id: If209c66b39c1b51f4970b786604eb95ec38ff74e
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

[{'created': '2014-10-09 01:16:34.000000000', 'message': 'Set <host> in cinder.conf to rbd:<pool> for RBD backend

Cinder volume can only be managed by a cinder-volume process that has <host>
configuration variable value matching <os-vol-host-attr:host> attribute of the
volume.

By default, host of a cinder-volume service is set to its hostname, which means
that if one controller is lost, none of its volumes can be managed by
cinder-volume processes on other controllers. This makes sense for Cinder LVM,
but not for RBD or other shared backends.

This commit sets <host> to the same value on all controllers when RBD backend

commit_message:
Set <host> in cinder.conf to rbd:<pool> for RBD backend

Cinder volume can only be managed by a cinder-volume process that has <host>
configuration variable value matching <os-vol-host-attr:host> attribute of the
volume.

By default, host of a cinder-volume service is set to its hostname, which means
that if one controller is lost, none of its volumes can be managed by
cinder-volume processes on other controllers. This makes sense for Cinder LVM,
but not for RBD or other shared backends.

This commit sets <host> to the same value on all controllers when RBD backend
is enabled, so that any controller can manage RBD backed volumes created by any
other controller.

Change-Id: I47161796dbb817eab026402760799bee24371863

commit_message:
Inherit roles for create_trust_context()

This change the default value of the option
'trusts_delegated_roles' to []. And delegate all of
the trustor roles when create the trust unless
user set the option to subset roles.

Change-Id: I3f1b70b78b91bfac9af5fadb71140679b208c999
Closes-bug: #1376562

commit_message:
Make it possible to get the request_id from python clients

This is so callers can extract the request_id for tracing
and associating with events (this is especially useful in Heat
where there are a lot of client calls and one needs to map
a Heat action to the underlying service requests).

Partial-bug: #1342922
Change-Id: I6c60946c8fcdb44f1b18733296982bf0d32334dc

The whole script is run with "-e", disable exit on error during the
read. Otherwise the script will fail directly.

commit_message:
Base for CLI tool profiling

This patch implements a simple wrapper for
profiling different CLI commands and saving
the results.

cProfile is used as a profiling tool; results
are saved in both prof and DOT-graph formats.

In order to enable profiling NAILGUN_LOAD_TEST
variable should be set.

Change-Id: I57216cdd067d3de256caf41d631998b6c5884a02

commit_message:
Base for CLI tool profiling

This patch implements a simple wrapper for
profiling different CLI commands and saving
the results.

cProfile is used as a profiling tool; results
are saved in both prof and DOT-graph formats.

In order to enable profiling NAILGUN_LOAD_TEST
variable should be set.

Change-Id: I843f556fbe1560f7fb418d9c671b9338fa388529

commit_message:
Updates to EC design spec

Mainly around the PUT and reconstructor section topics:

- multi-phase phase commit conversation concept
- reconstructor key concepts
- local data file cleanup
- rebalance and handoff reversion
- misc typo fixes
- additional info on GET handling of prior partial PUTs

Change-Id: I602dcd5f445bf5642c0bc15a6dd30dd40591d4ae
Implements: blueprint swift-ec

commit_message:
add back the deleted parameter in the configuration group tests

with the parameter deleted we can not rerun the tests on the same
instance without clearing the datstore_configuration_paramters
table and reloading the params. This will readd the parameter
that is deleted.

Change-Id: Ic1cdfa416a14c42b6c4323612ec609915224b6ee
Closes-Bug: #1379083

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-10-16 00:56:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)

ekotowski, it is very unlikely that I fully understand the change you are proposing. so these questions are based on that incomplete or flawed understanding of your proposed change.

Is there a benefit to changing _validate_configuration() and passing it config_rules which have to now be obtained by the caller? I see now a couple of new lines of identical code in the two callers, each calling load_parameters() and passing a potentially larger parameter to _validate_configuration than if _validate_configuration obtained it as it did in the old code. If you feel that fetching it one parameter at a time in _validate_configuration is inefficient, why not have _validate_configuration obtain it the way the callers are doing?

Your proposed change appears to make configurations case insensitive. Is that intended? Is that within the scope of this bug? I'm not suggesting that it is a requirement that this be eliminated, I just noticed no mention of this in the bug or the comments but I did see it n the code.

There appears to a subtle change in behavior of _validate_configuration() that may or may not be a good thing. Suppose _validate_configuration() was invoked for a datastore which does not support configuration groups, and further assume that it was invoked with values = None. The old code would throw no exception, the new code will. Is this intended? Is this a good thing?

Why is the exception being caught in tests/api/configurations.py changing from NotFound to UnprocessableEntity? I don't see why the thrown exception should change.

I don't like the change from 404 to 422

A part of the change requested in the bug is that the message should be more clear and the example of auto_increment_offset is provided. I see no code that implements that request.

The other tests have large blocks of code that are repeated; some scope for reducing lines of code.

-1 because I don't think the change completely addresses the bug, nor do I like (nor see the rationale) for changing from 404 to 422. It may even break the API in a way in which we don't want to."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-10-16 00:58:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I was wrong in earlier comment when I said:

A part of the change requested in the bug is that the message should be more clear and the example of auto_increment_offset is provided. I see no code that implements that request.

There does appear to be a section of code that does this. Sorry.'}, {'account_id': 13355, 'date': '2014-10-16 01:49:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(6 comments)

I updated _validate_configuration to pass in the config_rules in order to be able to unit test all of the validation logic without relying on the integration tests/running a Fake DB. 

The case insensitive portion was to keep parity with load_parameters_by_name call. I have created a new rules based dictionary based on the name and wanted a case insensitive lookup vs calling into the database for each paramater.

-404 vs 422 
Updated this because the original intention of the method was to throw a 422 for parameter validation, but the load_paramater_by_name was raising 404, thus never hitting the previous "if not rule check" from line 199 of service.py. 404 is also an incorrect status code for parameter value validation. 404 should be reserved for resource and routing failures. Per the API change guidelines: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/APIChangeGuidelines I thought we can update an error response code to be more accurate.

The bug was addressed in two areas. Area 1: In servce.py line 206 I now check if there are no rules for this datastore and throw a different error. Previously we would throw a 404 regardless of if the rules database was empty for a specific datastore. Area 2: Line 216 in service.py Previously we would call load_parameter_by_name and it would always throw a 404, because I changed everything to create a rules dictionary based upon all the rules up front, it allows the code to hit the if key no in rules_lookup on line 216 and give a cleaned up error message.'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-10-16 10:27:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

ekotowski, thanks for the detailed response. I think I understand all of them. I particularly like the fact that you restructured the code (adding the config parameter) to facilitate unit testing. Great solution!

The last question you had re: duplication of code.

You are always invoking _validate_configuration with some value of max_connections, MagicMock() and some value for config_values, except the one case where you pass in data.

The framework will execute all tests (methods whose names don't begin with _). So, you can easily create a method called _test_config_parameters_inner() or some such thing and make it do the common stuff, and where your tests just invoke it with different values for max_connections and config_values.

your code could reduce to something like:

def _test_config_values(max_connections, data_version, config):
	if config is None:
		config = MagicMock()
		...

	if data_version is None:
		data_version = MagicMock()
		...

	self.assertRaises ...

Nice work!"}, {'account_id': 5293, 'date': '2014-10-20 09:28:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Configuration group checking 0 validation rules

- Updated _validate_configuration
    - Updated from querying the database every parameter to fetching
      all the db rules in one call and passing them as a parameter.
    - Check for empty rules set and raise a 422
    - New error response: Configuration groups are not supported for this
      datastore: mysql 5.5.
    - Updated invalid parameter to raise a 422 instead of the previous
      404 that the load_parameters_by_name call used to raise.
    - New error response message for parameter not found: "The configuration
      parameter auto_increment_offset is not support for this datastore:
      mysql 5.5.
- Added unit tests covering the _validation_configuration method
- Modified test_configurations_create_invalid_values integration test
  to handle new error status code 422 instead of 404 for invalid
  configuration values

Closes-Bug: 1367107
Change-Id: I9cc873745afe19336c1fe5ef35ffdd3efde127b3

commit_message:
labs: verify MD5 checksum for Linux ISO image

Verify the MD5 checksum of the Linux distribution's ISO image before
trying to use it. Image corruption happens, and the resulting problems
are not always easy to diagnose.

Change-Id: I92852a28392002d4fcd64898453086d5920d0ef1

- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron/bc425eb : SUCCESS in 59m 01s
- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-full http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-full/4b48590 : SUCCESS in 1h 04m 25s (non-voting)
- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-heat-slow http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-heat-slow/479d3b3 : SUCCESS in 22m 50s
- check-grenade-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-grenade-dsvm/8b1872a : SUCCESS in 38m 07s
- check-tempest-dsvm-full-havana http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full-havana/4111765 : FAILURE in 11m 11s (non-voting)
- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-havana http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-havana/7d5ff12 : FAILURE in 11m 50s (non-voting)
- check-tempest-dsvm-full-icehouse http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full-icehouse/537a250 : SUCCESS in 49m 14s
- check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-icehouse http://logs.openstack.org/43/114643/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron-icehouse/ed3b25a : SUCCESS in 57m 48s'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-22 04:35:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Why do the network commands always have to be different?

The KeyValueAppendAction is nice, but it doesn't provide the same user experience.  Now to specify more than one of a thing users have to remember which ones use multiple occurrences of an option and which ones use a single option with a singe comma-delimited value.  OSC is not going to do that."}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2014-08-26 13:53:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think this is unique to have an array of dicts to populate and I don't think this is a stretch for the user to use this.  Is it that much of a stretch to specify one --fixed-ips subnet=127.0.0.1/24,ip_address=127.0.0.3 or two?  There are lots of places in OSC where the user has to supply key value pairs.  Why not allow the user to repeat them?"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-26 19:51:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Terry, I clearly need to study exactly what is really being specified by the user here.  Nova and Neutron are full of semi-wrong nomenclature that I really do not want to propagate (ex, the use of 'CIDR' as a noun!).

The example you show: 

  --fixed-ips subnet=127.0.0.1/24,ip_address=127.0.0.3 

probably makes more sense to me as:

  --fixed-ips 127.0.0.3/24

the mask length is sufficient to be able to calculate the subnet address given the IP address.

I know that is probably not the general reply to using either comma-separated lists or multiple option occurrences, but it is a great example of where we need to spend some effort to produce a clean user interface and hide the nonsense."}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2014-08-27 18:56:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Okay, I made up that example and it is wrong.  The pairs that need to be associated with a port are a subnet_id and a fixed ip address.'}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2014-08-27 18:57:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The reason I changed it to subnet is so the user could enter subnet name or id.'}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2014-08-27 19:05:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The only alternative that comes to mind is adding a subcommand where you have to do one of them at a time.  Something like:

    os port add ip fixed <subnet> <ipaddress>
    os port add dhcp option key=value key=value key=value

As for dhcp options, I'm not sure how you would remove them.  I think the user would have to enter all the options because I don't think there is a key.

    os port remove ip fixed <subnet> <ipaddress>
    os port remove dhcp option key=value key=value key=value

The same would have to be done for subnet allocation pools and host routes.  I'm sure there are others."}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2014-10-21 12:27:19.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add demjson to requirements

Demjson is a library used by openstack-doc-tools for checking JSON
syntax. Its error messages are much more useful than the terse messages
provided by the standard json library.

For a unified diff of output with and without demjson (checking the same
set of JSON sample files), see:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/96358/

Change-Id: I2b353f3cf04f4e233d18dcda1160f50316c337d8

commit_message:
Cleanup mock patch without `with` part 3

A good idea because it makes the code easier to read to get rid of
the `with` using mock.patch and mock.patch.object in favor decorators,
where possible in the tests.

This patch affects `ironic/tests/*`.

Change-Id: I2e5669248db85bf43d577d5080f2b901912b7f6e

Old value 'updated_at' field returned after update

Fixed 'updated_at' field returned after resource was changed.
And updated tests `save` in tests/objects and tests/api/v1.

Change-Id: Id62a98ea627b90f87c6865c5cdc58af049f85879
Closes-Bug: #1281638

I really don't understand how any of the create_node stuff works in a generic / non-devstack environment. Someone's going to have to explain that."}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-06-20 02:25:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

There are two dependencies here, which I don't think are clear from the code, but also not a fault of this patch. I think a separate patch (or patches) should address these:

- Ironic provides an admin-only API. These tests are exercising the ability of an operator to manage the available physical resources which Ironic exposes (create/update/delete them). The particular attributes being supplied (cpu arch, amount of ram, etc) is arbitrary. It might help to abstract that more in the tests.

- This should ONLY be run when creating nodes with the "fake" driver. Creating nodes with a production driver (eg, pxe_ipmitool) will cause the ironic-conductor service to begin trying to manage physical hardware which does not exist. While ironic-conductor is designed to handle hardware failure, it will begin logging errors (eg, to indicate the hardware it should manage is not manageable).

In a production environment, enrolling non-existent hardware which then logs a bunch of errors as part of a test is going to be profoundly confusing to the ops team.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-20 02:25:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17: -Verified

commit_message:
Get rid object model `dict` methods part 5

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

This patch refactors usage of objects in `driver` and
driver unit tests.

Change-Id: I87493042aa387a1fbc9bf381951dd4e5c223d350
Partial-Bug: #1256260

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

"}, {'created': '2013-12-26 10:30:41.000000000', 'message': "Get rid object model `dict` methods part 2

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of

commit_message:
Get rid object model `dict` methods part 2

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

This patch refactors usage of objects in REST API and api unit tests.

Change-Id: Ib9977177b7fac6ea582abefe832c9b1f8c313010
Partial-Bug: #1256260

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

This patch refactors usage of objects in `conductor` and conductor
unit tests. And this patch captures some changes in the code `drivers`
and drivers unit tests

commit_message:
Get rid object model `dict` methods part 3

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

This patch refactors usage of objects in `conductor` and conductor
unit tests.

Change-Id: Ib1e3314a0b57ab7b57b5a9546a51fed83552dc79
Partial-Bug: #1256260

"}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24: Do not merge

This patchset addresses several unrelated things.

It is changing some dict-like accessors to explicit object access methods, and also refactoring some unit tests, and I think it is changing some functionality of the tests in the process.

It's also fixing a double-convert-from-db issue which is mentioned at the end of the commit message -- and is actually a real bug. Good catch! Please file a bug for that and split that change out. It should be a small change, and I think it's suitable to land it after I-3.

However, I am blocking this changeset as we approach the end of Icehouse development [*] because it is doing a lot more than necessary and is part of a large patch series which is not on the release path. Please re-submit this when Juno development opens.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "Rid of specific `dict` methods in object model

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behaviour of objects.
This behaviour will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

This patch refactors usage of objects in unit tests and api. It is only
changing the way object attributes are accessed in the api and object
unit tests.

Change-Id: I299a2211f7f3d72312e421e477c259e558e8fef1
Partial-Bug: #1256260
"}, {'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "Get rid object model `dict` methods part 1

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

This patch refactors usage of objects in ironic/objects and
objects unit tests.

This pice of code:
	1)Chassis._from_db_object(cls(), db_chassis)
        2)Conductor._from_db_object(cls(), db_obj)
	3)Node._from_db_object(cls(), db_node)
	4)Port._from_db_object(cls(), db_port)

was deleted because this a bug (not previously filled in Ironic) where
chassis, node, conductor and port has been converted from db object
twice (the first time in @objectify). And fixed this bug in current
patch.

Change-Id: I299a2211f7f3d72312e421e477c259e558e8fef1
Partial-Bug: #1256260

commit_message:
Get rid object model `dict` methods part 1

Currently unified object model supports dict-like behavior of objects.
This behavior will be removed in the future so it's necessary to
change Ironic's code to use object attributes as attributes instead of
dictionary keys.

This patch refactors usage of objects in ironic/objects and
objects unit tests.

Change-Id: I299a2211f7f3d72312e421e477c259e558e8fef1
Partial-Bug: #1256260

commit_message:
Add docs jobs for subunit2sql

During a recent patch series to update the subunit2sql documentation [1]
it was discovered that we were neglecting to build the docs as part of
the jobs run and we weren't publishing them like other projects. This
commit addresses all of these oversights.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:openstack-infra/subunit2sql+branch:master+topic:docs-update,n,z

Change-Id: Ia382148b11e7dec6f2da7ec47a0573ff40c76109

commit_message:
Don't stop update immediately on error

When an error occurs during a stack update operation,
don't immediately stop the operation. Instead,
wait up to 4 minutes for resources already in progress
to complete before forcibly cancelling them.

Change-Id: Ib089dbc675c519668a44d1b0e3214feca5079978
Closes-bug: #1381984

commit_message:
Functional test UpdateStackTest

This is a port of tempest.api.orchestration.stacks.stack_update
in an effort to reproduce the postgres race described in
bug #1370865.

Subsequent changes will create an experimental postgres check job and
a change to the test which runs test_stack_update_add_remove enough
times to triger the race.

Change-Id: I8aee26e29f242b11a5d3c8d56a859ae770be86c2
Related-Bug: #1370865

commit_message:
ProphetStor driver consistency group support

Implement ProphetStor driver support for the new consistency group
feature in Cinder Kilo.

Change-Id: Id2f7a93cabcf4f54215a035b3ad8d30ea5439297
Implements: blueprint prophetstor-consistency-group

commit_message:
Updated cache module and its dependencies

This is to avoid cache module dependency on timeutils that are now moved
to oslo.utils.

The following changes are included:

 * neutron/openstack/common/cache/_backends/memory.py
  6ff6b4b Switch oslo-incubator to use oslo.utils and remove old modules
  2bedce3 Fix MemoryBackend not purging item from _keys_expired on delete

 * neutron/openstack/common/cache/backends.py
  39625e1 Set pbr 'warnerrors' option for doc build

 * neutron/openstack/common/cache/cache.py
  9c683be fix small typo

 * neutron/openstack/common/lockutils.py
  5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
  7209975 Always log the releasing, even under failure
  bbb266c Clarify logging in lockutils
  942e1aa Use file locks by default again
  ac995be Fix E126 pep8 errors
  15b8352 Remove oslo.log from lockutils

Change-Id: I02cb4b2bc4b7bcba948e67cffdb8bd0219c89a29

Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-14 11:55:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

This seems like a good improvement over memcached.

Is there an option, either in this change or another, of allowing authentication? Would credentials passed via the connection url be workable?

I guess that in most situations people would have their redis servers firewalled, but in those cases where they do not (perhaps in a casual installation) auth might be a nice to have.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-10-14 17:18:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

So a few responses:

1. Don't run redis where it's publicly accessible, very bad ;) Redis really doesn't have any type of security (it has some basic auth but its not multi-tenant and keys and values aren't stored encrypted or anything). So really really avoid doing that. Zookeeper has better support for this type of security, https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/ZOOKEEPER/Zookeeper+and+SASL but redis really is a poormans zookeeper for a reason ;)

2. As for enabling redis sentinel. I think I'd prefer to do that in a later patchset, the current infra setup is barely working as is (if you look at the unittest runs this driver is only getting tested in py27 and not py26 or py33) so I'd rather have the basics in, and get redis sentinel running in infra first (if it's not running there really isn't a way to ensure that the code I put up works, outside of my local env). How is zaquar testing with redis-sentinel? That review/commit you pointed me at just seems to be testing connection uri's and not any actual functionality of redis-sentinel (the important thing to test imho)."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:29:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:35:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:42:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 20.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:47:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: Verified+1

'}, {'created': '2014-10-13 18:42:07.000000000', 'message': 'Add a redis driver

Add the foundations of a redis driver that can be used
along side the rest of the driver types.

Redis provides a few nice benefits that act as a poor
mans zookeeper.

- Durability (when setup with AOF mode).
- Consistent, note that this is still restricted to only
  one redis server, without the recently released redis (alpha)
  clustering > 1 server will not be consistent when partitions
  or failures occur (even redis clustering docs state it is
  not a fully AP or CP solution, which means even with it there
  will still be *potential* inconsistencies).
- Master/slave failover (when setup with redis sentinel), giving
  some notion of HA.

Further resources/links:

- http://redis.io/
- http://redis.io/topics/sentinel
- http://redis.io/topics/cluster-spec

Change-Id: I2d90be1afae98f40ff5c4230563e686b23d42c8f

commit_message:
Add a redis driver

Add the foundations of a redis driver that can be used
along side the rest of the driver types.

Redis provides a few nice benefits that act as a poormans
zookeeper.

- Durability (when setup with AOF mode).
- Consistent, note that this is still restricted to only
  one redis server, without the recently released redis (alpha)
  clustering > 1 server will not be consistent when partitions
  or failures occur (even redis clustering docs state it is
  not a fully AP or CP solution, which means even with it there
  will still be *potential* inconsistencies).
- Master/slave failover (when setup with redis sentinel), giving
  some notion of HA (values *can* be lost when a failover transition
  occurs).

Further resources/links:

- http://redis.io/
- http://redis.io/topics/sentinel
- http://redis.io/topics/cluster-spec

Change-Id: I2d90be1afae98f40ff5c4230563e686b23d42c8f

commit_message:
Do not load Task.cache column by default

For 100 nodes, cache column may have 70MB. For sqlalchemy it takes almost 10s
to load it. This column wil be loaded only when accessed.

Closes-Bug: 1381757
blueprint 100-nodes-support

Change-Id: I220faf3b49244f3eda8bde26ede85f149eb2caa2

Currently, when you call `register-state-path --leave-symlink /a`, a
symlink is left at /a pointing to /mnt/state/a. However, /mnt/state
doesn't point at ephemeral storage until the instance has booted. So if
another element tries to write through the symlink, it goes wrong.

This patch makes the initial symlink point into the backup dir, fixing
this problem. The symlink is then corrected to point to /mnt/state
after the instance is booted and ephemeral storage has been attached.

  .
  ├── a
  └── b -> a

  $ ../bin/register-state-path --leave-symlink a
  $ ../bin/register-state-path --leave-symlink b
  $ tree
  .
  ├── a -> var/lib/use-ephemeral/a
  ├── b -> var/lib/use-ephemeral/b
  └── var
      └── lib
          └── use-ephemeral
              ├── a
              ├── b -> a
              └── stateful-paths

  $ ../os-refresh-config/pre-configure.d/01-setup-stateful-paths
  $ tree
  .
  ├── a -> mnt/state/a
  ├── b -> mnt/state/b
  ├── mnt
  │\xa0\xa0 └── state
  │\xa0\xa0     ├── a
  │\xa0\xa0     └── b -> a
  └── var
      └── lib
          └── use-ephemeral
              ├── a
              ├── b -> a
              └── stateful-paths

commit_message:
Symlink to backup dir until ephemeral storage available

Currently, when you call `register-state-path --leave-symlink /a`, a
symlink is left at /a pointing to /mnt/state/a. However, /mnt/state
doesn't point at ephemeral storage until the instance has booted. So if
another element tries to write through the symlink, it goes wrong.

This patch defers moving content (and leaving a symlink if required) to the
backup dir until finalise.d runs.

Change-Id: Id5bc25965db1fdf27f2bcb947c518f6f4566fd2f
Co-Author: Nicholas Randon

copy files from a path once.

This means that if path /a is registered twice, you don't end up with
/mnt/state/a/a.

symlinks can be a follow-on patch.

  $ tree boo

      └── lib
          └── use-ephemeral
              ├── a
              ├── b -> a
              └── stateful-paths

commit_message:
Handle double path registration

Canonicalise paths from /var/lib/use-ephemeral/stateful-paths and only
copy files from a path once.

This means that if path /a is registered twice, you don't end up with
/mnt/state/a/a.

Note: symlinks must be relative for this to work. Rewriting absolute
symlinks can be a follow-on patch.

Example (hacked slightly to work as if boo was root):

  $ tree boo
  boo
  └── var
      └── lib
          └── use-ephemeral
              ├── a
              ├── b -> a
              └── stateful-paths

  $ tree boo
  boo
  ├── mnt
  │   └── state
  │       ├── a
  │       └── b -> a
  └── var
      └── lib
          └── use-ephemeral
              ├── a
              ├── b -> a
              └── stateful-paths

Change-Id: I60eb87f44b8b8d122cb4af472327d390e8ba4c23
Co-Author: alexisl@hp.com

commit_message:
Remove confusing access "refs/meta/config" ACL def

We've had some cargo culting of the access "refs/meta/config"
stanza, so let's remove it where it exists.

A follow-up patch will consolidate all puppet-* module acls into
a single acl that also has this fix once change
I1837cef4610d23406d34b15cc949df62a616d960 merges.

Change-Id: Idde43c5b0ed49649e41bb9c9ee699ae8824fb068

commit_message:
Removes package name splitting

Reasons:
- There is no need of splitting of packages as its done in pkg module.
  This splitting was making packages value to be passed as dict
  instead of string.

Changes:
- Removed the splitting of packages variable while calling
   prepare method.

Change-Id: I86d5f7942131c954467e0129d4cfd938e8655a1b
Closes-Bug: #1369010

commit_message:
Represent memory unit in string

Enable unit representation for property 'mem_size' in
Compute node.
1. valid units are: MB or GB, MB being default choice
2. allow space separator(s) between number and unit
3. no space between number and unit is also allowed
4. use default value if property mem_size is not given
5. default value is 1024 MB

implements blueprint: compute-type-memory-unit-wd2

Change-Id: I124524200b6bde7f32ceafd0d45d412026f4ee1f

Add Cinder audit setup to send Ceilo notifications

Allows to get info about the volumes and snapshots existence
and size in a given period of time.

You should bundle this change with a tempest test that actually needs this change."}, {'account_id': 13173, 'date': '2014-10-16 08:05:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Hi Jordan, first of all let me thank you for taking your time on my proposal. I think it is a nice and small addition into the framework that enables more flexibility.

Regarding the usage, well this, with a very little effort, opens the possibility to create more customizable subnetworks. We also heavily use it in all of our internal tests.

Furthermore, wrapping this change into a full test, I think will make things more complicated  and expand the discussion into the test.'}, {'account_id': 8576, 'date': '2014-10-20 07:39:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I agree with @Jordan - It's not that this change is bad, it's that the Tempest policy is to only accept changes that are necessary.
So, unless this is fixing a bug, you should introduce it along with a test that's taking advantage of the new functionality, (ie creating a costume cidr)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 20:00:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

commit_message:
Now subnets created can be more custom

Added subnet.update(**kwargs) into the creation of the subnets so
now the test programer could use this methods for creating subnets with
custom cdirs, names, etc.

Change-Id: I84d6525398b9190176bc7afc19315fa77d74f3e3

commit_message:
Update installation guide for Juno release

I updated the installation guide for Juno release packages
on Ubuntu as follows:

1) Removed "debug" workaround for horizon.
2) Removed "sudoers" workaround for cinder.
3) Fixed other minor issues.

Change-Id: Ie4895ad4e339ca2cf860eee2203afea5d701b95c

commit_message:
auth_token: http_connect_timeout should be an int

The configuration option 'http_connect_timeout' from
'keystoneclient.auth_token' must be an integer, not a boolean.

Closes-Bug: #1362148
DocImpact: If keystoneclient is updated and somebody has set the option
to True, they must change it so that it is an integer, otherwise they
will get a configuration error.
Change-Id: I201c2dbe48e649ac302406dfff16aa482aa7cea2

commit_message:
Adds tenant_network_conf to tempest.conf

Adds the ability to define tempest.conf's tenant_network CIDR

Needed for large_ops job to achieve connectivity

Calculate CIDR based on large_ops number

Change-Id: Ic67a556cd817c179a1874fc136a9a1a59ec27e5b

commit_message:
Add project_id into generate image api params

Image view builder has following links will be generated:
href link, bookmark link, alternate link
those links include a project_id as reference
This patch adds a project_id into the param to make it
is possible to generate those kind of url.

Change-Id: I5641cc4c584af9e7d4a1f0f8560028599df8bee0

commit_message:
Implement containers for heat-engine and heat-api

Loosely followed this document for setting up Heat:
http://docs.openstack.org/icehouse/install-guide/install/yum/content/heat-install.html

Some gotchas:
- crux doesn't require escaping parenthesis for endpoint creation like
  keystone client
- heat icehouse packages are configured for qpid, so kombu had to be
  specified specifically

This firewall reference was handy for port information:
http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/config-reference/content/firewalls-default-ports.html

Implements: blueprint kube-heat-container

Change-Id: Ie4291a6c4c2b85a23a71fc0a003d9160bf0a32b8

commit_message:
Cap maximal cyclomatic complexity

flake8 has support for cyclomatic complexity (Mccabe) currently our
worst offender has a complexity of 28. So
set our max-complexity to 29 so that don't make things any worse.

https://github.com/flintwork/mccabe

Change-Id: Ib6db9de92b3e6e196008580318a2139976610349

- check-osc-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/37/129537/1/check/check-osc-dsvm-functional/a711a48 : FAILURE in 16m 09s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2014-10-20 14:00:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I realize this is the client, but in theory this could be considered a public API that you're changing in a backwards incompatible way. I agree the new name is better, but why not make a new method `initialize_clientmanager` with the conditional early return that then defaults to calling `authenticate_user` if the `client_manager` isn't already initialized? People could then still call `authenticate_user` with the old behaviour (if they're relying on it) and you could have the same behaviour that I agree is more desirable for interactive mode.

I'm new to the project so feel free to ignore me if we're not concerned with what would seem like a public API."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-10-20 14:44:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ian, I would consider the ClientManager itself to be our high-level API (see https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127873/3/examples/osc-lib.py,unified), if/when there is one.  shell.py is just that, the shell that sets up OSC.  I'm in the midst of cleaning up that interface, and to be honest, I don't know anything about these patches that are changing the auth and clientmanager creation.  Not that they're bad, but uncoordinated with the work I am doing ATM and at times conflicting with it.  The problems being addressed are real, but they are painting a house that still needs siding replaced..."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2014-10-20 14:50:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Dean, that's enlightening. I've just been bitten by stuff like this more than I'd like to admit. I've had high level public APIs that people bypass and then complain when changes like this are made. Setting as WIP. For now, I just want to know what you guys have to say about this idea.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-09 13:41:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-monasca-agent-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/40/127240/1/check/gate-monasca-agent-pep8/6e011c2 : SUCCESS in 58s
- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/40/127240/1/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/59e2a05 : SUCCESS in 58s'}, {'account_id': 12108, 'date': '2014-10-14 17:49:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Workflow-1

Hi Henrique.  First of all, thanks for your interest in Monasca.  I have been talking with some other members of the team and while we like the idea of trending type metrics and think they may be useful, we're not sure the monasca-agent is the correct place to implement them.  The data needed to calculate the trending metrics is already being sent by the monasca-agent and stored in the database.  We think it might be better to add this type of request to the monasca-api and do the calculation there rather than sending additional data from the agent.  For example, calculate difference(loads - loads[-n]). That would probably be relatively easy to add. "n" would be how many steps in the past to look at.  Does that make sense?  Also, this type of metric would be difficult to create an alarm on and would most likely only be useful for visualization in some type of external tool like graphite.  Feel free to add a bug/feature request to the monasca project to add this to the monasca-api (https://launchpad.net/monasca) or better yet, submit a patch set yourself.  Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 10046, 'date': '2014-10-14 19:51:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi, Gary. Thanks for your feedback. It seems nice. I'll investigate how we can do this in monasca-api. I had thought something similar to this "difference" of yours. Yes, it makes sense. I also thought about creating a new statistic called 'trend' or 'growth'. Does it sound interesting? I'll take some time investigating the monasca-api and hope to get in touch again asap.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 19:52:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Creating new "cpu_trend" metric

This patch creates the cpu_trend metric that indicates how much the
CPU utilization has grown on the observed window. For now, we just
consider the growth the percenctual difference between the initial
and the final observed values.

cpu.trend > 1 means the CPU util has grown.

Change-Id: I11926fdcd9297220d16a3e45c3c03b2f293391c8

commit_message:
Use keystone identity_uri instead of auth_*

Keystone middleware has deprecated the auth_host and friends in favor of
using identity_uri.

This was done in python-keystoneclient change:
I1f8f5064ea8028af60f167df9b97e215cdadba44

Change-Id: Ic43fc7656e63a890f25d0c8e9d2fed2213882b37

commit_message:
Add xmlsec1 dependency comments

Right now, Keystone IdP uses xmlsec1 command line
tool to sign the generated SAML assertions:

https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/contrib/federation/idp.py#L369

If not installed, the command will fail.

Change-Id: I9d846c4d5913b7b711f540989c243371e1da2181

commit_message:
Fixes docstrings to be more accurate.

These docstrings were modified because they had the wrong path for the
config file and incorrect testing instructions. Since both files were
saying essentially the same thing it made sense to fix other parts of
the docstring to be similar.

Change-Id: Ibf48a369bbbe2c45dcf1d68305c83afe54bda7ff

commit_message:
Extract Assignment tests from IdentityTestCase

Extracts tests for domains, projects, roles and
grants/role assignments from IdentityTestCase
and put them in AssignmentTestCase.

Change-Id: I0e426fa1803e144b1c7a3eb503b212c6469e67c4
Closes-Bug: 1367778

commit_message:
Remove extra flake8 args

By default, flake8 checks the current directory and its subdirectories,
so it tests already for "." - and "manila/common" is a subdirectory of
it.  Thus remove "." and also "manila/common" as subdirectory. Right now
"manila/common" gets tested twice - as part of "." and separate.

Closes-Bug: #1383154
Change-Id: Ie187686bd8b9e9981b2556c1d394fa9a9ca63915

commit_message:
Fix wrong disk type limitation for disk IO throttling

The disk I/O limits feature in QEMU block layer allows I/O throttling
to be used across all underlying storage types.

Change-Id: If99107955fc976b00ee101d4c6a685c29e655f82
Closes-Bug: #1362129
(cherry picked from commit 2e90d62727c093efbf60a7d86b1ee5262b041bbb)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow

Removed unused args to mock side-effect function and duplicate
constant.

commit_message:
Updated service.py and its dependencies

This is to avoid service module dependency on importutils that are now
moved to oslo.utils.

The following changes are included:

 * neutron/openstack/common/eventlet_backdoor.py
  5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
  90ae24b Remove redundant default=None for config options
  fcf517d Update oslo log messages with translation domains

 * neutron/openstack/common/loopingcall.py
  5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
  e377393 Changes calcuation of variable delay
  ab5d5f1 Use timestamp in loopingcall
  bc48099 Log the function name of looping call
  fb4e863 Remove deprecated LoopingCall
  fcf517d Update oslo log messages with translation domains

 * neutron/openstack/common/service.py
  5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
  6ede600 rpc, notifier: remove deprecated modules

 * neutron/openstack/common/systemd.py
  17c4e21 Fix docstring indentation in systemd

 * neutron/openstack/common/threadgroup.py
  5a1a016 Make stop_timers() method public
  fdc8883 Add graceful stop function to ThreadGroup.stop
  2d06d6c Simple typo correction
  4d18b57 threadgroup: use threading rather than greenthread

Change-Id: I4887545f861a93223e2c7cbcdd39efe991bff547

commit_message:
Cleanup of exception handling in network REST API plugin

Cleans up exception handling in the os-network API plugin so
that rather than very generic catching of exceptions, we only catch
those that we expect can occur. Adds new test cases where appropriate,
though some of the exceptions already had testcases.

Change-Id: Ie25f0cc60d157e259463a9e00c5639a09a869fce

commit_message:
Add previously published OSSNs

A handful of previously published OSSNs were never migrated to our
git repo or publishing area on the wiki.  This adds the existing
notes to the git repo.

A few updates have been made to the original notes to follow the
current formatting standards, correct typos, add affected release
info, and other similar changes.

Change-Id: I50d0d37f51350a2c0bd3e8096f1f856fe424904c

commit_message:
Hardware requirements for target nodes

planning-guide
- incorporated introductory material into 0020-system-requirements;
  deleted 0021-sysreq-intro file

- added general hardware guidelines to 0020-system-requirements

- 0020-system-requirements/0023-node-server-hardware-requirements
  - added links to community docs for Compute and Image storage requirements,
    object storage requirements
  - added link to OpenStack Operations Guide
  - added link to "nodes and roles" and monitoring/ceilometer
  - added link to "Calculating Hardware" section of Planning Guide

- added "Sample Target Node Configuration" based on info from Stefan

The two files in 0010-prerequisites suddently had Title-level build
errors so I fixed those.

user-guide
  Changed the recommendation for Ceph replication factor to 3, to
  match the recommendation given here.

terminology/overcommit -- added note to set CPU ratio to 1:1
until one understands the resource allocation for ones environment,
in support of note in target nodes recommendations.
We need a larger discussion about how to determine an appropriate
overcommit ratio but this will be more appropriate when one can reset
the ratio on the UI and without redeploying the environment.  It is
beyond the scope of this commit.

Closes-Bug: 1373419

Change-Id: I5f6e89646fccbaf1e77b1ef14cc154e4d78d290d

Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-08 20:08:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks Eoghan. I considered automatically starting multiples of the various coordinating agents but then decided not to for a few different reasons:

* managing the process and/or screens gets messy (see how lib/nova handles multiple fake rivers for an example)
* in the multinode case, we don't want to arbitrarily choose to have multiple agents on _this_ node when perhaps we want one on _this_ node and one on each of those _other_ nodes
* someone might want multiples of one type of agent and not the other

None of that stuff can be controlled just by the existence of the one variable, we'd need more.

So in order to maintain some simplicity I thought best to start the idea with a small change and then see where it takes us.

None of the above issues are insurmountable (have a problem in devstack just add more VARIABLES!) so if you think adding more features in this patch is the way to go, shout out.

For reference, the specific use case of mine that I'm trying to cover here is wanting a devstack that is already ready for coordination and then I, by hand, start and stop other agents to add to and remove from the various groups. That is I'm thinking of this as a development and testing aid, one that involves humans exploring, not automation."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-08 20:54:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Note that I need to add 'workload_partitioning=True'  to the [compute] section of config in order for the compute agent. Noting here instead of just doing it because I'm doing something else."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-08 20:54:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-10-09 08:37:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Allow use of ceilometer agent coordination

Juno brings tooz-based coordination of ceilometer central, compute
and alarm agents. If CEILOMETER_COORDINATION_URL is set it will be
used as the value for a tooz coordination backend. If memcached is
chosen, its package will be installed. Other backends, such as
zookeeper can be configured, but installation is left as an exercise
for the devstacker.

In the default devstack setup having coordination will do little as
there are only one of each agent, but this makes it a bit easier for
multi-node or multi-agent setups.

Change-Id: Ib85ccd435de3bc0ae56b5fe8c2fce6c2af9ff8d0

Fix empty functions causing stack failure

This patch adds a return value to several empty functions that are causing stack.sh to fail when the
Cisco Neutron plugin is enabled.

Change-Id: I43987d9cc5edc53de41c27354c3a737643d1cd43
Closes-bug: 1383273

commit_message:
Pass auth_url if os_no_client_auth specified

The standalone auth_password middleware expects 'X-Auth-Url' header
in the request. The recent version of heatclient doesn't pass the
required header which is retrieved from the option '--os-auth-url',
though we explicitly specify it in the commandline. Let's pass the
argument 'auth_url' and get heatclient working in standalone mode.

Change-Id: I3e67f4699c61c3ce5c42f25e3c8b137f8ba8a2e3
Closes-bug: #1380658

commit_message:
Remove ClientManager._service_catalog

Anything that needs a service catalog can get it directly from
auth_ref.service_catalog, no need to carry the extra attribute.

ClientManager.get_endpoint_for_service_type() reamins the proper
method to get an endpoint for clients that still need one directly.

Change-Id: I809091c9c71d08f29606d7fd8b500898ff2cb8ae

commit_message:
Fixed IP addresses for vboxnet addresses

the 0450* file was duplicate of the 0550 information,
apparently before the English was editted.  It was not
included in the build but was still in the source so
it's deleted.

Also added a couple links to the main docs and fixed
some awkward prose.

Change-Id: I9b999107024e48276f29b137c139beeca5698858
Closes-Bug:1380840

commit_message:
Release Notes -- refining new structure

Removed "Monitoring" section; moved ceilometer, mongodb, and zabbix
to "other"

Keystone and Murano also moved to other

1060-general renamed to 1060-openstack; moved one of those issues
to 1030-fuel-install

deleted vestigal 050-known-issues

Change-Id: I028aa9da90e5ef4d4262a71f914ff394c3f413b9

commit_message:
Fix F811 error in pep8

Somehow a bad merge commit happened and duplicated a test method.

This removes the duplicate method in order to unbreak the gate.

Change-Id: I3b8f7bee46161bd315a7f51678109e483eb0f281
Closes-Bug: 1383436

commit_message:
Fix support status for OS::Heat::SoftwareComponent

Since SoftwareComponent is derived from SoftwareConfig, the support
status 2014.1 inherited from SoftwareConfig was incorrectly shown for
the SoftwareComponent resource.
This patch fixes the problem by correctly setting support_status in
the SoftwareComponent resource.

Change-Id: I973755f11e21ccb4f8bbc532da4de964e07c65f1

commit_message:
Fix for circular imports in compile and runtime

Bug No: 1339814

get_runtime() is a redundant function not being currently used by any other
module. This is the only place in compile.py where runtime module is used.
Someone who needs to use Runtime() instance can directly import from
runtime.Runtime instead of using compile.get_runtime().

The runtime.py module however needs compile.py in several occassions.
So the import in runtime.py must be retained.

Change-Id: I6389e7210c10724bfc85dad7dad4693f733357f7

need to make sure that a firewall isn't going to block the
connection.  On Fedora, firewalld is enabled by default on a
minimal install so we need to check for it and stop devtest with

"}]
commit_message:
Check for firewalld before starting seed

Now that we are watching for a completion signal from the seed, we
need to make sure that a firewall isn't going to block the
connection.  On Fedora, firewalld is enabled by default on a
minimal install so we need to check for it and stop devtest with
a message about how to fix the problem.  The port is not
automatically opened to avoid silently poking holes in the user's
firewall, which might not be appreciated in strict environments.

Change-Id: I98d5ef17960c7cb963d1934c609d902a4492570d

commit_message:
systemd: always use /lib/systemd

Debian and Ubuntu use /lib/systemd whereas Fedora usr /usr/lib/systemd as the
default system unit directory. This already leads to conflict when the
debian-systemd is used.

Fedora provides a symbolic link between /lib/systemd and /usr/lib/systemd
to also support /lib/systemd directory. With this patch, we use /lib/systemd
everywhere.

This patch supersedes I413a92284e6a79e7fcdde99c5138bc3ce8e85e80.

Change-Id: I459f7514ab35082d31607968252a9005fa25de2a
See: https://bugs.debian.org/719634

will run unit tests on Ubuntu Precise. This is a problem because the
version of Ruby and therefore Facter is too old on Precise and causes
failures for certain Facter values only available in Facter > 2. This

and adds the puppet unit tests as an exception to set_node_options() to

commit_message:
Only run stackforge/puppet-* unit tests on trusty

Without this patch, stable/icehouse branches in stackforge/puppet-*
will run unit tests on Ubuntu Precise. This is a problem because the
version of Ruby and therefore Facter is too old on Precise and causes
failures for certain Facter values only available in Facter > 2. This
patch removes precise from the nodes to test the puppet-* modules on
and adds the puppet unit tests as an exception to set_node_options() to
prevent zuul from trying to use precise on stable/icehouse.

Change-Id: Id7453171a8ca2321528e0e0d3d2a0984e0304db3

commit_message:
Teach Grenade to do Juno to Kilo upgrades

First step in doing Juno to Kilo upgrades with Grenade is setting the
new base and target branches. Note this should come after both devstack
and grenade have stable/juno branches.

commit_message:
Remove grenade neutron non-voting from the gate

This commit removes the non-voting gate-grenade-dsvm-neutron job from
the list of jobs grenade gate pipeline. We shouldn't be running
non-voting jobs in the gate pipeline as it's just a waste of resources
if the jobs don't work.

Related-Bug: #1383439

Change-Id: I14b67585330efeff6c07a40292f4bcc4fd8fd332

commit_message:
Add jenkins-project to the default env list

Add jenkins-project to the list of envs used when "tox" is run locally
without arguments. This should make it easier for someone working on a
change to test locally before submitting the patch.

Change-Id: I5f2732daa2509ff378429959bd15d0f2f7f98692

commit_message:
Fix bug with expirer and unicode

Looks like I wasn't careful enough last time i fixed this bug- this
is basically the same deal, just further down the line. What happens
without this bug fix is you upload a object with a unicode name and
a x-delete-after header and when it does expire the customer object
gets removed but the expirer marker object doesn't.

Change-Id: I82359c87a0919d71693e49ecf08e0f1eedc9d18e

commit_message:
Use hostPort to lock 1 nova-compute/nova-network per node

Kubernetes does not have a horizontal scaling feature that works per
node.  A workaround is to use hostPort to cause the scheduler not to schedule
several replicationController replicas to each node.  By doing so, only one
nova-compute is launched per node up to a total of 6 nodes which is the most
we can generate in testing.

Change-Id: I1621f15cf1ec502418b454300645b46bc796dc8b

commit_message:
Put a cap on our cyclomatic complexity

flake8 supports cyclomatic complexity checking, so lets use it. Our
current worst offender is register_ironic_node (which I kind of agree
with) so setting our cap to 14 which is one higher than this.

Change-Id: Ic8f356d2d67324c0b2ccaa8a7b2cf7752635f68b

commit_message:
Put a cap on our cyclomatic complexity

flake8 has support for cyclomatic complexity (Mccabe) currently our
worst offender has a complexity of 67 (25 is considered very bad). So
set our max-complexity to 68 so we at least don't make things any worse.

This is the first step in bringing this number down to 25 or so.

https://github.com/flintwork/mccabe

Change-Id: I5117ca58ad28888e24c16251aa5e92084ead97ca

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-03 20:54:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for VM monitoring

This patch gives the Monasca Agent the ability to monitor virtual
machines (VMs) provisioned under Nova.  It bundles Ceilometer's
virtualization inspector to gather the actual metrics, includes a
monasca-setup plugin, and adds cross-tenant support.  The latter
enables the Agent to submit metrics on behalf of a different
tenant/project, giving the VM's owner a set of metrics without each
VM having to run its own Agent.  This plugin collects two sets of
measurements per metric: one for the VM's owner (in-cloud) and for
the Operations team (infrastructure).  They differ in the following
ways:
- Operations metric names are prefixed with "vm." in order to group VM
  and overcloud metrics separately
- Operations metrics include "tenant_id" as a dimension
- Operations metrics include "cloud_tier" dimension with the value
  "overcloud"
- The "hostname" dimension for Operations contains the name of the
  compute server; for the tenant, "hostname" is the name of the VM

The metrics gathered by this plugin include:
- Disk I/O: read/write operations/bytes per second
- Disk I/O: errors per second
- Network I/O: in/out packets/bytes per second
- CPU utilization as a percentage of CPU time over polling time

Change-Id: I23781a1ba552ef2551e6ff1caea21dd8f515d73d

commit_message:
Add support for VM monitoring

This patch gives the Monasca Agent the ability to monitor virtual
machines (VMs) provisioned under Nova.  It bundles Ceilometer's
virtualization inspector to gather the actual metrics, includes a
monasca-setup plugin, and adds cross-tenant support.  The latter
enables the Agent to submit metrics on behalf of a different
tenant/project, giving the VM's owner a set of metrics without each
VM having to run its own Agent.  This plugin collects two sets of
measurements per metric: one for the VM's owner (in-cloud) and for
the Operations team (infrastructure).  They differ in the following
ways:
- Operations metric names are prefixed with "vm." in order to group VM
  and overcloud metrics separately
- Operations metrics include "tenant_id" as a dimension
- Operations metrics include "cloud_tier" dimension with the value
  "overcloud"
- The "hostname" dimension for Operations contains the name of the
  compute server; for the tenant, "hostname" is the name of the VM

The metrics gathered by this plugin include:
- Disk I/O: read/write operations/bytes per second
- Disk I/O: errors per second
- Network I/O: in/out packets/bytes per second
- CPU utilization as a percentage of CPU time over polling time

Change-Id: I23781a1ba552ef2551e6ff1caea21dd8f515d73d

commit_message:
Adds memory stats meter to libvirt inspector

Uses libvirt 'virDomainMemoryStats' to retrive the memory
that is used by domain, implements 'inspect_memory_usage'
function in libvirt inspector.

blueprint libvirt-memory-utilization-inspector

Change-Id: I61480425d8690aa17fa11450b4ad1d73e3c8d804

commit_message:
Add max-complexity to pep8 for Keystone

The current highest complexity is 23, set the maximum complexity
for flake8 to 24. This should help to keep code simple and
maintainable. It should be possible to reduce the maximum
complexity to something closer to 20 with relatively small efforts.

keystone.common.sql.migrate_repo.versions.039_grant_to_assignment:
    'downgrade_assignment_table' is complexity of 21

keystone.token.controllers:
    'Auth._authenticate_token' is complexity of 23

Change-Id: I47cb13bac97e9144ef004977942b9eaa50a17b39

commit_message:
Explicitly set -nv ironic jobs non-voting

A previous commit to avoid running these jobs against icehouse removed
the application of 'voting: false' to the -nv jobs, causing them to
vote where they shouldn't.  This adds it back by explicitly applying it
to those jobs via regex.

Change-Id: Ice4423fdd3128869fa644f1e603721370230dfad

Introduced a flag in I1fb4d58a36c9a12f87527f4fb551f4b664c386bd, this
does not work when we set it from here. So this review removes the
NON_STANDARD_REQS flag. The reason it does not work is that

passed down into the process.

Change-Id: I379a5e6c566e8ac207c70089f3251eff6afe3379
'}]
commit_message:
remove non-standard-reqs flag from check-tempest-dsvm-f20-docker

Introduced a flag in I1fb4d58a36c9a12f87527f4fb551f4b664c386bd, this
does not work when we set it from here. So this review removes the
NON_STANDARD_REQS flag. The reason it does not work is that
devstack runs stack.sh with sudo and the environment variable is not
passed down into the process.

Change-Id: I379a5e6c566e8ac207c70089f3251eff6afe3379

I think this is a great change.  However it does make it so that one cannot pick "select" when both select and poll are available (that may or may not be desired by users but it has been in the wild this way).  Instead of removing the option of selection the poll method how about if we make the default None which means "pick the best one that glance supports".  Then we can still allow a user to select the method they want.  If necessary we could validate that selection against a know list of acceptable methods, however I would be inclined to give users enough rope to hang themselves and document the only supported methods (select and poll).'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-10-16 16:05:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Remove eventlet_hub option

The option has a default value that is not portable, and therefore the
test fails on OS like Darwin. There's actually no need to specify any
hub – no other OpenStack projects as that option – as in theory Eventlet
is smart enough to pick the best implementation available anyway.

However, since Glance only works with poll or select as a hub, let's try
them in that order. That avoids a user selecting things like 'epolls'
and expecting Glance to work, whereas it would fail.

Also remove a useless cleanup() call in the failing test as the
start_servers() method already does a cleanup itself.

Change-Id: Ia7765151ebb00cdf01e96cf39f3242899d358772

commit_message:
Adjust audit logs to avoid negative disk info

When requesting more disk than is available, the audit
logs will report negative values. This may confuse the
user or make him/her think the tracking is innaccurate.

This patch seeks to remove any confusion. It is in the
same vein as https://review.openstack.org/#/c/93261/
which addresses the same issue in regards to cpu and
memory audit logs.

Change-Id: I184985573b20144717ac40f1f3c26709030d5a03
Closes-bug: #1350542

commit_message:
Adds test scripts for upstream training content

This patch introduces a script for converting slides from upstream training
into HTML and PDF files. It can be invoked directly or via tox.

If you want to use tox to run the script, please add 'landslide' and
'weasyprint' to the test-requirements.txt file.

    $ tox -e check-upstream-training

Change-Id: Ib0d7aa625bc7b58e75c3b33b894371856fceaf2b

commit_message:
Updates test-requirements for upstream training

Adds landslide and weasyprint as dependencies to test-requirements.txt
for tox to be able to build pdf and html files in upstream training
contents. To generate the pdf and html files from rst the script
build-rst-slides script will be invoked and requires the given python
packages.

Change-Id: If7861fe192c8a3ace65a49dbafd875fa5bd1a83e

commit_message:
Don't shadow local variables "resource"

We could rename the local variables, but it's just as easy to not
use the resource module. Since the functions are not used, remove them.

Change-Id: I356fbe0042f24aba78fba5deebe7fa645a035d96

commit_message:
Update training guides requirements

Adds landslide and weasyprint for generating html and pdf files from
rst files. Training guides requires landslide for generating HTML5
presentations and weasyprint is used for generating the HTML5
presentations from html to pdf format.

This is required for building upstream-training content present under
training-guides project.

Change-Id: Iec27132141265bf4308ad22bb0750f146c18bb21

commit_message:
XenAPI: Inform XAPI who is connecting to it

XenServer supports an 'originator' being passed to the login function
This originator is very useful in identifying how XAPI is being used
and, when there is a problem, which software package issued which
commands

Change-Id: I003979bb3796e870890e220cf4b046e51581a373

commit_message:
Changing the value type of http_connect_timeout

The value type of http_connect_timeout definition
is changed from Bool to Int value. Python treats
a value more than 1 as True but oslo config defines
Boolean values as 'true, '1', 'yes' and 'on'.
So http_connect_timeout is only configured 1 or None.

Change-Id: I53075cc04d0ccea543f8e657279534208ed03058
Closes-bug: #1368545

commit_message:
Remove unused ec2 driver option

Remove the unused ec2 driver option from the config. This option
is unused since the credential backend is used for the ec2 contrib
extension.

Change-Id: I5385a086210e415a14b0ed1605c9ded50a280ad2

commit_message:
Compile Horizon message catalogs during stack.sh

Recently compiled message catalogs (mo files) were removed
in Horizon and django_openstack_auth repositories.
We need to compile message catalogs to make translations
available for Horizon users. It is useful for developers too.

Change-Id: I0831e8308205c116d8e3bb8b43be7f0dd6fa0c0a

[{'created': '2014-10-17 12:31:57.000000000', 'message': "Update WSGI app creation to be compatible with Django 1.7

This resolves the following error when trying to run Horizon:

AppRegistryNotReady: The translation infrastructure cannot be
initialized before the apps registry is ready. Check that you don't
make non-lazy gettext calls at import time.

and is backwards-compatible with our currently supported versions (back
to 1.4).

Change-Id: I1e59f2bf6633a34cfe9230aa028f345e5fa70f94
Closes-Bug: #1382023
(cherry picked from commit 686af384c201148c3aebcfbf18b2527587d70ea4)
"}]
commit_message:
Update WSGI app creation to be compatible with Django 1.7

This resolves the following error when trying to run Horizon:

AppRegistryNotReady: The translation infrastructure cannot be
initialized before the apps registry is ready. Check that you don't
make non-lazy gettext calls at import time.

and is backwards-compatible with our currently supported versions (back
to 1.4).

Change-Id: I1e59f2bf6633a34cfe9230aa028f345e5fa70f94
Closes-Bug: #1382023
(cherry picked from commit 686af384c201148c3aebcfbf18b2527587d70ea4)

commit_message:
Limit Pecan version, fix Pandas usage

In order to bypass bug fixed in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129602/, we limit Pecan to version
before 0.8.

Also, let's fix get_measure() usage by passing datetime object directly
to get_measure() rather than random string. We validate them in the API
like the rest of timestamp objects.

commit_message:
Minor refactor of _setup_instance_group()

This patch is a minor refactoring of the _setup_instance_group()
method in the filter scheduler.  The majority of the method was inside
of a conditional.  This primarily reverses that and reduces the
nesting depth used.  There should be no functional changes at all in
this patch.

Change-Id: Iab4d63200653a4320c91dc1356091ff9d961cafd
Related-bug: #1379451

commit_message:
add InstanceGroup.get_by_instance_uuid

Add a new method to the InstanceGroup object that lets you get a group
by an instance UUID.  Right now Nova only lets you have an instance in
a single group, so that's why this is a method of InstanceGroup and
not InstanceGroupList.

Change-Id: Ic0181e241471ad817284209e6a1093a438962bf1
Related-bug: #1379451

commit_message:
Catch correct exception for Cinder api version detection

Catch the EndpointNotFound exception raised by Keystone rather
than the one thrown by Cinder since keystoneclient raises keystone
exceptions and not cinder exceptions. Also update the fake
keystone client to mirror this behavior.

Change-Id: I9f4579cf55fc697470dd8803553d7968e22a6bec
Closes-Bug: #1382659

commit_message:
ofagent: Ignore unknown l2pop entry removals

l2pop can send us entry removal without the corresponding addition.
Gracefully ignore it instead of crashing.

Closes-Bug: #1357198
Change-Id: I5a0cc44ba62faf15d6fe3730a9532a3826647820

commit_message:
Compare subnet length as well when deleting DHCP entry

When searching for the DHCP subnet entry to delete, the existing code
compares only the subnet prefix and ignores subnet length.  This could
delete the wrong entry/entries if nested subnets are present.

Change-Id: Icf079c42adeca14ef84ec57dc45a5930fde8786d
Closes-Bug: #1362416

Drop sslutils and versionutils modules

The modules are not used since when we've switched to oslo.messaging.

commit_message:
Delete the placeholder file: example.rst

example.rst was a placeholder, because we needed specs/kilo to
exist for people submitting specs. Now that we have an approved spec,
the kilo directory exists.

See https://review.openstack.org/127047 for more information as to
why example.rst was there in the first place.

Change-Id: Ic062d265dce75e284c47ad90d2adb4cdca6134f0

commit_message:
Install all binaries located in bin

Until now, there were some elements which installed everything
located in the bin directory, which other elements depended on.
Take this logic out of those elements and made it a general rule.

Change-Id: I22349b909c6d74cd57ff8073183309ffa024b777
Closes-Bug: 1378710

Migrate geard to svc-map

This patch migrates the geard element from map-services to svc-map
by adding the -a option to appropriate os-svc-* calls and adding
a svc-map file.

commit_message:
Add missing packages to tempest element

Attempts to use this element failed due to missing the
following packages:
libssl-dev libffi-dev

This patch adds the packages to the element, including
pkg-map installs and map files.

Also changing shell called in init.d/51-tempest to be /bin/bash.

Change-Id: I6859e4309cc73127ac389de70c829ac59afcfd91
Closes-Bug: #1379047

commit_message:
Add workaround for Ubuntu Cloud archive

I added a workaround for the Ubuntu Cloud archive repository
because the 'add-apt-repository' method does not contain
information about Juno packages.

Change-Id: Ib222dc1a1919e3e3f55e694426d25fbefb9e3cbe
Closes-Bug: #1362521

commit_message:
Use oslo.i18n

oslo.i18n provides the i18n function that were provided by
oslo-incubator's gettextutils module

Import _ where needed, oslo.i18n deprecated the builtin method.

Closes-Bug: #1382187
Change-Id: I12aa1c725aa4bb52a9aa46e9c3d2b303839de48b

commit_message:
Swap trusts delegated from from heat_stack_owner to _member_

Currently, we require users to have a special role, specific to heat,
which is defaulted to heat_stack_owner.  This can cause confusion if
folks don't know new users need this role, and it's not really serving
any functional purpose (it's just needed because you have to delegate
at least one role via the trust).

So, instead, we can use the default _member_ role, which is created
for default project membership by keystone when creating users.

This should mean in most circumstances users can be created and use
heat without any additional configuration, since they should already
have the _member_ role.

There is residual confusion re Member vs _member_, but according to
the information I can find, e.g bug #1330132 and the keystone.conf
member_role_name option, _member_ is the right default to use.

Deployers are still of course free to modify the heat.conf option to
suit their local policies if needed, this should just make things
a little easier for people dealing with default OpenStack installs.

Change-Id: Id8bc84de48d65b7c05531571502d4fbdad5cc02f
Related-Bug: #1306665

commit_message:
No need to push our rabbit user/pass to rabbit cookbook

Because the rabbit user/pass is stored in internal user database,
no need to push them to rabbit cookbook and expose them in config file.
And configuring rabbitmq default password with clear test is insecure,
so remove it.

Change-Id: Iab95e2dc8cd28b4a45574cf8883f1626dc332db0
Closes-Bug: #1381343

commit_message:
VMware: Support spawn VM with multiple disks

The VMware driver spawn contains logic to check whether
a block device mapping is provided or not. This branching will either
trigger the logic to boot from an image or to use the volume provided
as the root disk.
However, this implementation doesn't handle the case where the user
wants to boot from an image and attach volumes at the same time.
This patch addresses this issue by checking whether the instance
contains an image reference.
If an image reference is provided: we boot from image, and potentially
we
can add block device mappings to the VM created. Otherwise, we use
the volume provided as the root disk.

Closes-Bug: #1271966

Change-Id: I131b414e58e9338b39e94ec73a839991e75952b8

commit_message:
Updated fileutils and its dependencies

This is to avoid fileutils dependency on excutils that are now moved to
oslo.utils.

The following changes are included:

* neutron/openstack/common/__init__.py
  6b048e7 Let oslotest manage the six.move setting for mox

 * neutron/openstack/common/_i18n.py
  9ce1d96 Fix i18n import
  5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n

 * neutron/openstack/common/fileutils.py
  6ff6b4b Switch oslo-incubator to use oslo.utils and remove old modules
  2b966f9 Fix deletion of cached file for policy enforcer
  9c88dc3 file_open: fixed docstring to refer to open() instead of file()
  6c7407b fileutils: port to Python 3
  fcf517d Update oslo log messages with translation domains

 * neutron/openstack/common/log.py
  6c706c5 Delete graduated serialization files
  5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
  6ff6b4b Switch oslo-incubator to use oslo.utils and remove old modules
  aa74411 log: add missing space in error message
  037dee0 Set stevedore log level to WARN by default
  37c0091 Add unicode coercion of logged messages to ContextFormatter
  6614413 Correct coercion of logged message to unicode
  1188d88 Except socket.error if syslog isn't running
  ac995be Fix E126 pep8 errors
  631f880 Set keystonemiddleware and routes.middleware to log on WARN level
  726d00a Adjust oslo logging to provide adapter is enabled for
  433fa0b Make logging_context_format_string optional in log.set_defaults
  ac92c06 Add default log level for websocket
  5fd77eb Ability to customize default_log_levels for each project
  4d9328c Python 3: enable tests/unit/test_log.py
  cb5a804 Move `mask_password` to strutils

Note: cb5a804 is partially included; that's ok because we don't use the
moved function in Neutron.

Change-Id: I3bfcaff2620b368d807e9468bb7abc01d6471661
