commit_message:
Reduce security group db calls to neutron server

Within ovs agent daemon loop, prepare_devices_filter will impose heavy workloads
to neutron server in order to retrieve the security groups message to apply
firewall rules. If agent is configured to use Noopfirewall driver or security
groups are disabled, there is no need for loading the rules from server and
refreshing the firewalls. This will reduce the number of db calls and improve
performance for neutron server in this case.

Change-Id: Id244aab3cac37fc6ed3dc05cbee91cdf9e34d9cc
Closes-Bug: #1365806

commit_message:
Fixes k8s neutron pod image source and formatting

Previously, the k8s neutron pod was pulling the image from
danehans instead of kollaglue. Additionally, the formatting was
incorrect causing kube not to pull the image at all.

Change-Id: I6f787a432ffb9cae404f915ac5228ddcb88e877c

commit_message:
l3_agent: avoid name conflict with context

module name, context, conflicts with argument name in many place in
l3_agent. In order to avoid such conflict, import context as n_context
following Neutron practice.

Change-Id: Ic3754818f84064d2c8da04914826fc912437b2f0
Closes-Bug: #1381900

commit_message:
Do not override user-defined Device Size

This change introduces a flag which identifies whether or not the
user has manually set the Device Size field when launching an
instance with a new volume. If the user has made a change then the
value will not be overridden by the logic that sets the Device Size
based on the selected image/flavor unless the user-defined value is
too small.

Change-Id: I1f02fd386a9b6836fb95433d9cb819af4f267d6c
Closes-bug: 1370080

commit_message:
Use six instead of str for exceptions

Use six.text_type instead of str for exceptions to allow lazy
translations with oslo.i18n.

Remove some unneeded msg assignment.

Change-Id: Ie26c2b90503f130f69444cfb51bf5cef8f592f98

commit_message:
Schema enhancement to support MultiSegment Network

Description:
Currently, there is nothing in the schema that ensures segments
for a network are returned in the same order they were specified
when the network was created, or even in a deterministic order.

Solution:
We need to add another field named 'segment_index' in
'ml2_network_segment' table containing a numeric position index.
With segment_index field we can retrieve the segments in the
order in which user created.

This patch set also fixes ML2 invalid unit test case in
test_create_network_multiprovider().

Closes-Bug: #1224978
Closes-Bug: #1377346

Change-Id: I560c34c6fe1c5425469ccdf9b8b4905c123d496d

commit_message:
Release 4.2.0

Changes:
 - Added option to configure libvirt service name via class parameters
 - Added support for multiple SSL APIs
 - Added option to configure os_region_name in the nova config
 - Corrected resource dependencies on the nova user
 - Fixed os version fact comparison for RedHat-based operating systems
   for specifying service provider
 - Fixed ssl parameter requirements when using kombu and rabbit
 - Added class for extended logging options

Change-Id: I38c5f6a40efe905cf5bf78ddf07008a56ac0ac1f

commit_message:
Translation download: Update all existing translations

Download translations for all languages that are in the repo.

this avoids the situation that a file gets downloaded with 75 %
translations and then not updated as contents changed and translations
do not catch up.

Change-Id: Ic3bc5fa2642aeaabee5d4c1e0c3764baed811a5d

puppetlabs/stdlib 4.x is backwards compatible with 3.x and still tested
on Puppet 2.7. Updating stdlib to 4.x allows modules to use newer
functions without breaking older functionality.

Change-Id: I74e4d3a7bc11cd194fc33a1bbb70f07836ea5d32
'}]
commit_message:
Update stdlib dependency to 4.x

puppetlabs/stdlib 4.x is backwards compatible with 3.x and still tested
on Puppet 2.7. Updating stdlib to 4.x allows modules to use newer
functions without breaking older functionality.

Change-Id: I74e4d3a7bc11cd194fc33a1bbb70f07836ea5d32

commit_message:
Add translation checks for training-guides

There is now a first translation for the training-guides in Japanese, so
we can run the check jobs for translations.

Use openstack-doc-translation template and remove jobs that are part of
the template.

Change-Id: I70a4b56639805f17d0802fa602b88bb774b64bd8

commit_message:
Build docs for openstack/governance

Add a check job to build versions of the docs to make reviews easier
(some of the output is generated by sphinx extensions). We still need to
publish the results somewhere when we're done.

Change-Id: I73d21bdc7af961c39ac50f17c30f754409f31660

implementation into separate modules.

commit_message:
Add ExtraConfig param to storage templates

This patch extends the ExtraConfig parameters to the storage nodes
when using tuskar-api to deploy an overcloud.

Change-Id: Ied9978efe76ed9c6078a10bc1a736d7ae93f3ffc

commit_message:
Refactor _make_subnet_dict to avoid issuing unnecessary queries

Use joined loads for attributes dns_nameservers and host_routes.

As a result, particular scenarios like restarting DHCP agent
could benefit from improved server-side performance.

Change-Id: I6470356b601e2fcf74c7e0a6df438cef7099e9fe
Closes-Bug: #1374044

(1 comment)

Comment is inline.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-10-09 08:49:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks Chris for this thought-provoking patch.

But just to clarify ... in order for a malicious agent to be used as a DoS attack, surely this would require a hypervisor breakout by the attacker, in which case all bets are off in any case?

i.e. if anyone malicious is let loose on the host-level outside their instances, then they can wreak all manner of havoc?

However, I do like the idea of surfacing the partitioning of the workload in the logs, modulo Igor's observation about log message length.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-09 10:07:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

"But just to clarify ... in order for a malicious agent to be used as a DoS attack, surely this would require a hypervisor breakout by the attacker, in which case all bets are off in any case?"

Depending on the memcached setup, the attacker could be anywhere on any network; if memcached is not firewalled or only on a private network on which controllers run then it can be reached. This is common knowledge for people doing large scale installations but for people running a casual or small installation (say with devstack or packstack) being able to subtly manipulate the coordination (in a way that wouldn't give immediate catastrophe) violates the principle of least surprise. At least to me I would expect my coordination service to be at least somewhat hardened against this kind of problem.

I don't know but presumably a weakly installed zookeeper could have similar problems.

I don't think there is a major problem here, because it is easy to administratively control the problem, but I do think the need to do so will violate people's expectations. We tend to require a password for things like mysql despite there being options for IP-based access controls. I'm asking if a similar thing is important here?

With regard to Igor's comments and the usefulness of logging the partitioning: I only injected those log messages to demonstrate the problem (when the length of resources drops to 0 you know things have gone extra bad) not as something to be committed to the real code. I can certainly cook something to do that, but that wasn't my goal here.

My initial goal was to just make the inspector because I'm _desperate_ for tools of that kind that allow me to inspect a running set of ceilometer services without having to dig through loads of log files. I want to watch the watchmen easily.

It was only after creating the tool that I realized there might be a problem and this commit changed from committing the tool to demonstrating the problem. If the tool or the logs are desired I can make separate clean commits for those.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-10-09 10:25:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Note that keystone also may use memcache to cache tokens, which potentially gives rise to a more serious attack vector.

Since memcache could be configured to use SASL authentication, but IIUC keystone chooses to rely on the plain-text dogpile MemcachedBackend as opposed to the SASL-capable binary BMemcachedBackend, this suggests that there's an underlying assumption here that memcached is always appropriately firewalled off?

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-20 14:22:58.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127271/ for a packaging of the relevant bits here as a potentially useful script.'}]

[{'created': '2014-10-08 21:37:30.000000000', 'message': "Demo potential service denial via coordination

When using coordination it is possible to maliciously join a group and
send a heartbeat, be partitioned resources, but do no work. Other
workers in the same group will receive fewer resources, sometimes as
low as 0.

This changeset includes changes which allow a demo, download it,
start up a ceilometer enabled devstack and:

* Change ceilometer.conf to add:

    [coordination]
    backend_url = memcached://localhost

    [compute]
    workload_partitioning = True

* Change pipeline.yaml's interval to something 60 seconds or less

* boot several instances (I used ten)
* run several compute agents with the following start up (so
  debugging messages are visible)

    /usr/bin/ceilometer-agent-compute 2>&1 |grep '####'

* run this new inspector thing I created to verify that the expected
  number of agents are in the expected group:

    bin/ceilometer-coordination-inspect.py compute-`hostname`

* run the inspector again to fake regular additions (with heartbeat)
  to the group (new processes are forked every 5 seconds or so):

    bin/ceilometer-coordination-inspect.py --fake compute-`hostname`

That last will carry on running, adding new members to the group and
displaying the full membership list.

Each time the real compute agents do discovery they will show as having
fewer resources to work with. Those resources they do not have are
not being polled.

I've only tried this so far with memcached, where it would be
expected to be like this because there's no auth and we're not using
opaque keys. Presumably there is at least some documenting we want
to do here (to control access to memcached or at least explain the
risk), and perhaps some implementation of auth for the zookeeper
backend.

Change-Id: I1368f975bfe82162b36eeb0d27f225648f77f327
"}]
commit_message:
Demo potential service denial via coordination

When using coordination it is possible to maliciously join a group and
send a heartbeat, be partitioned resources, but do no work. Other
workers in the same group will receive fewer resources, sometimes as
low as 0.

This changeset includes changes which allow a demo, download it,
start up a ceilometer enabled devstack and:

* Change ceilometer.conf to add:

    [coordination]
    backend_url = memcached://localhost

    [compute]
    workload_partitioning = True

* Change pipeline.yaml's interval to something 60 seconds or less

* boot several instances (I used ten)
* run several compute agents with the following start up (so
  debugging messages are visible)

    /usr/bin/ceilometer-agent-compute 2>&1 |grep '####'

* run this new inspector thing I created to verify that the expected
  number of agents are in the expected group:

    bin/ceilometer-coordination-inspect.py compute-`hostname`

* run the inspector again to fake regular additions (with heartbeat)
  to the group (new processes are forked every 5 seconds or so):

    bin/ceilometer-coordination-inspect.py --fake compute-`hostname`

That last will carry on running, adding new members to the group and
displaying the full membership list.

Each time the real compute agents do discovery they will show as having
fewer resources to work with. Those resources they do not have are
not being polled.

I've only tried this so far with memcached, where it would be
expected to be like this because there's no auth and we're not using
opaque keys. Presumably there is at least some documenting we want
to do here (to control access to memcached or at least explain the
risk), and perhaps some implementation of auth for the zookeeper
backend.

Change-Id: I1368f975bfe82162b36eeb0d27f225648f77f327

commit_message:
WIP Enable deep confirmation of telemetry samples

This patchset preserves for future reference a set of changes that
allows confirmation that metering still works after an upgrade and
that the new upgrade service has successfully been able to get
samples from the newly run processes.

The parent included this functionality but it was considered a bit
too intrusive (see below) and extensive to be included in a normal
javelin run. This code can be mined for future reference if needed.

This change requires that javelin have access to the BASE_RELEASE
and SAVE_DIR environment variables from a grenade run. This requires
a change in grenade.sh. The change makes it possible to get at the
timestamp on the datadump file for any project. That timestamp can
then be used as a fixed point in time against which to make
comparisons with sample timestamps.

Change-Id: Ie0ee0a94449eaf322db1d4440e74d5a8feee2c25

commit_message:
Changed order of calls to register new nodes

Modified agent to checking if node was before registered, based on existence
of nailgun_uid file. If file exist, only put is call, in other case when we
try made post (if call was succes-201 or node exist 409, we call put method)

Change-Id: Id1ef1650cf47c8e5fd7e844362b3fb41afad8fdd
Closes-Bug: #1305017

commit_message:
Remove string concatenation related to volume attachment

Translatable string "on" is a part of string concatenation
and it makes difficult to translate it properly.

Change-Id: Ib2bf65791899a3c69087749d3a5fcf5061568b5d
Closes-Bug: #1382874

commit_message:
Action logs payload collection added

Field 'body' is added to 'action_logs' table with its processing in handler.
'body' contains action log record, its structure is checked with json scheme.

Blueprint: send-anon-usage

commit_message:
Rename parameter 'tag' to 'vlan_tag' in l23network module

In puppet >3.0 word 'tag' is reserved, so it have to be
renamed.

Change-Id: Ie2b62d2b96ee9ca9d4ced15d038979561899e910
Closes-Bug: 1305600

commit_message:
Create buttons in network topology respect quotas

Network topology create (networks, routers, instances) buttons should respect
quotas and the buttons should show feedback if the quota is exceeded.

Change-Id: Ide0e461d598b0d623192a5b2455a0ad3340c5683
Closes-bug: 1367678

commit_message:
Use newer python-ldap paging control API

The API for using the LDAP simple paged results control changed
between python-ldap version 2.3 and 2.4. Our current implementation
fails with an AttributeError when trying to use paging with version
2.4 of python-ldap.

This patch detects the capabilities of the underlying python-ldap
version and uses the newer API in versions of python-ldap that have
removed the older API.

commit_message:
Increase settings for dnsmasq and sysctl

* Make a new variable dhcp_lease_max. It increases the number of
  available leases from 1000 to 1800. It allows to provision nodes on
  scale, when Debian Installer or Anaconda looses IP in the middle of
  install.
* Make a new variable lease_time. It increases the default lease size
  to 120m, up from the default 60m.
* Add cache-size to dnsmasq template. dnsmasq will keep more entries in
  case.
* Increased neighbour table on master node to keep more ARP requests
  that come in parallel once deployment is started. This change also
  removes unneed broadcast traffic. New values are:
  net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh1 = 256
  net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh2 = 1024
  net.ipv4.neigh.default.gc_thresh3 = 2048
* Fix linting

Related-Bug: #1376680
Related-Bug: #1379917
Related-Bug: #1381997
blueprint 100-nodes-support
DocImpact

Change-Id: I4da8070143e401f7a9246e72eda35e601b8c6386

Greg,   Ok the issue with my.cnf is as follows.  /mnt/state is not mounted until runtime as thus I cannot copy cnf files into /mnt/state/etc/mysql until runtime as the mount will overwrite these files later.   /etc/mysql is setup as  soft link  to /mnt/state/etc/mysql by the mysql+mariadb elements at install time.  I don't see a reason for /etc/mysql to exist on /mnt/state at all think the solution to this is just put all conf files etc into /etc/mysql, not into /mnt/state/etc/mysql at all.  (they should be all re-generated by os-refresh-config..I don't a reason why there would be persistent state info there)  Are you agreed with this approach?  If so I'll push up (maybe another fix) to do that."}, {'account_id': 1872, 'date': '2014-05-27 09:45:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Ok that approach won't work either. (though I think /mnt/state/mysql/etc should go for other reasons)   The problem is that cluster.cnf must be a template/must be parsed by os-refresh-config it depends on mysql.nodes and mysql.cluster-name. So this parsing has to be done at runtime. commit_message:
Use Percona Packages for Ubuntu and Debian

Adjust the install of Percona XtraDB Cluster to use Percona Packages
instead of a Percona tarball for Ubuntu and Debian.

This pulls the packages in from the Ubuntu repository. The minimum requirement
for the Percona packages is trusty.

This element currently will not work on Fedora and checks for it but Fedora
uses the Mariadb element to provide a MySQL HA solution instead.

Change-Id: Ie13bf0f7a972ed7f69623c9a661065b46441c3e9

commit_message:
HTTP requests monitoring middleware added

New wsgi middleware was added to middleware stack of main webpy
application. The middleware is a class which implements logic for
collecting info from requests and responses, forming appropriate data
structure and dumps it to db for further usage.

Change-Id: If420f3141eb5a357f010f6ef0b4def0e5a7874bd
Implements: blueprint send-anon-usage

subject: Add host_uuid to libvirtd.conf
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 6926, 'name': 'Bogdan Dobrelya', 'email': 'bdobreli@redhat.com', 'username': 'bogdando'}, {'_account_id': 8786, 'name': 'Vladimir Kuklin', 'email': 'aglarendil@gmail.com', 'username': 'aglarendil'}, {'_account_id': 8971, 'name': 'Fuel CI', 'username': 'fuel-ci', 'inactive': True, 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 9387, 'name': 'Aleksandr Didenko', 'email': 'adidenko@mirantis.com', 'username': 'AD'}, {'_account_id': 11090, 'name': 'Sergii Golovatiuk', 'email': 'sgolovat@redhat.com', 'username': 'holser'}, {'_account_id': 11827, 'name': 'Stanislaw Bogatkin', 'email': 'regs+ubuntu.com@sbog.ru', 'username': 'sbogatkin'}, {'_account_id': 13343, 'name': 'Stanislav Makar', 'email': 'stas.makar@gmail.com', 'username': 'smakar'}, {'_account_id': 13344, 'name': 'Oleksiy Molchanov', 'email': 'omolchanov@mirantis.com', 'username': 'cvieri.lviv'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-15 13:12:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-15 13:12:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/40/128640/1/check/noop/81f851b : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 9387, 'date': '2014-10-15 13:37:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11827, 'date': '2014-10-15 13:49:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Alex, it will not work.
Puppet facter just parses the output of dmidecode and problem is that this UUID is not unique - it depends from hardware. Seems that it right to generate unique UUID and create some top-level fact with it. In other way we cannot guarantee than that UUID will be unique.

But generate uuid in openstack::compute isn't right, cause it breaks idempotency."}, {'account_id': 9387, 'date': '2014-10-15 13:59:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yeah, in this case we need a custom fact that will:
- set value to $::uuid fact if it exists
- if $::uuid does not exist, it should generate a random uuid and store it somewhere on the system
- if $::uuid does not exist and there is a previously stored value, use that stored value in order to provide idempotency.
Something like that.'}, {'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-15 14:36:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Gentlemen,

I agree that it wont work with master and I should redo it. 

Stanislaw, why does it break idempotency? I am using augeas with onlyif.

Aleksandr, I recommend to create only new fact called something like 'uuid_2' that will generate new uuid. No need to store this value, because we can use onlyif with augeas.

Does it make sense?"}, {'account_id': 9387, 'date': '2014-10-15 14:43:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Agreed, it makes sense since we only need this for a single config file. But let's give that fact some meaningful name, like 'random_uuid' (since it will always provide random result)."}, {'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-15 14:45:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Great, fine by me.'}, {'account_id': 11827, 'date': '2014-10-15 14:52:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Oleksiy, ok, onlyif seems to be works.
But we need to rework this slightly any way.'}, {'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-15 15:04:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Stas, does it mean that you are happy with our latest comments with new fact?'}, {'account_id': 11827, 'date': '2014-10-15 15:16:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Oleksiy, yep.'}, {'account_id': 11090, 'date': '2014-10-15 16:50:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Firstly, I believe this should go to 

https://github.com/stackforge/puppet-nova/blob/master/manifests/migration/libvirt.pp

Also, there should be a more complex logic

Usually, libvirt's uuid is the same with UUID from
dmidecode -s system-uuid

There are some known vendor's like SuperMicro and Tyan where they have the same ID for all series. It can be zero or just number which is identical to all boards in series. 

Getting number from
cat /proc/sys/kernel/random/uuid
fixes the problem though your augeas lense should also verify
00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000
It's known Tyan problem

Getting numbers from
cat /proc/sys/kernel/random/uuid
creates the potential problem with idempotancy, where you have a new value on every puppet run.

cat /proc/sys/kernel/random/boot_id
behaves better as you have the same number until you reboot the hardware.

Though I belive the best value is
cat /var/lib/dbus/machine-id
as it keeps the same even after reboot."}, {'account_id': 9387, 'date': '2014-10-16 08:40:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Actually, one-time randomly generated uuid is OK for us, because we use onlyif in augeas resource, which guarantees we will not try to override existing host_uuid in libvirtd.conf (= idempotency).

So in this case we don't actually need a new fact, we can use generate("/bin/cat", "/proc/sys/kernel/random/uuid") or generate('/bin/sh', '-c', "uuidgen").

It will be fine even in case of puppet-master + agent scheme as long as we have "onlyif" in augeas resource.'}, {'account_id': 11090, 'date': '2014-10-16 09:01:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sasha, I am more concerned about host_uuid size == 0, It doesn't fix when you have 00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000  (Tyan problem). Also, we may create a fact from /var/lib/dbus/machine-id which will be handy for operation."}, {'account_id': 9387, 'date': '2014-10-16 09:13:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-16 09:14:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sergii, host_uid size == 0 means that the string size is equal to zero.

So I agree with Aleksandr's last comment, and recommend to keep current approach. Fact will be used only in one place and only once, and it will increase our facts collection."}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2014-10-16 11:00:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

But '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000' string has non zero size, please address that case as well"}, {'account_id': 9387, 'date': '2014-10-16 11:40:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

In libvritd.conf shipped with out packages we have host_uuid = "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000" in comment section. So during deploy there is no way it can appear in the config so match+size should work just fine.'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2014-10-16 13:32:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11827, 'date': '2014-10-16 14:41:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 13343, 'date': '2014-10-20 09:31:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 11090, 'date': '2014-10-20 09:39:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 11:56:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 8786, 'date': '2014-10-20 11:56:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 11:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+2

Build succeeded (gate pipeline).

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/40/128640/1/gate/noop/746fba1 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 11:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Change has been successfully merged into the git repository.'}]

commit_message:
Nailgun object interface for ActionLog added

Single and collection objects for ActionLog entity added to nailgun
objects system. It needed for further utilization by logic which sends
this data to collector service.

JSONSchema for aforementioned entity defined.

Unit tests updated.

Change-Id: Icf40bdb84785f64e9e43025d69482451c8de6ea4
Implements: blueprint send-anon-usage

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

    great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Do not match subnets if no networks defined

Server will now skip looking for subnets on shared networks
if the server doesn't have any networks defined. Added tests
to verify existing behavior as well as to guard regression.

Change-Id: I81bc3bf753843f521ccb8a96b9a40a6f82ca8d92
Closes-Bug: #1380846

[{'created': '2014-09-10 18:07:10.000000000', 'message': "WIP Xen: Attempt to find and cleanup orphaned SR on delete

Before some patches merged to better handle failures to boot an instance
from a volume it was possible to have an attached volume with an SR and
plugged PBD but no VM.  And the destroy method in xenapi short circuits
if no VM is present because everything is looked up from there in order
to be cleaned up.

This adds a check to see if a volume is supposed to be attached during
destroy if no VM is present and attempts to look it up via the SR uuid
and clean it up.

I would like to say that this patch is unnecessary, as it's sort of
hackish, but it's possible that some deployments have instances in this
state and this will allow them to cleanup without manually running
commands on the hypervisor.

Soliciting feedback while tests are being written.

commit_message:
Xen: Attempt to find and cleanup orphaned SR during delete

Before some patches merged to better handle failures to boot an instance
from a volume it was possible to have an attached volume with an SR and
plugged PBD but no VM.  And the destroy method in xenapi short circuits
if no VM is present because everything is looked up from there in order
to be cleaned up.

This adds a check to see if a volume is supposed to be attached during
destroy if no VM is present and attempts to look it up via the SR uuid
and clean it up.

I would like to say that this patch is unnecessary, as it's sort of
hackish, but it's possible that some deployments have instances in this
state and this will allow them to cleanup without manually running
commands on the hypervisor.

Closes-bug: #1367918
Change-Id: I7745af7e22164a96af800ae796bda077e49bf291

commit_message:
Increase test rate limit to avoid rate limit error

The current rate limit is 200 requests per minute. I'm getting
consistent tox failures as the machine is exceeding this rate. The fix
impacts only test code and adjusts the limit and a test that has a
hard-coded reference to the old limit. Why 500 you may ask? Because
600 worked and 450 failed consistently with the rate limit error.

In addition, the change addresses the fact that some test
configuration values are duplicated in the test; the change makes the
test reference the configuration value.

Change-Id: I4bb290d8de6253d65b7877c743bb288ee2bce536
Closes-Bug: #1376689
Closes-Bug: #1378932

commit_message:
Pass block device info in pre_live_migration

In case of block migration, this adds block device information to the
disk information handled by pre_live_migration, so that at least in the
case of libvirt no spurious files are created corresponding to volumes.

Co-Authored-By: florent.flament@cloudwatt.com
Change-Id: I373001e0ef0e4fe4ab900d399756f27101cfe5c8
Closes-Bug: 1376586

commit_message:
Add Quota roll back for deallocate fix ip in nova-network

in nova-network, deallocate_fixed_ip function reserve quota
first then do deallocate operations if any operation failed,
the quota reserve operation need to be rollback.

Change-Id: If57d2b8a24b2f6ed3d90a1357e89782194df013c
Closes-Bug: #1284930

commit_message:
Allow source-repositories to be disabled completely

In our official image builds we are only allowed to use resources
that are "blessed" by the build system.  This means that external
things like git repos and tar files are not allowed.  Currently,
even in offline mode source-repositories expects those things to
be available in the cache, so we need a way to disable it entirely.

This change adds an environment variable NO_SOURCE_REPOSITORIES
that does so.  It can be set in an environment.d script so elements
that might rely on a source repository will know it's not available.
The 02-lsb script in redhat-common is one such example and is
updated to handle this case.

Change-Id: I0de63bee6ad79733d6711478c707a9b41593e85f

commit_message:
Put a cap on our cyclomatic complexity

flake8 has support for cyclomatic complexity (Mccabe) currently our
worst offender has a complexity of 18 (25 is considered very bad). So
set our max-complexity to 20 so we keep our complexity in a great shape.

https://github.com/flintwork/mccabe

Change-Id: I682f3c192e46bd50236b10a337f0b129c4b02eb8

commit_message:
Add Parallels Cloud Server support into virt/libvirt driver

This specification proposes to implement modification in
virt/libvirt driver to support Parallels Cloud Server
(http://www.parallels.com/products/pcs/).

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-08 10:54:43.000000000', 'message': "Avoid overwritting of hooks

Until now there was a possibility for two elements to install hooks
with the same name, so one of them was overwritten. Change logic to
copy the hooks and fail in case one with the same name exists.

Also, instead of copy the whole element into the temporary hook dir,

commit_message:
Avoid overwritting of hooks

Until now there was a possibility for two elements to install hooks
with the same name, so one of them was overwritten. Change logic to
copy the hooks and fail in case one with the same name exists.

Change-Id: Ic2c46835b27c9319f7a889ffd0ccf3f5ccc1f0cd
Closes-Bug: 1251952

Change-Id: I144c8993fe040169f440bd4f7a428fdbe3d745cf
"}, {'created': '2014-07-22 18:14:49.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Use dracut for building ramdisks

Super rough WIP demonstrating what has to be done to build our
deploy ramdisks with dracut.  In theory should pass the f20
overcloud job, almost certainly won't work on Ubuntu right now
due to my use of Fedora package names.

There have also been some changes merged recently to support DHCP
in our ramdisks, which I believe dracut will already handle, but we
will need to verify that it continues working.

Change-Id: I144c8993fe040169f440bd4f7a428fdbe3d745cf
"}, {'created': '2014-08-20 23:26:34.000000000', 'message': "Enable dracut deploy ramdisks

Allow the use of dracut for building deploy ramdisks.  This
factors out the common functionality between this new element
and the existing ramdisk element so they can coexist.

The element builds dracut from source on Ubuntu because the
Ubuntu dracut package is broken and very old, so it can't be
installed properly and causes a number of other issues that
are fixed by using a newer version of Dracut.

This initial version should work in virtualized environments.
Further validation of its suitability for real baremetal
deployments will need to be done in the future, but this should
be sufficient to enable that work.

Regarding Dracut specifically, in order to limit the changes
needed in the existing scripts this element continues to use a
cut down version of the /init script that we were building for the
existing ramdisk.  However, instead of running it as pid 0 it is
run as a Dracut pre-mount hook.  This allows Dracut to set up all
of the hardware and system bits, while falling early enough in the
Dracut sequence to complete the deployment before Dracut would try
to boot off the hard disk.

Change-Id: I144c8993fe040169f440bd4f7a428fdbe3d745cf

commit_message:
Enable dracut deploy ramdisks

The element builds dracut from source on Ubuntu because the
Ubuntu dracut package is broken and very old, so it can't be
installed properly and causes a number of other issues that
are fixed by using a newer version of Dracut.

This initial version should work in virtualized environments.
Further validation of its suitability for real baremetal
deployments will need to be done in the future, but this should
be sufficient to enable that work.

Regarding Dracut specifically, in order to limit the changes
needed in the existing scripts this element continues to use a
cut down version of the /init script that we were building for the
existing ramdisk.  However, instead of running it as pid 0 it is
run as a Dracut pre-mount hook.  This allows Dracut to set up all
of the hardware and system bits, while falling early enough in the
Dracut sequence to complete the deployment before Dracut would try
to boot off the hard disk.

bp tripleo-juno-dracut-ramdisks
Change-Id: I144c8993fe040169f440bd4f7a428fdbe3d745cf

commit_message:
Fixed bug launchpad #1382809 to manage token expired

Currenntly Freezer handle token refresh when uploading data segments,
but there's a bug in the file backup.py in the lines ~130 and ~178.
The client object called to upload the tar meta data and the
swift manifest, can  be expired as it is initialized before
the segments upload process.

launchpad: https://bugs.launchpad.net/freezer/+bug/1382809

Change-Id: I88c9d922c51a43c1722268d4dbed77e594e089aa

(1 comment)

I am expecting to get long description about all commands not only deployment.create. 

Plus I think that forcing people to use "-h" to get this description is bad. At least in case of rally <group>. 



E.g.


  boris@ubuntu:~$ rally task
  usage: rally task [-h]
                    
  {abort,delete,detailed,list,plot2html,results,sla_check,start,status,validate}
                  ...
  rally task: error: too few arguments

and 


  boris@ubuntu:~$ rally task -h
  usage: rally task [-h]
                  {abort,delete,detailed,list,plot2html,results,sla_check,start,status,validate}
                  ...

  Task management.

    Set of commands that allow you to manage benchmarking tasks and results.

  Commands:
    abort       Abort started benchmarking task.
    delete      Delete task and it's results.
    detailed    Display results table.
    list        List all tasks, started and finished.
    plot2html   Generate html report from task results.
    results     Diplay raw task results.
    sla_check   Display SLA check results table.
    start       Start benchmark task.
    status      Display current status of task.
    validate    Validate a task configuration file.

  positional arguments:
    {abort,delete,detailed,list,plot2html,results,sla_check,start,status,validate}

  optional arguments:
    -h, --help            show this help message and exit



By the way I would prefer to remove position arguments. Remove oslo excutils

Remove the openstack/common/excutils.py file as it's not specified
in openstack-common.conf and is now deprecated (removed actually)
in oslo-incubator in favor of oslo.utils.

commit_message:
Put a cap on our cyclomatic complexity

flake8 has support for cyclomatic complexity (Mccabe) currently our
worst offender has a complexity of 28 (25 is considered very bad). So
set our max-complexity to 29 so we at least don't make things any worse.

This is the first step in bringing this number down to 20 or so.

https://github.com/flintwork/mccabe

Change-Id: Ic90093ab80d9d3e27c257ea1a5cc393e09ebc7ee

commit_message:
Logging audit for guestagent/redis

Adjust logging to conform to logging standards.
Cleaned up a few messages that were unclear and changed some
LOG.info messages to LOG.debug

Change-Id: I3570dddf0ba7c576b4cf9cb6affa55335fd23ac7
Partial-Bug: #1324206

commit_message:
Add rpm/deb specs for python-tasklib package

- add python-tasklib spec
- add python-tasklib to requirements-rpm
- add python-tasklib to bootstrap image

Partially implements blueprint packages-for-fuel-tacklib

Change-Id: Ic808a2bce79c2d912b25cc87ac2bed8bdb005bc6

commit_message:
The version of sphinx being brought in is broken

The global requirements repo has blocked 1.3b1, so
in order for pylockfile builds to stop failing so
should we. In the future we should investigate why
the requirements aren't syncing for this repo.

Change-Id: I8a999cc044d3687cc410b56b1db490e38b9b9a50

commit_message:
Passthrough{Specific} and allNodesConfig for BlockStorage nodes

Purpose of this change is to allow passthrough of *specific values*
for *same key* in particular to BlockStorage nodes. Same
behaviour is already implemented for controllers and computes.

Change-Id: I7074a8f7d406adaa56e55013b10bd520fcacfcf6

commit_message:
Migrate from map-services to svc-map

This patch migrates the collectl element from map-services to
svc-map by adding the -a option to os-svc-enable and adding a
svc-map file.

Change-Id: I13ad6055ebfe46d25dc1bf598eaabafb6ac6bb5a

commit_message:
Update node-validate error messages

Upon executing node-validate upon a node in Ironic, the
error message/reason is provided without any clear instruction
as to where the missing parameters are supposed to be defined.

This fix proposes to update the error messages to specify where
the information is missing.

Change-Id: I66e84ac3341882ae72796cc9536f20773142267f
Closes-Bug: #1379911

commit_message:
Scale images in the upstream-training guide

Most images that exceeded the slide area were too wide.  These were
fixed by adding a 'max-width: 100%' CSS rule.  Release cycle images in
the 01-release-cycle.rst presentation were too tall because the
two-column layout was not preserved when the presentation was converted
from the ODP source document.  This change restores the two-column
layout.  The images now scale appropriately across a variety of
operating systems and browsers.  The print.css changes were tested with
the print rendering engines of Firefox and Chrome.

Change-Id: Ic5d4c3c959d37fda0d57009f282be1238388cc59
